ies/ |title= Top 10 Beavis And Butthead Classic Rock Song Commentaries |last= Wardlaw |first= Matt |accessdate= 20 December 2011 |publisher= Ultimate Classic Rock|ref={{SfnRef|Wardlaw}}}}\n* {{cite news |url= http://www.aftonbladet.se/nojesbladet/musik/rockbjornen/article13549648.ab |title= B\u00e4sta liveakt h\u00e5rdrock: Iron Maiden |last= Wejbro |first= Sandra |date= 31 August 2011 |accessdate= 1 September 2011 |language= Swedish |newspaper= [[Aftonbladet]]|ref={{SfnRef|Wejbro|2011}}}}\n* {{cite news |url= http://www.dailymail.co.uk/home/moslive/article-1022475/He-aint-heavy-hes-captain----Iron-Maiden-rocker.html |title= He ain't heavy he's your captain |date= 6 June 2008 |accessdate= 23 June 2011 |location=London |work=[[Daily Mail]] |first=Jon |last=Wilde|ref={{SfnRef|Wilde|2008}}}}{{deprecated inline|certain=yes|date=January 2020}}\n* {{cite web|last= Williams |first= Scott|title= Iron Maiden Reading 2005 Review|date= 31 August 2005|url= http://www.efestivals.co.uk/festivals/reading/2005/review-ironmaiden.shtml|publisher=EFestivals.com|accessdate =11 October 2006|ref={{SfnRef|Williams|2005}}}}\n* {{cite web |url= http://yle.fi/vintti/yle.fi/pop/emman-historia.html |title= Emman historia |accessdate= 4 September 2011 |language= Finnish |publisher= [[YLE]]|ref={{SfnRef|YLE}}}}\n* {{cite journal |title= Raising Hell |journal= [[Kerrang!|Kerrang! Legends]] |volume= 112 |first= Simon |last= Young |issue= 2 |page= 32|ref={{SfnRef|Young(1)}}|bibcode= 2006S&T...112f..54K |year= 2006 }}\n* {{cite journal |title= Iron Men |journal= [[Kerrang!|Kerrang! Legends]] |first= Simon |last= Young |issue= 2 |pages= 90\u201393 |ref={{SfnRef|Young(2)}}}}\n* {{cite journal |script-title=ja:YOSHIKI\u518d\u3073\uff01 |journal= Headbang |first= Chizuka |last= Kakizawa |volume= 9 |pages= 40\u201349 |date= 17 January 2016 |ref={{SfnRef|Kakizawa}}}}\n* {{cite journal |title= Guitar Heroes: hide |journal= Rock 'n' Roll |first= Yusuke |last= Kato |volume= 93 |date= 27 January 1995 |ref={{SfnRef|Kato}}}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|last=Bushell|first=Gary|title=Iron Maiden: Running Free|publisher=Hal Leonard Corp|year=1985|isbn=978-0-946-39184-4|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/ironmaidenrunnin00bush}}\n*{{cite book|last=Daniels|first=Neil|title=Iron Maiden - Updated Edition: The Ultimate Illustrated History of the Beast |publisher=Voyageur Press|year=2016|isbn=978-0-760-35167-3}}\n*{{cite book|last=Di'Anno|first=Paul|title=The Beast: Singing With Iron Maiden\u2015The Drugs, the Groupies . . . the Whole Story|publisher=John Blake|year=2010|isbn=978-1-844-54884-2}}\n*{{cite book|last=Dickinson|first=Bruce|title=What Does This Button Do?: An Autobiography|publisher=Dey Street Books|year=2017|isbn=978-0-062-46813-0}} \n*{{cite book|last=Halfin|first=Ross|title=Iron Maiden|publisher=Vision On|year=2008|isbn=978-1-846-09445-3}} \n*{{cite book|last=McMurtrie|first=John|title=Iron Maiden: On Board Flight 666|publisher=Orion Publishing|year=2013|isbn=978-1-409-14136-5}} \n*{{cite book|last=Popoff|first=Martin|title=2 Minutes to Midnight: An Iron Maiden Day-by-Day|publisher=Backbeat Books|year=2013|isbn=978-1-617-13565-1}}\n*{{cite book|last=Prato|first=Greg|title=Iron Maiden: '80 '81|publisher=self-published|year=2015|isbn=978-1-508-53638-3}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category multi|Iron Maiden (band)|Ed Force One}}\n* {{Official website|www.ironmaiden.com}}\n\n{{Iron Maiden}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Iron Maiden (band)| ]]\n[[Category:1975 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Brit Award winners]]\n[[Category:Capitol Records artists]]\n[[Category:EMI Records artists]]\n[[Category:English heavy metal musical groups]]\n[[Category:Epic Records artists]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Harvest Records artists]]\n[[Category:Ivor Novello Award winners]]\n[[Category:Kerrang! Awards winners]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1975]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from London]]\n[[Category:New Wave of British Heavy Metal musical groups]]\n[[Category:Parlophone artists]]\n[[Category:Universal Music Group artists]]\n[[Category:Warner Music Sweden artists]]\n", "name_user": "RALFFPL", "label": "safe", "comment": "grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iron_Maiden"}
{"title_page": "Hume Highway", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2011}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=April 2011}}\n{{Infobox Australian road\n| type         = Freeway \n| road_name    = Hume Highway\n| road_name2   = Hume Freeway / Hume Motorway\n| state        = nsw\n| state2       = vic\n| image        =\n| caption      = \n| length       = 840\n| length_ref   = <ref name=\"Google Maps 1\"/><ref name=\"Google Maps 2\"/><ref name=\"Google Maps 3\"/><ref name=\"Google Maps 4\"/>\n| direction_a  = NE\n| direction_b  = SW\n| end_a        = {{plainlist|\n*{{AUshield|NSW|A22}} [[Great Western Highway]] <small>(A22)</small>\n*<small>{{NSWcity|Summer Hill}}, [[Sydney]]</small>\n}}\n| end_b        = {{plainlist|\n*{{AUshield|VIC|M80}} [[M80 Ring Road, Melbourne|Western Ring Road]] <small>(M80)</small>\n*<small>[[Campbellfield, Victoria|Campbellfield]], [[Melbourne]]</small>\n}}\n| est          = 1817\n| through      = {{NSWcity|Liverpool|Campbelltown|Berrima|Marulan|Goulburn|Yass|Gundagai|Tarcutta|Holbrook|Albury}}, [[Albury-Wodonga]], [[Wangaratta]], [[Benalla]], [[Seymour, Victoria|Seymour]], [[Craigieburn, Victoria|Craigieburn]]\n| route        = {{plainlist|\n*{{AUshield|NSW|A22}} \n*<small>({{NSWcity|Summer Hill}} \u2013 {{NSWcity|Liverpool}})</small>\n*{{AUshield|NSW|A28}}\n*<small>({{NSWcity|Liverpool}} \u2013 {{NSWcity|Prestons}})</small>\n*{{AUshield|NSW|M31}}\n*<small>({{NSWcity|Prestons}} \u2013 NSW/Vic. Border)</small>\n*** Either {{AUshield|VIC|M31}} or {{AUshield|N|M31}}\n*<small>(NSW/Vic. Border \u2013 [[Campbellfield, Victoria|Campbellfield]])</small>\n}}\n| former       = see [[Hume Highway#Former route allocations|Former route allocations]]\n| exits        = {{plainlist|\n* {{AUshield|NSW|A3}} [[A3 (Sydney)|Centenary Drive / Roberts Rd]] <small>(A3)</small>\n* {{AUshield|NSW|A6}} [[A6 (Sydney)|Stacey Street]] <small>(A6)</small>\n* {{AUshield|NSW|A28}} [[Cumberland Highway]] <small>(A28)</small>\n* {{AUshield|NSW|A34}} Macquarie Street, [[Liverpool, New South Wales|Liverpool]] <small>(A34)</small>\n* {{AUshield|T|12}} [[Camden Valley Way]]\n* {{AUshield|NSW|M5}} [[M5 South Western Motorway|South Western Motorway]] <small>(M5)</small>\n* {{AUshield|NSW|M7}} [[Westlink M7|WestLink]] <small>(M7)</small>\n* {{AUshield|NSW|A9|}} {{AUshield|NSW|B69|}} [[Metroad 9|Narellan Road]] <small>(A9)</small>\n* {{AUshield|NSW|B88}} [[Picton Road]] <small>(B88)</small>\n* {{AUshield|NSW|B73}} [[Old Hume Highway]]<small>(B73)</small>\n* {{AUshield|NSW|A48}} [[Illawarra Highway]] <small>(A48)</small>\n* {{AUshield|NSW|M23}} [[Federal Highway (Australia)|Federal Highway]] <small>(M23)</small>\n* {{AUshield|NSW|A25}} [[Barton Highway]] <small>(A25)</small>\n* {{AUshield|NSW|A20}} [[Sturt Highway]] <small>(A20)</small>\n* {{AUshield|NSW|A41}} [[Olympic Highway]] <small>(A41)</small>\n* {{AUshield|NSW|B58}} [[Riverina Highway]] <small>(B58)</small>\n* {{AUshield|VIC|B400}} [[Murray Valley Highway]] <small>(B400)</small>\n* {{AUshield|VIC|A300|VIC|B300}} [[Midland Highway (Victoria)|Midland Highway]] <small>(A300/B300)</small>\n* {{AUshield|VIC|M39}} [[Goulburn Valley Freeway]] <small>(M39)</small>\n* {{AUshield|S|55}} [[Sydney Road, Melbourne|Sydney Road]] <small>(State Route 55)</small>\n}}\n| location     = Location Hume Hwy.svg\n}}\n\nThe '''Hume Highway''', inclusive of the sections now known as the '''Hume Freeway''' and '''Hume Motorway''', is one of Australia's major inter-city [[National Highway (Australia)|national highway]]s, running for {{convert|840|km|mi}} between [[Melbourne]] in the southwest and [[Sydney]] in the northeast.<ref name=\"Google Maps 1\"/><ref name=\"Google Maps 2\"/><ref name=\"Google Maps 3\"/><ref name=\"Google Maps 4\"/><ref>{{Cite report |first1=Emma|last1=Dixon|first2=Cassandra|last2= Hay|editor=Reviewed and approved by Hugh Swinbourne|date=6 September 2009|title=Hume Highway Holbrook Bypass Environmental Assessment |url=http://www.rta.nsw.gov.au/roadprojects/projects/south_western_region/hume_hway_dup/holbrook_bypass/public_information.html |publisher=NSW Roads and Traffic Authority |page=1 |chapter=Chapter 1. Introduction |chapterurl=http://www.rta.nsw.gov.au/roadprojects/projects/south_western_region/hume_hway_dup/holbrook_bypass/documents/05_chapter_1_introduction.pdf |accessdate=2013-02-09|quote=The total length of the Hume Highway is 807 kilometres from Sydney to Melbourne}}</ref> Upgrading of the route from Sydney's outskirts to Melbourne's outskirts to [[dual carriageway]] was completed on 7 August 2013.<ref name=holbrook>https://au.prime7.yahoo.com/v1/news/a/-/local/18411793/four-lanes-at-last-as-bypass-opens-video/</ref>\n\nFrom north to south, the road is called the Hume Highway in metropolitan Sydney, the Hume Motorway between the suburbs of Edmondson Park and [[Prestons, New South Wales|Prestons]] and [[Berrima, New South Wales|Berrima]], the Hume Highway elsewhere in [[New South Wales]] and the Hume Freeway in [[Victoria, Australia|Victoria]]. It is part of the [[National Highway (Australia)|Auslink National Network]] and is a vital link for road freight to transport goods to and from the two cities as well as serving [[Albury-Wodonga]] and [[Canberra]].\n\nThe main alternative route between Sydney and Melbourne is the [[Princes Highway]]/[[Princes Freeway]]/[[Southern Freeway|Princes Motorway]] route (A1/M1) which follows the coast for most of its length. Other inland alternate routes include the [[Olympic Highway]] route (A41) between [[Albury]] and Sydney via [[Wagga Wagga]], [[Cowra]] and [[Bathurst, New South Wales|Bathurst]], and also the [[Federal Highway (Australia)|Federal Highway]] / [[Monaro Highway]] route (M23/A23/B23) via Canberra which links with the Hume Highway near [[Goulburn]] and the Princes Highway in East Gippsland.\n\nIn New South Wales during 2013, the [[National Highway (Australia)|National Highway]] shield, National Highway 31, was replaced with a standard alphanumeric route number, the M31 south of Prestons (along with the A22 east of Liverpool into the Sydney CBD and the A28 for a short length through Liverpool). This re-numbering for the first time in over 20 years created one continuously signed route along the Hume Highway, having already been signed the M31 in Victoria during the 1990s. During 2013, the route between Berrima and Prestons was also renamed the Hume Motorway.<ref name=\"RMS Road Name Changes\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rms.nsw.gov.au/documents/projects/key-build-programs/alpha-numeric/nsw-factsheet.pdf |format=PDF |title=Road number and name changes in NSW |page=3 |work=[[Roads and Maritime Services]] |publisher=Government of New South Wales |access-date=26 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160325194425/http://www.rms.nsw.gov.au/documents/projects/key-build-programs/alpha-numeric/nsw-factsheet.pdf |archive-date=25 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe coast of New South Wales from the [[Queensland]] border to the Victorian border is separated from the inland by an [[escarpment]], forming the eastern edge of the [[Great Dividing Range]]. There are few easy routes up this escarpment. To climb from the coast to the tablelands the Hume Highway uses the [[Bargo, New South Wales|Bargo Ramp]], a geological feature which provides one of the few easy crossings of the escarpment.\n\nIn the first twenty years of European settlement at Sydney (established 1788), exploration southwest of Sydney was slow. This area was heavily wooded at the time, especially the \"[[Bargo, New South Wales|Bargo brush]]\", which was regarded as almost impenetrable. In 1798 explorers (Wilson, Price, Hacking, and Collins) reached the [[Moss Vale, New South Wales|Moss Vale]] and [[Marulan, New South Wales|Marulan]] districts, but this was not followed up. Any settlement would have to await the construction of an adequate access track, which would have been beyond the colony's resources at the time, and would have served little purpose as a source of supplies for Sydney, due to the time taken to reach Sydney. In 1804, [[Charles Throsby]] penetrated through the Bargo brush to the country on the tablelands near Moss Vale and [[Sutton Forest, New South Wales|Sutton Forest]]. On another expedition in 1818, he reached Lake Bathurst and the [[Goulburn|\"Goulburn Plains\"]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.abs.gov.au/Ausstats/abs@.nsf/0/4e782ee652d0db0aca2569de001fb2dd?OpenDocument |title=Official Year Book of the Commonwealth of Australia 1931 |publisher=Australian Bureau of Statistics www.abs.gov.au |accessdate=2006-04-28}}</ref> Many of the early explorers would most likely have used aboriginal guides, but they do not appear to have given them credit.{{citation needed|date=May 2012}}\n\nAfter Charles Throsby's 1818 journey towards present day Goulburn, followed by Hamilton Hume and William Hovell's [[Hume and Hovell expedition|overland journey]] from Appin (near Campbelltown) to Port Phillip and return in 1824, development of the Southern Tablelands for agriculture was rapid. The present route of the Hume Highway is much the same as that used by the pioneers.\n[[File:Tahmoor Gorge.jpg|thumb|290x290px|Tahmoor Gorge in its Pristine Best.]]\nThe route taken by the Hume Highway to climb from the coast to the Southern Tablelands and across the Great Divide is situated between the parallel river gorge systems of the [[Wollondilly River|Wollondilly]] and [[Shoalhaven River|Shoalhaven]] rivers. This country consists generally of a gently sloping plateau which is deeply dissected by the [[Nepean River]] and its tributaries. The route of the Highway, by using four high-level bridges to cross these gorges, avoids the Razorback Range, and has minimal [[Earthworks (engineering)|earthworks]]. The climb from the western side of the Nepean River at [[Menangle, New South Wales|Menangle]] up to [[Mittagong]] is fairly sustained, a fact that is hard to appreciate at high speed on the modern freeway. The highway climbs non-stop over a distance of {{convert|16|km}} from the [[Pheasants Nest, New South Wales|Pheasants Nest]] bridge over the Nepean River to [[Yerrinbool, New South Wales|Yerrinbool]], before dropping slightly before the final climb to reach the tablelands at [[Aylmerton, New South Wales|Aylmerton]], a climb of over {{convert|430|m}} in {{convert|25|km}}.<ref>{{google maps|url=https://www.google.com.au/maps/dir/-34.2372996,150.6623305/-34.4072059,150.5048609/@-34.3218533,150.5137292,12z/data=!3m1!4b1!4m2!4m1!3e1?hl=en|title=Pheasants Nest Bridge to Aylmerton |accessdate=31 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Early road construction===\nGovernor [[Lachlan Macquarie]] ordered the construction of a road, which became known as the '''Great South Road''' (the basis of the northern end of the Hume Highway) in 1819 from Picton to the Goulburn Plains and he travelled to Goulburn in 1820, but it is unlikely that even a primitive road was finished at that time.\n\n[[File:Sydney Road near Benalla 1914.jpg|thumb|right|A passable section of \"Sydney Road\" in the shire of [[Benalla]], 1914.]]\nThe Great South Road was rebuilt and completely re-routed between [[Yanderra, New South Wales|Yanderra]] and Goulburn by Surveyor-General [[Thomas Mitchell (explorer)|Thomas Mitchell]] in 1833. The ''Main Roads Management Act'' of June 1858 declared the Great Southern Road, from near Sydney through Goulburn and [[Gundagai]] to Albury, as one of the three main roads in the colony. However, its southern reaches were described as only a 'scarcely formed bullock track' as late as 1858. The road was improved in the mid-1860s with some sections near Gundagai \"[[Road surface#Gravel surface|metalled]]\" and all creeks bridged between Adelong Creek (approximately 10 kilometres south of Gundagai and now known as the village of Tumblong) and Albury.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.rta.nsw.gov.au/cgi-bin/index.cgi?action=heritage.show&id=4309569 |title =Hillas Creek Bridge| work = Heritage and conservation register| publisher = Roads and Traffic Authority of New South Wales | year=2004| accessdate=16 March 2008}}</ref>\n\nMitchell's route in New South Wales, except for the bypasses at Mittagong, Berrima and [[Marulan, New South Wales|Marulan]] (dual carriageways were completed in 1986) is still largely followed by the current highway.<ref>Mitchell, T. L., The south eastern portion of Australia showing the routes of the three expeditions and the surveyed territory, Boone, 29 New Bond Street, London, 1838.</ref> Mitchell intended to straighten the route north of Yanderra, but was not granted funding, although his proposed route through [[Pheasants Nest, New South Wales|Pheasants Nest]] has similarities to the freeway route opened in 1980.<ref>{{Cite book| last=Lay | first=Max | title =History of Australian Roads | publisher = [[Australian Road Research Board]] |year=1984 | isbn=0-86910-164-1}}</ref> Mitchell's work on the Great South Road is best preserved at [[Towrang, New South Wales|Towrang]] Creek (10 kilometres north of Goulburn), where his stone arch culvert still stands, although it was superseded in 1965 by a concrete box culvert which in turn was superseded by the current route of the highway when it was duplicated in 1972.\n\nIn contrast in Victoria there was an early and major change to Mitchell's route. Mitchell's original route between Albury and Melbourne went through [[Mitchellstown]] on the [[Goulburn River]] and took a long detour to the West of [[Mount Macedon]].<ref>Road from Jugiong Creek to Port Phillip, 12 Apr 1838, [Sketch book 3 folio 87], Department of Lands Sketch books, [Surveyor General], NRS 13886, New South Wales State Archives.</ref>\n\nIn March 1837 [[Charles Bonney]] blazed a new trail from [[Mitchellstown]] through [[Kilmore, Victoria|Kilmore]] to Melbourne, a route that took a day and a half off the previous journey. The bulk of Bonney's track formed the Sydney Road for the next 139 years.<ref>Williams, Martin, Charles Bonney and the fertile Kilmore Plains, Victorian Historical Journal, Volume 90, No. 1, June 2019, p. 108.</ref>\n\nBonney's new route of the Sydney Road was especially surveyed in 1840.<ref>{{cite web | title=Map shewing the surveyed lands at Port Phillip from the government surveys made in 1840 [cartographic material] | first=John | last=Arrowsmith | date=1 March 1841 | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/12014411?q&versionId=14165711 | accessdate=13 August 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1914 the NSW section of the highway was declared a main road. Until it was named the Hume Highway in 1928 it was known as the \"Great South Road\" in NSW and \"Sydney Road\" in Victoria. It was named after [[Hamilton Hume]], who with [[William Hovell]] were the first Europeans to traverse an overland route between Sydney and Port Phillip, in what later became Victoria.\n\nThe Hume Highway was fully sealed by 1940.\n\n===Timeline of duplication and bypass works===\nDuplication works on the highway began in the 1960s and concluded in 2013.<ref name=holbrook /> The entire route between Sydney and Melbourne is now a dual carriageway, [[limited access highway]].\n\n*1962 - [[Chiltern, Victoria|Chiltern]] to [[Barnawartha, Victoria|Barnawartha]] opened January, 1962. This is referred to as the \u2018Hume By-pass Road\u2019. Although initially opened as a single carriageway, two lane bypass, it was the first rural bypass of a [[Victoria (Australia)|Victorian]] Chiltern town on the Hume Highway and was designed to allow for the future construction of a second carriageway.<ref name=49th>Country Roads Board Victoria. ''Forty-Ninth Annual Report for the Year Ended 30th June, 1962'', Melbourne, Victoria: Government Printer, 1962. p. 7, p. 22</ref>\n*1962 - [[Craigieburn, Victoria|Craigieburn]] \u2018Hume By-pass Road\u2019 opened January, 1962 at a cost of 388,000 Australian Pounds. This dual carriageway bypass over the [[Sydney\u2013Melbourne rail corridor|Sydney to Melbourne railway]] and Craigieburn Road has since been bypassed itself by the M31 Hume Freeway bypass, opened in 2007.<ref name=49th />\n*1965/66 - [[Broadford, Victoria|Broadford]] to [[Tallarook]]. Duplication of 4 miles completed during the financial year.<ref>Country Roads Board Victoria. ''Fifty-third Annual Report for the Year Ended 30th June, 1966'', Melbourne, Victoria: Government Printer, 1967. p. 11</ref>\n*1966 - 1.6&nbsp;km of dual carriageway opened over Bendooley Hill between Mittagong and Berrima (superseded by Berrima bypass in 1989).\n*1966/67 - Craigieburn to [[Kalkallo, Victoria|Kalkallo]]. 4.4 miles of dual carriageways completed during the financial year.<ref name=54th>Country Roads Board Victoria. ''Fifty-Fourth Annual Report: for the year ended 30th June, 1967'', Burwood, Victoria: Brown, Prior, Anderson, 1968. p. 34</ref>\n*1966/67 - Tallarook. 1.4 miles completed south of Tallarook and 1.3 miles completed north of Tallarook during the financial year.<ref name=54th />\n*1967/68 - Kalkallo to [[Beveridge, Victoria|Beveridge]]. 4.1 miles of dual carriageways completed during the financial year.<ref>Country Roads Board Victoria. ''Fifty-Fifth Annual Report: for the year ended 30th June, 1968'', Burwood, Victoria: Brown, Prior, Anderson, 1969</ref>\n*1969/70 - Beveridge. Completion of 11 miles of dual carriageway during the financial year, including a deviation at Beveridge and continuation south to connect with existing dual carriageways north of Craigieburn.<ref>Country Roads Board Victoria. ''Fifty-Seventh Annual Report: for the year ended 30th June, 1970'', Burwood, Victoria: Brown, Prior, Anderson, 1971. p. 3</ref>\n*1970/71 - Tallarook bypass. 4.5 mile bypass of Tallarook opened during the financial year.<ref>Country Roads Board Victoria. ''Fifty-eighth Report: for the year ended 30th June, 1971'', Burwood, Victoria: Brown, Prior, Anderson, 1971. p. 21</ref>\n*1973 - stage 1 of Camden bypass (Macarthur Bridge across Nepean River floodplain) opened.\n*1973 - first section of South Western Expressway (9.8&nbsp;km), later subsumed into the Hume Highway, was opened from Cross Roads to Campbelltown Rd Raby on 26 October.\n*1974 - stage 2 of Camden bypass (new dual carriageway route Narellan Rd-Macarthur Bridge) opened.\n*1974 - second section of South Western Expressway (5.8&nbsp;km), also later subsumed into the Hume Highway, was opened from Campbelltown Rd Raby to Narellan Rd Macarthur on 16 December.\n*1976 - [[Wallan, Victoria|Wallan]] to Broadford section opened 3 May 1976, by the [[Premier of Victoria]], the Hon R J Hamer, ED, MP. At that time it was the longest section of freeway ever opened at one time in Victoria (34&nbsp;km) and was the 'single biggest construction project carried out by the [[Country Roads Board|CRB]] since its inception in 1913'.<ref>Country Roads Board Victoria. ''Sixty-Third Annual Report: for the year ended 30th June, 1976'', Burwood, Victoria: Brown, Prior, Anderson, 1976. p. 10</ref>\n*1977 - new route of Hume Highway, built to freeway standard, opened from Yanderra to Aylmerton (13.5&nbsp;km) on 24 May.\n*1979 - [[Violet Town]] to [[Baddaginnie, Victoria|Baddaginnie]]. 10&nbsp;km of dual carriageways opened early 1979 at a cost of A$5.1m.<ref name=66th>Country Roads Board Victoria. ''66th Annual Report. 1978-1979'', Burwood, Victoria: Brown, Prior, Anderson, 1979. p. 19</ref>\n*1979 - [[Avenel, Victoria|Avenel]] to Tubbs Hill, near [[Longwood, Victoria|Longwood]]. 14.5&nbsp;km duplication opened 19 December 1979, by the Minister for Transport, the Hon Robert Maclellan MLA, at a cost of A$6.5m.<ref name=66th />\n*1980 - Violet Town bypass. 12&nbsp;km from Wibrahams Road to the existing freeway at One Mile Creek, opened 21 March 1980, by the Minister for Transport, the Hon Robert Maclellan MLA at a cost of A$11m.<ref>Country Roads Board Victoria. ''67th Annual Report. 1979-1980'', Kew, Victoria: Country Roads Board Victoria. 1980</ref>\n*1980 \u2013 35&nbsp;km deviation of Hume Highway bypassing the Razorback Range opened on 15 December from Narellan Rd Macarthur to Yanderra, connecting sections opened December 1974 and May 1977.\n*1981 - Avenel bypass. 16&nbsp;km north-east from the [[Goulburn Valley Freeway|Goulburn Valley Highway]] interchange, opened 1 December 1981 by the Minister for Transport, the Hon Robert Maclellan MLA at a cost of A$25m.<ref>Country Roads Board Victoria. ''69th Annual Report. 1981-1982'', Kew, Victoria: Country Roads Board Victoria. 1982. p. 11</ref>\n*1982 \u2013 [[Seymour, Victoria|Seymour]] bypass opened 14 December 1982 by the Minister for Transport, the Hon. Steve Crabb MP. The 9&nbsp;km bypass cost A$26m to complete. At this stage, although largely opened to traffic, a one kilometre section of south bound carriageway south of Seymour was still under construction.<ref>Country Roads Board Victoria. ''Activity Report 1982/83'', Kew, Victoria: Country Roads Board Victoria, 1983. p. 8</ref>\n*1984 \u2013 [[Longwood, Victoria|Longwood]] section. This 10&nbsp;km section from Oxenburys Road to Creighton Road was opened by the Assistant Minister of Transport, the Hon. Jack Simpson MP, on 18 May 1984. The project cost A$10m. The opening marked the halfway point for the duplication of the highway within Victoria, with the total length of dual carriageways at that point measuring 151&nbsp;km.<ref>Road Construction Authority Victoria. ''1st Annual Report 1983-84'', Kew, Victoria: Road Construction Authority, Victoria, 1984. p. 11</ref>\n*1985 \u2013 Barnawartha to [[Wodonga]] duplication, from Hanson Road to Parkers Road. An initial 4&nbsp;km of the 12.6&nbsp;km duplicate carriageway was completed in 1985.<ref name=rca1987>Road Construction Authority Victoria. ''Annual Report 1986-87'', Kew, Victoria: Road Construction Authority, Victoria, 1987. p. 63</ref>\n*1986 - 7.3&nbsp;km Marulan Bypass opened on 27 November 1986.<ref name=his2013>[http://www.rms.nsw.gov.au/documents/projects/south-western/hume-highway/history-begins-with-a-road.pdf] History Begins With a Road (RMS)</ref>\n*1987 \u2013 [[Benalla]] bypass opened March 1987. The 36.5&nbsp;km bypass was at this time the longest stretch of highway duplication opened at once in Victoria. The project cost was A$70m and extended from south of [[Baddaginnie, Victoria|Baddaginnie]] to Chivers Road, south of [[Glenrowan, Victoria|Glenrowan]].<ref name=rca1987 />\n*1987/88 \u2013 Barnawartha to Wodonga, from Hanson Road to Parkers Road. The remaining 8.6&nbsp;km of the 12.6&nbsp;km duplicate carriageway was expected to be open to traffic in \u2018the second half of 1987\u2019.<ref name=rca1987 />\n*1987/88 \u2013 Chiltern to Barnawartha. 21&nbsp;km A$31m duplication from Gilmours Road to Hanson Road was expected to be \u2018opened to traffic in stages from July 1987 until late 1989\u2019.<ref name=rca1987 />\n*1988/89 \u2013 12.5&nbsp;km Glenrowan bypass completed during the financial year at a cost of A$31.5m.<ref>Road Construction Authority Victoria. ''Annual Report 1988-1989'', Kew, Victoria: Road Construction Authority, Victoria, 1989. p. 48</ref>\n*1989 - Berrima Bypass. 15.5&nbsp;km-long bypass officially opened to traffic on 22 March 1989 at a total cost of A$80m.<ref name=his2013 />\n*1990 \u2013 [[Springhurst, Victoria|Springhurst]] to Chiltern, Victoria. This 5.2&nbsp;km duplication opened to traffic in March 1990, at a cost of A$8.5m.<ref name=vic1990>VicRoads. ''VicRoads Annual Report, 1989-1990'', Kew, Victoria: VicRoads, 1990, p. 57</ref>\n*1990 \u2013 [[Euroa]] to Balmattum, Victoria. Duplication of this 8&nbsp;km section was opened to traffic in June 1990, at a cost of A$16m.<ref name=vic1990 />\n*1990 \u2013 The 3.3&nbsp;km Barnawartha (Victoria) bypass was fully completed and opened to traffic in June 1990, at a cost of A$11m.<ref name=vic1990 />\n*1991 \u2013 3.3&nbsp;km duplication north of Springhurst opened in November 1991.<ref name=\"VicRoads. 1992, p. 40\">VicRoads. ''VicRoads Annual Report, 1991-1992'', Kew, Victoria: VicRoads, 1992, p. 40</ref>\n*1991 \u2013 10&nbsp;km duplication from Coppabella Road to Reedy Creek completed on 17 December 1991.<ref name=his2013 />\n*1992 \u2013 Euroa bypass opened to traffic on 3 April 1992, at a cost of A$43m - A$2m under budget.<ref name=\"VicRoads. 1992, p. 40\"/>\n*1992 - Mittagong Bypass. Originally part of the 1970s/1980's F5 project, this 8.2&nbsp;km-long bypass was opened on 17 August 1992 at a completed cost of A$83m.<ref name=his2013 /><ref name=\"RTA Annual Report 1992-1993, p. 6\">RTA Annual Report 1992-1993, p. 6</ref>\n*1992 \u2013 13&nbsp;km Goulburn Bypass opened to traffic on 5 December 1992 at a completed cost of A$84m.<ref name=his2013 /><ref name=\"RTA Annual Report 1992-1993, p. 6\"/>\n*1993 - Cullerin Range Deviation. 34&nbsp;km-long freeway-grade deviation officially opened on 5 April 1993 at a cost of A$132m.<ref name=his2013 /><ref name=\"RTA Annual Report 1992-1993, p. 6\"/>\n*1994 - Springhurst bypass. 5&nbsp;km opened to traffic in March 1994, at a cost of A$7.7m.<ref name=vic1994>VicRoads. ''VicRoads Annual Report 1993-94'', Kew, Victoria: VicRoads, 1994, p. 17</ref>\n*1994 - [[Wangaratta]] bypass. A$80m 20&nbsp;km bypass opened to traffic in April 1994, eight months ahead of schedule and A$30m under budget. This was the final section of the Hume Highway in Victoria to be duplicated.<ref name=vic1994 />\n*1994 - Yass Bypass. 18&nbsp;km dual-carriageway officially opened on 25 July 1994 at a total cost of A$106m.<ref name=his2013 /><ref name=\"RTA Annual Report 1994-1995, p. 74\">RTA Annual Report 1994-1995, p. 74</ref>\n*1995 - Cullerin to Yass Duplication. First 11&nbsp;km section opened on 14 September 1994, followed by the second 6&nbsp;km section on 3 May 1995. Final cost was A$59.1m.<ref name=his2013 /><ref name=\"RTA Annual Report 1994-1995, p. 74\"/>\n*1995 - Jugiong Bypass. 13&nbsp;km dual-carriageway opened on 11 October 1995 at a total cost of A$85.5m.<ref name=his2013 /><ref name=\"RTA Annual Report 1995-1996, p. 79\">RTA Annual Report 1995-1996, p. 79</ref>\n*1996 - Tarcutta Range Deviation. A$52.6m 9.4&nbsp;km-long upgrade south of Tumblong opened to traffic on 3 May 1996.<ref name=his2013 /><ref name=\"RTA Annual Report 1995-1996, p. 79\"/>\n*2004 - Craigieburn bypass (section one) opened to traffic December 2004 between the [[M80 Ring Road|Metropolitan Ring Road]] and Cooper Street.<ref>VicRoads. ''VicRoads Annual Report 2004-05'', Kew, Victoria: VicRoads, 2005, p. 33</ref>\n*2005 - Craigieburn bypass (section two) opened December 2005, completing the A$305m 17&nbsp;km bypass.<ref>VicRoads. ''VicRoads Annual Report 2005-06'', Kew, Victoria: VicRoads, 2006, p. 45</ref>\n*2007 - [[Albury-Wodonga]] bypass. Construction commenced in May 2005 and was opened to traffic on 6 March 2007. The [[New South Wales|NSW]] section comprised 14.6&nbsp;km from [[Table Top, New South Wales|Ettamogah]] to the [[Murray River]] through the city of Albury. The [[Government of Australia|Australian Government]] fully funded the A$374 million NSW section of the project.<ref>Roads and Traffic Authority NSW. ''Annual report 2007'', Sydney, New South Wales: RTA, 2007. p. 35-36</ref> The A$150m Victorian section was largely funded by the federal government, with the A$5.8m Bandiana Link funded by the State Government of Victoria.<ref>VicRoads. ''VicRoads Annual Report 2006-07'', Kew, Victoria: VicRoads, 2007, p. 38</ref>\n*2009 - Southern Hume Highway Duplication. Work began in October 2007 and the 65&nbsp;km section (2&nbsp;km shorter than the previous highway route) was progressively opened to traffic from mid 2009 and completed in December 2009. Completion of this section left only 21&nbsp;km of the Hume Highway as single carriageway, through the towns of Tarcutta, Holbrook and Woomargama.<ref name=rta2010>Roads and Traffic Authority NSW. ''Annual report 2009-10'', Sydney, New South Wales: RTA, 2010. p. 25</ref>\n[[File:Looking south down the Hume Highway in Holbrook (1).jpg|thumb|The Hume Highway as it passed through [[Holbrook, New South Wales|Holbrook]], the final town on the highway to be bypassed]]\n*2009 - [[Coolac]] Bypass. Construction began in May 2007. The 12&nbsp;km bypass was opened to traffic in August 2009. The project was fully funded by the Australian Government at a cost of A$171 million.<ref name=rta2010 />\n*2009 - Sheahan Bridge duplication, Gundagai. This A$70.6 million project was fully funded by the Australian Government and was completed in 2009. Traffic was switched to the new bridge in May 2009 to enable essential maintenance on the existing bridge. Both bridges were available to traffic as dual carriageways in December 2009.<ref name=rta2010 />\n*2011 - [[Woomargama]] Bypass. This 9&nbsp;km bypass was opened on 7 November 2011. The A$265 million project was funded by the Australian Government.<ref name=rta2012>New South Wales. Roads and Maritime Services. ''Annual report 2011-12'', Sydney, New South Wales: NSW Government, 2012. p. 18</ref>\n*2011 - [[Tarcutta]] Bypass. The 7&nbsp;km Tarcutta Bypass was opened to traffic on 15 November 2011. The A$290 million project was funded by the Australian Government.<ref name=rta2012 />\n*2013 - [[Holbrook, New South Wales|Holbrook]] bypass. In June 2013, the NSW department of [[Roads and Maritime Services|Roads and Maritime]] celebrated the imminent completion of the duplication of the Hume Highway with a community day at the Holbrook Bypass.<ref>New South Wales. Roads and Maritime Services. ''Annual report 2012-13'', Sydney, New South Wales: NSW Government, 2013. p. 18</ref>\n\n==Route==\n[[File:(Updated Route Marker) Hume Highway (NSW) Destination Distances.png|thumb|Distances to destinations through the Hume Highway heading southbound with the current M31 route number[[File:Hume Hwy (NSW) Distances Updated.gif|thumb|right|Distances to destinations along the highway from Sydney using the former National Highway 31 route marker which was replaced by the M31 Route Number]]<br />]]\n[[File:Hume Fwy (VIC) Distances.gif|thumb|right|Approximate road distances (in kilometres) along the Hume Freeway southwards from the Victorian border. Currently, VicRoads removed the National Highway sign and will only include the M31 sign. However the old style is still shown in many signs]]\nAt its Sydney end, the Hume Highway begins at [[Parramatta Road]], in [[Summer Hill, New South Wales|Summer Hill]]. This route is numbered as A22. The first {{convert|31|km}}<ref name=\"Google Maps 1\"/> of the highway was known as ''Liverpool Road'' until August 1928, when it was renamed as part of the Hume or Great Southern Highway, as part of the creation of the NSW highway system. Sections of the highway through Sydney's suburbs continue to be also known by its former names of Liverpool Road, Sydney Road and Copeland Street (through Liverpool).\n\nThe main Hume Highway effectively commences at the junction of the [[M5 South Western Motorway]] and the [[Westlink M7]] at {{NSWcity|Prestons}}. Heading eastbound, the M5 provides access to [[Sydney Airport]] and the CBD; while the M7 provides access to [[Newcastle, New South Wales|Newcastle]] and [[Brisbane]] bypassing the Sydney CBD. Both of these routes are [[road pricing|tolled]].\n\nOther than sections within the urban areas of Sydney and Melbourne, the Hume Highway is dual carriageway or expressway standard for its full length in Victoria and New South Wales.\n\nAlthough the full length of the Hume Highway is dual carriageway (with at-grade intersections and restricted entry from adjoining land), there are considerable lengths of the highway which are of full freeway standard. Most of these sections are bypasses of the larger towns on the route, where the need to deviate the route to construct the bypass made it practical to deny access from adjoining land and thus provide full freeway conditions. In addition to these bypasses the sections between Casula (in southwestern Sydney) and Berrima (built 1973\u201392), and Broadford to Wallan (1976), which were both constructed as major deviations, are also of full freeway standard. The entire section in Victoria is categorised as a freeway by government roads authority [[VicRoads]], although a few intersections along the route are not yet grade-separated. The speed limit on the full length of the highway is {{convert|110|kph|mph|1|abbr=on}}.\n\nAs the Hume Freeway approaches Melbourne at the suburb of [[Craigieburn, Victoria|Craigieburn]], {{convert|27|km}} north of the [[Melbourne central business district]], the Craigieburn Bypass now diverts the Hume Freeway (and the M31 designation) to the east of the former route, to terminate at the [[Western Ring Road]]/[[Metropolitan Ring Road]] (M80). This bypass was opened in two stages, in December 2004 and December 2005.\n\nAt its Melbourne end, the original alignment of the Melbourne\u2013Sydney route followed Royal Parade northward from where it begins at its intersection with Elizabeth Street and Flemington Road. Royal Parade becomes Sydney Road at Brunswick Road and then became the Hume Highway itself at Campbellfield. This ceased to be the designated route of the Hume Highway in 1992, with the completion of Stage 1 of the Western Ring Road, at which point the designation of the southbound highway was truncated. The former highway south from the Western Ring Road to Elizabeth Street is route is now numbered as State Route 55 and is now officially called [[Old Hume Highway|Sydney Road]].\n\n===Recent New South Wales upgrading===\n[[File:Holbrook Bypass Golden Guidepost 001.JPG|thumb|A \"Golden Guidepost\" on the Holbrook Bypass section of the Hume Freeway. The guidepost symbolises the connection of Melbourne and Sydney by dual carriageway.]]\nBetween February 2009 and March 2012, both carriageways were widened between Brooks Road and Narellan Road. This work was undertaken in 3 stages. The first stage, widening to 4 lanes each way between Brooks Road and St Andrews Road [[St Andrews, New South Wales|St Andrews]] was completed in 2010. The second stage, widening to 4 lanes each way between St Andrews Road and Raby Road commenced in 2009 and was completed in mid-2011. The final stage, widening to 3 lanes each way between Raby Road and Narellan Road, commenced in September 2010 and was completed in March 2012.<ref name=RTA_f5_widen>[http://www.rta.nsw.gov.au/constructionmaintenance/majorconstructionprojectssydney/f5widening/index.html F5 Freeway widening \u2013 RTA]</ref> Construction of a pedestrian bridge over the highway to link [[Claymore, New South Wales|Claymore]] and [[Woodbine, New South Wales|Woodbine]] was also completed. This section of the highway, opened as part of the two stages opened in October 1973 and December 1974, was originally designed for widening of the carriageways to three lanes.\n\nWork commenced in 2010 on a {{convert|9.5|km|mi|abbr=on}} bypass of Holbrook. The bypass was opened to traffic on 7 August 2013 after being postponed due to wet weather.<ref name=delayedopen>{{cite web|title=Holbrook bypass opens to traffic|url=http://www.rta.nsw.gov.au/newsevents/news/2013/130806-holbrook-bypass-opens-to-traffic-tomorrow.html|work=Roads and Maritime Services|publisher=NSW Government|accessdate=6 August 2013|date=6 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Four lanes at last as bypass opens|url=http://au.prime7.yahoo.com/v1/news/a/-/local/18411793/four-lanes-at-last-as-bypass-opens-video/|work=Prime7|publisher=Yahoo!7|accessdate=8 August 2013|date=8 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Lambert|first=Olivia|title=Lawrence adds dash to Holbrook bypass opening|url=http://www.bordermail.com.au/story/1691704/lawrence-adds-dash-to-holbrook-bypass-opening-video-photos/?cs=11|accessdate=8 August 2013|newspaper=The Border Mail|date=8 August 2013}}</ref> The opening of the bypass resulted in dual carriageway (much to freeway standard) over the full length of the Hume Highway for the first time.\n\n===Current Victorian upgrade projects===\n[[VicRoads]] has undertaken a planning study for the upgrading of the Hume Freeway by removal of direct access from adjoining properties and grade-separation of the intersections between [[Kalkallo, Victoria|Kalkallo]] and [[Beveridge, Victoria|Beveridge]]. These intersections have the highest accident rate of the Hume Freeway in Victoria.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.vicroads.vic.gov.au/NR/rdonlyres/A245C58C-88F0-4D1D-B3E4-277DEBC17159/0/HumeKalkalloLandUseBusinessandAgricultureupdate.pdf| title =Hume Kalkallo Land Use Business and Agriculture|publisher = VicRoads |accessdate = 2008-06-08 |format=PDF}}</ref> The study, completed in March 2009, intended to amend council planning schemes so as to reserve space for the upgrade, but no timetable has been set for the project.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.vicroads.vic.gov.au/Home/RoadsAndProjects/RoadProjects/NothernSuburbs/HumeHighwayAccessRestoration+ProjectKalkallo.htm |title=Hume Highway, Kalkallo to Beveridge \u2013 Access restoration planning |publisher=VicRoads |accessdate=8 June 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn addition a 4-level interchange between the Hume Freeway and the [[Outer Metropolitan Ring Road]] is proposed for construction after 2020.<ref>{{Cite map|url=http://www.vicroads.vic.gov.au/Home/RoadsAndProjects/RoadProjects/PlanningStudies/OuterMetropolitanRingPlanningStudy.htm|title=Outer Metropolitan Ring Road planning study|publisher=VicRoads|accessdate=24 June 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090618211315/http://www.vicroads.vic.gov.au/Home/RoadsAndProjects/RoadProjects/PlanningStudies/OuterMetropolitanRingPlanningStudy.htm|archivedate=18 June 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vicroads.vic.gov.au/NR/rdonlyres/26785B2E-3762-4BCE-A89E-77FB9AF343C6/0/FigureS1maponly.jpg |title=Map of recommended option for Outer Metropolitan Ring Road |publisher=VicRoads |accessdate=24 June 2009 |format=jpg |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090628235353/http://www.vicroads.vic.gov.au/NR/rdonlyres/26785B2E-3762-4BCE-A89E-77FB9AF343C6/0/FigureS1maponly.jpg |archivedate=28 June 2009 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Landscapes===\nHeading north from Melbourne, the road passes through the hills of the [[Great Dividing Range]], some of which is covered with box eucalypt forest but of which much is cleared for farmland, before levelling out near Seymour to cross flat, mostly cleared farming country to Wodonga and the Victoria-New South Wales border. Victoria's landscape differs from that of the typical 'true Australian [[Outback]]', but a dry summer can leave the ground parched. [[Mount Buffalo National Park|Mount Buffalo]] can be seen in the distance to the east as the highway comes down off the Warby Range near Glenrowan, and a museum commemorating [[Ned Kelly]] is located nearby. At Wangaratta the highway passes close to the Rutherglen and Milawa wine-producing areas.\n\nContinuing north, the [[Murray River]], the south bank of which is the Victoria-New South Wales border, is crossed on the bypass of Albury-Wodonga. From Albury, the highway skirts Lake Hume and continues across undulating country generally north-east towards Holbrook and then Tarcutta. Just north of Tarcutta the highway encounters the first of several ranges which form outliers of the Great Dividing Range, and which are crossed as the highway climbs the slopes to the tablelands west of Yass. From here the highway runs eastward, to Goulburn where it again turns northeast. Most of the New South Wales countryside from Albury to Marulan has been developed for [[wool]] production, with Yass and Goulburn in particular noted for their fine wool.\n\n===Fixed speed camera locations===\nIn April 2007, 'point-to-point' fixed speed-camera sites were installed, in the median strip along the Craigieburn Bypass section and northward to [[Broadford, Victoria|Broadford]], in Victoria, at roughly 15\u201320&nbsp;km intervals. These measure both instantaneous (flash photography) speed and its speciality in the point-to-point versions (between two or more sites and then the average speed is measured to the fixed speed limit, comparing how long it takes a vehicle to reach one point from another). There are five sites, with two cameras (radar version) at each, totalling ten altogether.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.camerassavelives.vic.gov.au/home/cameras/camera+systems/hume+freeway+point-to-point/ | title = Point-To-Point Speed Cameras - Hume Fwy | work = Speed & Red Light Cameras | publisher = Cameras Save Lives - Department of Justice (Victorian Government) [non-VicRoads] | year=2012 | accessdate =27 November 2013}}</ref><br />\nIn Sydney: next to Ashfield Primary School, near Culdees Road Burwood, Willee St Enfield, Stacey St Bankstown, Brennan St Yagoona, and Knight St Lansvale.\n[[File:Point to Point Speed Cameras.jpg|thumb|right|Point-to-point speed camera on the Hume Highway in Victoria]]\n\n===Former route allocations===\nThe Hume Highway has many former route allocations including former National Route 31.<ref>[http://www.ozroads.com.au/NationalSystem/natroutes.htm National Routes], ''Ozroads'', Retrieved on 1 June 2013.{{Self-published source|date=October 2013}}</ref> Where and when the former route numbers were implemented are stated below.\n*''Summer Hill - Chullora:''\n** {{AUshield|R|31}} National Route 31 <small>(1954-1994)</small>\n** {{AUshield|Met|5}} Metroad 5 <small>(1994-2001)</small>\n** {{AUshield|S|31}} State Route 31 <small>(2001-2013)</small>\n*''Chullora - Casula:''<ref>[http://www.ozroads.com.au/NSW/RouteNumbering/State%20Routes/31/sr31.htm NSW State Route 31], ''Ozroads'', Retrieved on 1 June 2013.{{Self-published source|date=October 2013}}</ref>\n** {{AUshield|R|31}} National Route 31 <small>(1954-1994)</small>\n** {{AUshield|S|31}} State Route 31 <small>(1994-2013)</small>\n*''Casula - Prestons:''\n** {{AUshield|R|31}} National Route 31 <small>(1954-1979)</small>\n** {{AUshield|N|31}} National Highway 31 <small>(1979-1992/93)</small>\n** {{AUshield|Met|5}} Metroad 5 <small>(1992/93-1994)</small>\n** {{AUshield|None|Met}} No Shield <small>(1994-2013)</small>\n*''Prestons - Campbelltown:''<ref>[http://www.ozroads.com.au/NSW/RouteNumbering/Metroads/5/metroad5.htm NSW Metroad 5], ''Ozroads'', Retrieved on 1 June 2013.{{Self-published source|date=October 2013}}</ref>\n** {{AUshield|R|31}} National Route 31 <small>(1954-1979)</small>\n** {{AUshield|N|31}} National Highway 31 <small>(1979-1998)</small>\n** {{AUshield|Met|5}} Metroad 5 <small>(1998-2013)</small>\n*''Campbelltown - NSW/Vic. Border:'' \n** {{AUshield|R|31}} National Route 31 <small>(1954-1979)</small>\n** {{AUshield|N|31}} National Highway 31 <small>(1979-2013)</small>\n*''NSW/Vic. Border - Campbellfield:''\n**{{AUshield|R|31}} National Route 31 <small>(1954-1979)</small>\n** {{AUshield|N|31}} National Highway 31 <small>(1979-1996/97)</small>\n** {{AUshield|N|M31}} National Highway M31 <small>(1997\u2013present in most signs)</small>\n\n==Exits and major interchanges==\n{{main|Hume Highway exits and interchanges}}\nThe Hume Highway exits and major intersections are spread across {{convert|840|km}}<ref name=\"Google Maps 1\"/><ref name=\"Google Maps 2\"/><ref name=\"Google Maps 3\"/><ref name=\"Google Maps 4\"/> in the Australian states of New South Wales and Victoria. The Hume Highway [[National Highway (Australia)|national route]] is divided into four sections comprising, from north to south, urban stretches of the highway in Sydney, a [[motorway]] from the outskirts of Sydney to the [[Southern Highlands (New South Wales)|Southern Highlands]], a [[grade separation|grade-separated]] highway in regional New South Wales and across the state border, and a [[freeway]] throughout regional Victoria and into the outer suburbs of northern Melbourne.\n\nIn Sydney, the Hume Highway stretches {{convert|31|km}} southwest from {{NSWcity|Haberfield}} in the [[Inner West (Sydney)|inner west]] to {{NSWcity|Prestons}} via {{NSWcity|Enfield|Greenacre|Villawood|Liverpool}} and {{NSWcity|Casula}}.<ref name=\"Google Maps 1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com.au/maps/dir/-33.8861825,151.1388406/-33.9568058,150.8757672/@-33.9215167,150.9373809,12z/data=!4m9!4m8!1m5!3m4!1m2!1d150.9707108!2d-33.8890431!3s0x6b12bd9357eeb335:0x4692ee0457319662!1m0!3e0 |title=Hume Highway; 71 Parramatta Rd, Haberfield NSW 2045, Australia to Camden Valley Way, Prestons NSW 2170, Australia |publisher=[[Google Maps]] |date=2017 |access-date=9 January 2017}}</ref> From Sydney's southwestern outskirts, the Hume Motorway stretches {{convert|88|km}} south by southwest, from Prestons to outside {{NSWcity|Berrima}} [[Bypass (road)|bypass]]ing {{NSWcity|Campbelltown|Camden|Mittagong|Bowral}} and {{NSWcity|Moss Vale}}.<ref name=\"Google Maps 2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/maps/dir/-33.955464,150.877111/-34.51929,150.2978607/@-33.9926783,150.9128245,13.26z/data=!4m5!4m4!1m1!4e1!1m0!3e0?hl=en |title=Hume Motorway; -33.9554640, 150.8771110 to Hume Motorway & Hume Hwy & Old Hume Hwy & M31, New South Wales 2577, Australia |publisher=[[Google Maps]] |date=2017 |access-date=7 January 2017}}</ref> From outside Berrima, the Hume Highway stretches {{convert|426|km}} southwest by west, bypassing {{NSWcity|Sutton Forest|Marulan|Goulburn|Yass}}, {{NSWcity|Bowning|Bookham|Jugiong|Gundagai|Tarcutta}}, {{NSWcity|Holbrook|Thurgoona|Lavington}} and {{NSWcity|Albury}} before crossing the Murray River and entering Victoria.<ref name=\"Google Maps 3\">{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/maps/dir/-34.51929,150.2978607/-36.108022,146.9026578/@-36.1078856,146.9031213,20.43z/data=!4m2!4m1!3e0?hl=en |title=Hume Highway; Old Hume Hwy & M31, New South Wales 2577, Australia to Bandiana Link Rd & Hume Hwy & Hume Fwy & National Highway M31, Wodonga VIC 3690, Australia |publisher=[[Google Maps]] |date=2017 |access-date=9 January 2017}}</ref> From this point the Hume Freeway continues {{convert|295|km}} southwest by south, bypassing {{VICcity|Wodonga|Chiltern|Wangaratta|Benalla}}, {{VICcity|Seymour|Broadford|Beveridge|Craigieburn}} and terminating at {{VICcity|Thomastown}}.<ref name=\"Google Maps 4\">{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/maps/dir/-36.1080155,146.902666/-37.6892258,144.9862545/@-37.6882871,144.9738899,14.95z/data=!4m2!4m1!3e0?hl=en |title=Hume Freeway; Hume Hwy, Wodonga VIC 3690, Australia to M80, Thomastown VIC 3074, Australia |publisher=[[Google Maps]] |date=2017 |access-date=9 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nFrom northeast to southwest, termini, major exits and interchanges occur with the [[Great Western Highway]] / [[Parramatta Road]] (A22), [[A3 (Sydney)|A3]] (A3), [[A6 (Sydney)|A6]] (A6), [[Henry Lawson Drive]], [[Cumberland Highway]] (A28), [[M5 Motorway (Sydney)|M5 Motorway]] (M5), [[Westlink M7]] (M7), [[Camden Valley Way]] (A28), [[A9 (Sydney)|A9]] (A9), [[Remembrance Drive]], [[Old Hume Highway]] (B73), [[Illawarra Highway]] (A48), [[Federal Highway (Australia)|Federal Highway]] (M23), [[Yass Valley Way]], [[Barton Highway]] (A25), [[Lachlan Valley Way]] (B81), [[Burley Griffin Way]] (B94), [[Snowy Mountains Highway]] (B72), [[Sturt Highway]] (A20), [[Olympic Highway]] (A41), [[Riverina Highway]] (B58), [[Murray Valley Highway]] (B400), [[Great Alpine Road]] (B500), [[Midland Highway (Victoria)|Midland Highway]] (A300/B300), [[Goulburn Valley Freeway]] (M39), [[Goulburn Valley Highway]] (B340), [[Northern Highway, Victoria|Northern Highway]] (B75), [[Sydney Road, Melbourne|Sydney Road]] (SR55), and [[M80 Ring Road, Melbourne|Metropolitan Ring Road]] (M80).<ref name=\"Google Maps 1\"/><ref name=\"Google Maps 2\"/><ref name=\"Google Maps 3\"/><ref name=\"Google Maps 4\"/>\n\nMajor river crossings, from northeast to southwest, are the [[Nepean River|Nepean]] (three times), [[Wingecarribee River|Wingecarribee]], [[Paddys River (Southern Highlands, New South Wales)|Paddys]], [[Murrumbidgee River|Murrumbidgee]], [[Murray River|Murray]], [[Ovens River|Ovens]], [[King River (Victoria)|King]] and [[Goulburn River|Goulburn]] rivers. The Hume also crosses the [[Prospect Creek (New South Wales)|Prospect]], [[Jugiong Creek|Jugiong]], and [[Tarcutta Creek|Tarcutta]] creeks.<ref name=\"Google Maps 1\"/><ref name=\"Google Maps 2\"/><ref name=\"Google Maps 3\"/><ref name=\"Google Maps 4\"/>\n\n==Towns==\nIn New South Wales, all towns on the Hume Highway have been bypassed. From Sydney, southwards to the Victorian border, the bypassed towns include [[Campbelltown, New South Wales|Campbelltown]], [[Camden, New South Wales|Camden]], [[Picton, New South Wales|Picton]], [[Mittagong]], [[Berrima, New South Wales|Berrima]], [[Marulan, New South Wales|Marulan]], [[Goulburn]], [[Gunning, New South Wales|Gunning]], [[Yass, New South Wales|Yass]], [[Bowning, New South Wales|Bowning]], [[Bookham, New South Wales|Bookham]], [[Jugiong, New South Wales|Jugiong]], [[Coolac, New South Wales|Coolac]], [[Gundagai]], [[Tarcutta, New South Wales|Tarcutta]], [[Holbrook, New South Wales|Holbrook]], [[Woomargama, New South Wales|Woomargama]] and [[Albury]].\n\nIn Victoria, all towns have been bypassed. They are, in order from the NSW border, [[Wodonga]], [[Chiltern, Victoria|Chiltern]], [[Wangaratta]], [[Benalla]], [[Euroa, Victoria|Euroa]], [[Violet Town, Victoria|Violet Town]], [[Seymour, Victoria|Seymour]], [[Broadford, Victoria|Broadford]] and [[Craigieburn, Victoria|Craigieburn]].\n\n===Camden===\n{{main|Camden, New South Wales{{!}}Camden}}\n[[File:Douglas Park Bridge F5 Freeway.jpg|thumbnail|Hume Highway at Douglas Park near Picton]]\n[[Camden, New South Wales|Camden]] dates from 1840 and lies {{convert|60|km}} south west of Sydney on the Nepean River. It retains a rural character and has many historic buildings. There is an aviation museum at nearby [[Narellan, New South Wales|Narellan]]. Urban sprawl has made Camden part of the Sydney metropolitan area.\n\nBefore the mid-1980s, the Hume Highway ran west from the Cross Roads at [[Prestons, New South Wales|Prestons]], 4&nbsp;km south of Liverpool to [[Edmondson Park, New South Wales|Edmondson Park]], where it followed the route of what is now Cowpasture Road. It then ran southwest to Camden. This section is now the Camden Valley Way.\n\nThe Hume Highway has twice bypassed Camden. The first bypass was opened in 1973, via the Macarthur Bridge, and ran from Narellan to Benkennie (South Camden). This was in turn bypassed in December 1980 when a section of what was then called the South Western Freeway (route F5) from Campbelltown to Yerrinbool opened. From the north, the freeway then ran from the Cross Roads to Campbelltown Rd at St Andrews (opened August 1973) and St Andrews-Camden Road (opened December 1974) joining the southern section from Yerrinbool to Aylmerton (opened May 1977). This became the route of the Hume Highway and national route 31 in the mid 1980s.\n\nThe former highway from Camden south to Aylmerton is now called Remembrance Drive. It climbs southwards from Camden, goes through the Razorback Ridge to Picton, and then climbs to Tahmoor and Bargo. It reaches the Southern Tablelands and rejoins the present Hume Highway at Aylmerton, 6&nbsp;km north of Mittagong. The whole route from Cross Roads to Aylmerton is now state route 89.\n\n[[File:Hume Highway in NSW.jpg|thumb|right|Hume Highway through Southern Highlands]]\nAn alternative route to the highway runs from Aylmerton through Mittagong and Bowral to join the Illawarra Highway at Moss Vale and then follows the Illawarra Highway through Sutton Forest to rejoin the Hume Highway at Hoddles Crossroads (named after Surveyor Robert Hoddle who also laid out the Melbourne CBD).\n\n===Mittagong===\n{{Main|Mittagong}}\n[[Mittagong]] lies {{convert|110|km}} south-west of Sydney, just off the Hume Highway at the edge of the Southern Tablelands. Mittagong is also a part of the [[Southern Highlands (New South Wales)|Southern Highlands]] region. It is notable for being the location of Australia's first ironworks. Mittagong's streets are lined with various species of deciduous trees and it has a busy town centre.\n\nUntil August 1992 when the Mittagong bypass was opened, the town was dominated by trucks and in winter it was also busy with skiers' traffic on the way to the Australian Alps. Today the Hume Highway bypasses Mittagong and all the towns of the Southern Tablelands. In the late 1990s, engineers detected subsidence under part of the bypass where it runs along a steep slope near the Nattai River. This was caused by features of the local geology, and mining activity at the adjacent Mount Alexandra coalmine from the 1950s to the 1970s.<ref>{{Cite web| year=2001 | url=http://www.dotars.gov.au/dept/media/2001/d4_2001.aspx | title=Media release: Plan to Bridge the Hume Highway at Mittagong | publisher=[[Department of Transport and Regional Services]] www.dotars.gov.au | accessdate=26 Apr 2006|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050624182524/http://www.dotars.gov.au/dept/media/2001/d4_2001.aspx|archivedate=24 June 2005}}</ref> The problem was remedied by closing one carriageway at a time and building a pair of 'land bridges' across the unstable section of the slope.\n\n===Moss Vale===\n{{main|Moss Vale|Sutton Forest}}\n[[Moss Vale, New South Wales|Moss Vale]] has several beautiful old and attractive buildings and Leighton Gardens, in the centre of the main street, is a pleasant park. It is best during spring when its flowers are in blossom or in autumn when the leaves of its exotic deciduous trees are changing colour. [[Sutton Forest, New South Wales|Sutton Forest]] is surrounded by farms, vineyards and is home to elegant country homes and estates. It has a church, an inn, a couple of restaurants and one or two specialty shops.\n\n===Berrima===\n{{main|Berrima, New South Wales}}\n[[File:Hume Hwy bridges over Greenhills Rd.JPG|thumb|right|Twin bridges carrying the Hume Highway over Greenhills Road north of Berrima {{Coord|34|28|S|150|21|E|region:AU-NSW}}]]\n[[Berrima, New South Wales|Berrima]] has flourished since it was bypassed in March 1989, with tourists finding it an easy day trip from either Sydney or [[Canberra]] to enjoy the town square and the Georgian architecture of this historic town. Berrima is the last Southern Highlands town that the Hume Highway passes.\n\n===Marulan===\n{{main|Marulan}}\nThe [[Marulan, New South Wales|Marulan]] bypass was opened in 1986. The southern part of Governor [[Lachlan Macquarie]]'s road of 1819 ran from [[Sutton Forest, New South Wales|Sutton Forest]] roughly along existing minor roads through what is now Penrose State Forest to Canyonleigh, Brayton, Carrick and Towrang, where it joined the current route to Goulburn. Branching from this route (now part of the [[Illawarra Highway]]) just west of Sutton Forest, a road, now known as Old Argyle Road, developed in the 1820s. It ran to [[Bungonia, New South Wales|Bungonia]], via [[Wingello, New South Wales|Wingello]], [[Tallong, New South Wales|Tallong]], and the southern outskirts of Marulan. Marulan lies on the [[150th meridian east]].\n\nWhen [[Thomas Mitchell (explorer)|Thomas Mitchell]] rerouted the Great South Road in the 1830s, he decided to bring these two roads together to meet at old Marulan, with roads proceeding west to Goulburn and south to Bungonia. When the railway reached Marulan in 1868, the town migrated 3&nbsp;km north to the railway station. Nevertheless, the old cemetery remains at the Bungonia Road intersection. A quarry is about to be developed near the intersection, so an interchange has been built. It is at this point that the highway climbs the Marulan Ramp, which is part of the divide between the Shoalhaven and Wollondilly River systems.\n\n===Towrang Stockade===\n{{main|Towrang Convict Stockade}}\n[[File:Towrang bridge.JPG|thumb|left|Towrang bridge of 1839]]\n[[Towrang]] Creek was the site of a major stockade for chain-bound convicts and others involved in the construction of the '''Great South Road'''. The stockade was located on the western side of the Highway and was used from around 1836 to 1842. The stockade became the principal penal establishment in the southern district and was noted for its harsh discipline. There were usually at least 250 convicts stationed there. They slept on bare boards with a blanket apiece, 10 men to a box or cell. One of the two official floggers was later found murdered.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/New-South-Wales/Goulburn/2005/02/17/1108500193619.html |title=Travel \u2013 Goulburn |work=[[Sydney Morning Herald]] |accessdate=26 April 2006|date=8 February 2004}}</ref> The stockade used to be accessible by a stile, but this has been taken down to discourage use of the once daunting intersection of the Highway with [[Towrang]] Road. There are the remains of the powder magazine next to the [[Wollondilly River]], three graves on the north bank of Towrang Creek, and the remains of a weir on Towrang Creek built for the stockade. Aboriginal stone tools have also been found on the banks of Towrang Creek, indicating that this was a route well-travelled long before [[Hamilton Hume]] came this way in 1824.\n\nThere is also a rest area on the eastern side of the highway, where a well-preserved bridge dating from 1839 (possibly designed by [[David Lennox]]) and a 1960s concrete box culvert can be viewed.\n\n===Goulburn===\n{{main|Goulburn}}\nAfter the cities of Liverpool and Campbelltown, [[Goulburn, New South Wales|Goulburn]] is the first major rural city along the Hume Highway from Sydney. It is the centre of a rich agricultural area specialising in fine wool production. From this area comes some of the world's finest [[wool]]. Therefore, the town has a monument called [[Big Merino|The Big Merino]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bigmerino.com.au/|title=The Big Merino|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-07-27}}</ref> near the service station. Goulburn was bypassed on 5 December 1992 and the main street (Auburn Street) is quieter, but still busy during Saturday morning shopping. Picturesque Belmore Park is located midway along Auburn Street. A number of architecturally and historically significant buildings are located near Belmore Park, including the courthouse, the post office and the railway station. Also in central Goulburn are two cathedrals, both of architectural note. A number of old houses and hotels are located near the railway station on Sloane Street.\n\n===Gunning===\n{{main|Gunning, New South Wales}}\n[[Gunning, New South Wales|Gunning's]] 19th century main street was built very wide, for the time of horse and bullock-drawn wagons. This served the town well when the main highway between Sydney and Melbourne carried cars and trucks through the town. This ceased when the bypass was completed on 5 April 1993. The town is now much quieter, and it has been able to resume a more rural pace of life. It has developed something of an industry in providing bed and breakfast accommodation. The recently built [[Gunning Wind Farm]] is located beside the highway, with its wind turbines providing a distinctive landmark.\n\n===Yass===\n{{main|Yass, New South Wales}}\n[[Yass, New South Wales|Yass]] has an historic [[Yass Valley Way|main street]], with well-preserved 19th century verandah-post pubs (mostly converted to other uses). It is popular with tourists, some from [[Canberra]] and others taking a break from the Hume Highway. Hamilton Hume's farm ''Cooma Cottage'' is located east of Yass, close to the intersection of the former routes of the Hume and Barton Highways. He lived there until his death in 1873. The Yass Bypass opened on 25 July 1994.\n\n===Bookham===\n{{main|Bookham, New South Wales}}\n[[Bookham, New South Wales|Bookham]] is situated {{convert|29|km}} west of Yass. The Hume Highway once passed through the village, but now bypasses it. This bypass was completed in two stages, the south stage opened on 18 February 1998 and the north stage opened on 11 July 2001.\n\n===Coolac===\n{{main|Coolac}}\n[[File:2 km from the Coolac - Cootamundra exit on the Hume Highway.jpg|thumb|Hume Highway near Coolac]]\nThe {{convert|11|km|adj=on}} section at [[Coolac, New South Wales|Coolac]] was the last two lane section of highway between Sydney and Gundagai until it was bypassed with a dual carriageway on 14 August 2009,<ref>{{Cite web |title=Coolac Bypass |work=Roads and Traffic Authority |publisher=Government of New South Wales |url=http://www.rta.nsw.gov.au/constructionmaintenance/majorconstructionprojectsregional/southwest/coolac/index.html |accessdate=25 August 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090918170506/http://www.rta.nsw.gov.au/constructionmaintenance/majorconstructionprojectsregional/southwest/coolac/index.html |archivedate=18 September 2009 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> after a delay due to indigenous heritage issues, the construction contract was awarded to [[Abigroup]] in February 2007.<ref>{{Cite news|title=More delays to highway bypass |work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]] |location=Australia |date=14 February 2006 |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/australia/nsw/riverina/200602/s1569224.htm |accessdate=5 March 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|title=Contract awarded to construct Coolac bypass |publisher=[[Government of Australia|Australian Government]] |date=1 March 2007 |url=http://www.ministers.dotars.gov.au/jl/releases/2007/March/L022_2007.htm |accessdate=2007-03-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070903183321/http://www.ministers.dotars.gov.au/jl/releases/2007/March/L022_2007.htm |archivedate=3 September 2007 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Gundagai===\n{{main|Gundagai}}\n[[File:Hume Highway.JPG|thumbnail|Hume Highway near Gundagai]]\nAt Snake Gully, adjacent to the highway north of Gundagai is the ''[[Dog on the Tuckerbox]]''. A statue (with a souvenir shop next door) was erected five miles (eight kilometres) from Gundagai. Snake Gully serves as a way station for many highway travellers.\n\nGundagai was bypassed on 25 March 1977 with the completion of the first Sheahan Bridge over the [[Murrumbidgee River]]. This bridge was the second longest road bridge in New South Wales (the [[Sydney Harbour Bridge]] being the longest), until the completion of the duplicate Sheahan Bridge on 17 May 2009,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rta.nsw.gov.au/constructionmaintenance/majorconstructionprojectsregional/southwest/sheahan/index.html |title=Sheahan Bridge duplication \u2013 NSW RTA, accessed 2009-06-13 |access-date=13 June 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090709083109/http://www.rta.nsw.gov.au/constructionmaintenance/majorconstructionprojectsregional/southwest/sheahan/index.html |archive-date=9 July 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> This is now the 4th longest road bridge in New South Wales - {{convert|1|m}} longer than the Sydney Harbour Bridge. The original Sheahan Bridge was only one lane in each direction.\n\nThe [[Prince Alfred Bridge]], on the old route of the highway across the Murrumbidgee floodplain, is of major engineering interest, as it is one of Australia's longest timber trestle bridges, as is the adjacent 1903 railway bridge. Gundagai was originally located on the river flats directly beside the Murrumbidgee River, but a disastrous flood in 1852 destroyed the town and drowned 89 people. The town was then relocated to its present position. A grade-separated interchange was completed at the intersection of the Highway and West Street in December 2006.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rta.nsw.gov.au/constructionmaintenance/majorconstructionprojectsregional/southwest/weststreet/index.html |title=Hume Highway West Street Interchange Gundagai \u2013 NSW RTA, accessed 2009-06-13 |access-date=17 May 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070830102038/http://www.rta.nsw.gov.au/constructionmaintenance/majorconstructionprojectsregional/southwest/weststreet/index.html |archive-date=30 August 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Tumblong===\n[[File:Hume Highway near the Sturt Highway turnoff.jpg|thumbnail|Near the [[Sturt Highway]] turnoff]]\nThe route of the highway between Tumblong and Tarcutta is the third route of the highway in this location. The original route led west from Tumblong along the Murrumbidgee River, before turning south over difficult country, crossing what is now the [[Sturt Highway]] and rejoining the current route of the highway as Lower Tarcutta Road. This was replaced in December 1938 by the first Tumblong deviation, to the east of the current route. The main features of this section of the highway were a deep, narrow cutting and the reinforced concrete bowstring arch bridge over Hillas Creek. This bridge has been preserved as it is one of only two bridges in New South Wales built to this design, and is visible on the western side of the highway close to the interchange with the [[Snowy Mountains Highway]]. The second and current deviation opened to traffic on 21 November 1983.\n\nApproximately {{convert|38|km}} southwest of Gundagai is the interchange with the [[Sturt Highway]], which leads to [[Wagga Wagga]], [[Mildura]] and [[Adelaide]].\n\n===Tarcutta===\n{{main|Tarcutta}}\n[[File:Tarcutta truckie memorial.jpg|thumb|National Truck Driver Memorial at Tarcutta]]\n[[Tarcutta, New South Wales|Tarcutta]] is located almost exactly halfway between Sydney and Melbourne and has been a popular stopover and change-over point for truck drivers making their way between the two cities. There is a memorial to truck drivers who have died on the local stretch of the Hume Highway. It was near Tarcutta that the final section of the Hume Highway was sealed in 1940. Construction began on a {{convert|7|km|adj=on}} bypass of Tarcutta in 2010. The bypass, which passes west of the town, was opened to traffic on 15 November 2011.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Tarcutta bypass |work=Roads and Traffic Authority |publisher=Government of New South Wales |date=2011-12-01 |url=http://www.rta.nsw.gov.au/roadprojects/projects/south_western_region/hume_hway_dup/tarcutta_bypass/index.html |accessdate=2011-12-08}}</ref> As improvements to the Hume Highway have reduced travelling time between Sydney and Melbourne to about nine hours driving time in good conditions, the town's importance to the average motorist has diminished.\n\n===Holbrook===\n{{main|Holbrook, New South Wales}}\n[[Holbrook, New South Wales|Holbrook]] was called Germanton until anti-German sentiment during [[World War 1]] led to the town and the shire being renamed in honour of the wartime submarine captain, [[Norman Douglas Holbrook|Lt Holbrook]] who was awarded the Victoria Cross. From 1995, a feature of the town has been a partial reconstruction of [[HMAS Otway (S-59)|HMAS ''Otway'']], an Oberon class submarine. This landmark was in recognition of the town's namesake's connections with submarines. Holbrook had the only set of [[traffic signal]]s (for [[pedestrians]]) that remained on the Hume Highway between the [[Sydney Orbital]] and [[Melbourne]]'s [[Western Ring Road]]. A bypass, that was officially opened by [[Prime Minister of Australia|Prime Minister]], [[Julia Gillard]] and [[Minister for Infrastructure and Transport (Australia)|Minister for Infrastructure and Transport]], [[Anthony Albanese]] on 23 June 2013, did not open for traffic until August 2013.<ref name=weeklytimes>{{cite news|title=PM opens Holbrook bypass|url=http://www.dailyadvertiser.com.au/story/1591144/gallery-holbrook-bypass-official-opening/|accessdate=16 July 2014|newspaper=The Weekly Times|date=26 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rms.nsw.gov.au/roadprojects/projects/south_western_region/hume_hway_dup/ |title=Completion of Hume Highway Duplication |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=23 April 2014 |website=Roads and Maritime Services |publisher=NSW Government |accessdate=16 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Woomargama===\n{{main|Woomargama}}\n[[Woomargama, New South Wales|Woomargama]], is a village between Holbrook and Albury which acts as a local service centre for a rich woolgrowing area. The {{convert|9|km|adj=on}} bypass of Woomargama was opened on 7 November 2011.<ref>{{Cite web| title = Woomargama bypass | work = | publisher = Roads and Maritime Services | date = 2011-12-01 | url = http://www.rta.nsw.gov.au/roadprojects/projects/south_western_region/hume_hway_dup/woomargama_bypass/index.html | accessdate = 2011-12-08}}</ref>\n\n===Table Top===\n{{main|Table Top, New South Wales{{!}}Table Top}}\n[[Table Top, New South Wales|Table Top]] is a small town located approximately {{convert|16|km}} north of Albury. The road was diverted a much longer route to the northwest to allow the construction of the [[Hume Dam]].\n\n===Albury-Wodonga===\n{{main|Albury|Wodonga}}\n[[File:Hume Freeway Albury 2008.jpg|thumb|The Hume Highway by-passing the Albury CBD.]]\n[[File:Hume Highway bypass in Albury 01.jpg|thumb|Hume Highway ramp at Albury]]\n[[File:Hume Freeway at Albury 1.JPG|thumbnail|Hume Highway from an overpass at Albury]]\n[[Albury]]'s history is linked with the two famous Australian explorers, [[Hamilton Hume]] and [[William Hovell]], as the city's location sprung from their crossing of the [[Murray River]]. Albury, commonly associated with its Victorian twin, [[Wodonga]], is one of the few rural Australian cities to experience a boom, mainly from industrialisation in recent times.\n\nThe Albury bypass, was first proposed in 1964 but only opened on 6 March 2007. Following a series of announcements and changes of plans through the 1990s, when Albury residents failed to agree on whether an 'internal' or 'external' bypass route was more appropriate, the 'internal bypass' option was chosen. Approval was granted in 2004 and construction, by [[Abigroup]],<ref>[http://www.rta.nsw.gov.au/constructionmaintenance/majorconstructionprojectsregional/southwest/alburybypass/ Albury Wodonga Hume Freeway project] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090908083928/http://www.rta.nsw.gov.au/constructionmaintenance/majorconstructionprojectsregional/southwest/alburybypass/ |date=8 September 2009}}</ref> began in January 2005. The route is parallel to and on the eastern side of the Sydney\u2013Melbourne railway, beginning at the railway overpass {{convert|10|km}} north of Albury. After crossing the Murray River, the bypass crosses the railway to rejoin the previous highway at the southern end of the Lincoln Causeway, connecting to the Wodonga bypass. The Albury bypass includes a freeway standard connection to the Murray Valley Highway at Bandiana, east of Wodonga.\n\n===Wangaratta===\n{{main|Wangaratta}}\n[[Wangaratta]] is, after Wodonga, the largest centre in northeast Victoria, with a population of approximately 17,000 at the {{CensusAU|2011}}.{{citation needed|date=January 2017}} Wangaratta is at the junction of the [[Great Alpine Road]]. Hume and Hovell passed through this area on their 1824 expedition and the town was founded in 1837 when the surrounding area was opened for farming. The town was bypassed in 1994.\n\nAttractions include Merriwa Park, a sunken garden adjacent to the King River, Airworld at Wangaratta Airport, and old goldfield areas of nearby [[Beechworth, Victoria|Beechworth]] and [[Chiltern, Victoria|Chiltern]].\n\n===Benalla===\n{{main|Benalla}}\n[[Benalla, Victoria|Benalla]] is a large town located just off the Hume Freeway between Melbourne and Wangaratta. Founded in 1848, growth was slow until a goldrush in the 1850s. It had many associations with the Kelly gang and the courthouse was the venue for a number of their trials. It also has a memorial to the Australian war hero [[Edward Dunlop|Sir Edward 'Weary' Dunlop]], an Australian doctor who acted as a leader to allied troops on the [[Burma Railway|Thailand-Burma Railway]] in [[World War II]].\n\n===Euroa===\n{{main|Euroa}}\n[[Euroa, Victoria|Euroa]] is famous for a [[Ned Kelly]] bank robbery. The town is located on the Seven Creeks and has pretty gardens and a number of attractive 19th century buildings.\n\n===Seymour===\n{{main|Seymour, Victoria{{!}}Seymour}}\nThe Hume Highway bypass of [[Seymour, Victoria|Seymour]] opened in December 1982. Seymour remains on the [[Goulburn Valley Highway|M39 Goulburn Valley Highway]]. The town is in the rich Goulburn Valley which supports the local vineyards. The large [[Puckapunyal]] military base is located west of Seymour. Once the centre of the bushranging area of Victoria, it has a museum which displays many period relics of that era. It was until the 1970s a major railway maintenance centre, and part of the railway workshops now houses a railway museum. The museum's collection of rolling stock, including State carriages used by governors and monarchs, is extensive.\n\n===Kalkallo===\n{{main|Kalkallo}}\nConstruction of the [[Donnybrook, Victoria|Donnybrook]] Road interchange, immediately to the north of the Craigieburn Bypass, replaced the dangerous<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.starnewsgroup.com.au/story/42353 |title=\"Fix for deadly\" \u2013 Star News Group \u2013 article, 22 May 2007 |access-date=22 May 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927051202/http://www.starnewsgroup.com.au/story/42353 |archive-date=27 September 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> at-grade intersection with (C723) at [[Kalkallo, Victoria|Kalkallo]] an overpass and entry/exit ramps in both directions, at a cost of $32 million. Works commenced in December 2007 and completion occurred in March 2009, three months ahead of schedule.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.vicroads.vic.gov.au/Home/RoadsAndProjects/RoadProjects/NothernSuburbs/Donnybrook+Road+Interchange.htm| title =Donnybrook Road Interchange Project|publisher = VicRoads |accessdate=8 June 2009}}</ref><!-- March isn't explicitly stated in link but is in the name of the ribbon cutting image. Meta info in the image shows 6 March 2009 -->\n\n===Craigieburn===\n{{main|Craigieburn, Victoria}}\n[[File:Hume Freeway Craigieburn Bypass.jpg|thumb|right|Craigieburn Bypass]]\nPrior to the opening of the [[Craigieburn, Victoria|Craigieburn]] Bypass in 2005, the Hume Highway skirted Craigieburn (the town centre was bypassed in the 1950s). The section of the Highway from Craigieburn to Campbellfield (on Melbourne's outskirts) was a significant bottleneck, with 12 sets of [[traffic signals]] in {{convert|17|km|adj=on}} section of road. The Craigieburn Bypass now links directly to the [[Western Ring Road]]/[[Metropolitan Ring Road]]. By 2013, the [[Old Hume Highway|Old Hume Highway (Sydney Road)]] section from Fawkner to Campbellfield was again becoming a bottleneck due to poor traffic signal coordination. There was some opposition for the bypass by several local governments in the northern suburbs of Melbourne, including the [[City of Darebin]] and the [[City of Moreland]], as well as local environmental groups. Their alternative proposal was rejected by the state government.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.dpc.vic.gov.au/domino/Web_Notes/MediaRelArc02.nsf/d025c300601da9dc4a25688e00143d49/8437be9e7baff83d4a256a1e007e2135!OpenDocument |title=BATCHELOR SLAMS COUNCILS OVER FLAWED RUSSELL REPORT |work=Department of Premier and Cabinet |publisher=Government of Victoria |date= |access-date=13 June 2009}}</ref> A pedestrian and [[cyclist]] cement path \u2013 the [[Craigieburn Bypass Trail|Galada Tamboore Pathway]] \u2013 runs the length of the bypass and connects with the Metropolitan Ring Road path, from where it is possible to connect to the [[Merri Creek Trail]], [[Western Ring Road Trail]], the City of Whittlesea Public Gardens and Edgars Road. The Craigieburn Bypass is shown in the [[1969 Melbourne Transportation Plan]] as part of the F2 Freeway corridor, which extended south along Merri Creek, Hoddle St, Barkly St in [[St Kilda, Victoria|St Kilda]], south through Elwood and Brighton, then east along South Road, connecting to the Dingley Freeway corridor.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Australian Roads|New South Wales|Australia}}\n* [[Old Hume Highway]]\n* [[Highways in Australia]]\n* [[List of highways in New South Wales|Highways in New South Wales]]\n* [[Highways in Victoria]]\n* [[Freeways in Australia]]\n* [[Freeways in Australia#Rural region|Freeways in New South Wales]]\n* [[Freeways in Australia#Rural region 2|Freeways in Victoria]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Bibliography==\n* {{cite book |author=Carroll, Brian |date=1983 |title=The Hume - Australia's highway of history |publisher=Kangaroo Press |isbn=0949924482}}\n* {{cite book |author=McGirr, Michael |date=2005 |title=Bypass: The Story of a road |isbn=9780330421904}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.rms.nsw.gov.au/documents/projects/south-western/hume-highway/history-begins-with-a-road.pdf |title=The Old Hume Highway \u2013 History begins with a road |work=[[Roads & Maritime Services]] |publisher=Government of New South Wales; Australian Government |date=May 2013 |access-date=}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Hume Highway}}\n{{Attached KML|display=inline, title}}\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=P2jtpkagg1I Driving the Hume Hwy \u2013 900km in 6 minutes \u2013 Youtube video]\n*[http://abc.net.au/news/stories/2007/11/14/2090695.htm?section=australia Hume Highway to receive $785m upgrade: Vaile]\n*[http://www.theage.com.au/news/National/Libs-to-finish-Hume-duplication-by-2012/2007/11/14/1194766735989.html Libs to finish Hume duplication by 2012]\n*[http://www.qbr.com.au/index.cfm?storyid=33385&cp=displaystory&type=s QBR (Queensland Business review) Coalition to complete duplication of Hume Highway by 2012]\n*[http://www.smh.com.au/news/National/ALP-to-fix-NSW-rural-transport-corridors/2007/11/12/1194766556144.html ALP to fix NSW rural transport corridors]\n*[http://www.smh.com.au/news/federal-election-2007-news/vaile-exhorts-colleagues-to-keep-up-the-fight-to-win/2007/11/14/1194766770508.html Vaile exhorts colleagues to keep up the fight to win]\n\n===Construction news===\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090918170506/http://www.rta.nsw.gov.au/constructionmaintenance/majorconstructionprojectsregional/southwest/coolac/index.