osed-circuit and pay-per-view events produced by the National Wrestling Alliance and World Championship Wrestling\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_NWA/WCW_closed-circuit_events_and_pay-per-view_events"}
{"title_page": "Vocational panel", "text_new": "A '''vocational panel''' ({{lang-ga|rolla gairm bheatha}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Olltoghch\u00e1n an tSeanaid, 2020 |url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/ga/election-results/seanad-general-election-2020/ |publisher=Oireachtas |accessdate=3 April 2020 |language=ga |date=3 April 2020 |quote=Foilseofar na tortha\u00ed comhairimh is d\u00e9ana\u00ed do na c\u00faig rolla gairm bheatha anseo d\u00edreach tar \u00e9is toradh gach comhairimh a fh\u00f3gairt.}}</ref>) is any of five lists of candidates from which are elected a total of 43 of the 60{{#tag:ref|Of the other 17 senators, 6 are elected from [[University constituency|university constituencies]] and [[Nominated members of Seanad \u00c9ireann|11 are appointed]] by the [[Taoiseach]] ([[prime minister]]).|group=\"n\"}} senators in [[Seanad \u00c9ireann]], the [[upper house]] of the [[Oireachtas]] ([[parliament]]) of [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]. Each panel corresponds to a grouping of \"interests and services\" ([[profession]]s or [[vocation]]s) of which candidates are required to have \"knowledge and practical experience\". The panels are nominated partly by Oireachtas members and partly by vocational organisations. From each panel, between five and eleven senators are [[Indirect election|elected indirectly]], by Oireachtas members and [[Local government in the Republic of Ireland|local councillors]], using the [[single transferable vote]]. The broad requirements are specified by Article 18 of the [[Constitution of Ireland]] and the implementation details by [[acts of the Oireachtas]], principally the Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947, and associated [[statutory instrument]]s.<ref>{{cite web |title=Commencement, Amendments, SIs made under the Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947 |url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/isbc/1947_42.html |website=Irish Statute Book |accessdate=3 April 2020 |date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Interests and services, and subpanels==\nArticle 18.7.1\u00b0 of the Constitution defines the five panels and specifies that each shall elect between five and eleven senators. The 1947 act defines the numbers of senators to be elected from each of the panels, and also provides for the division of each panel into two sub-panels: the nominating bodies sub-panel and the Oireachtas sub-panel, with a minimum number from each sub-panel.\t \n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: right;\"\n|+Senate vocational panels\n!rowspan=2|Panel\n!colspan=2|Senators\n!colspan=2|Nominating bodies (as of 2020)\n!rowspan=2 class=\"unsortable\"|\"Interests and services\" represented<ref>[http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1947/act/42/section/3/enacted/en/html#sec3 Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947 s.3]</ref>\n|-\n!Total  !!Min. per<br/>sub-panel\n!Number<ref>{{cite web |title=Register of Nominating Bodies as revised at the annual revision and signed by the Seanad Returning Officer in pursuance of section 19 of the Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947, as amended. |url=https://data.oireachtas.ie/ie/oireachtas/electoralProcess/nominatingBodies/seanad/2019/2019-07-24_register-of-nominating-bodies-2019_en.pdf |publisher=Oireachtas |accessdate=1 April 2020 |date=24 July 2019}}</ref> \n!Max nominees<br/>per body<ref>[http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1954/act/1/section/7/enacted/en/html s.26(2) of the 1947 act as amended by s.7 of the 1954 act]</ref>\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[Administrative Panel|Administrative]]\n| 7  || 3\n| 20 || 1\n|align=\"left\"| \"Public administration and social services, including voluntary social activities\"\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[Agricultural Panel|Agricultural]]\n| 11 || 4\n| 10 || 2\n|align=\"left\"| \"Agriculture and allied interests, and fisheries\"\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[Cultural and Educational Panel|Cultural and Educational]]\n| 5  || 2\n| 34 || 1 \n|align=\"left\"| \"The national language {{bracket|i.e. [[Irish language|Irish]]}} and culture, literature, art, education\" and \"such [[profession]]al interests as may be defined by law\", namely \"law\" and \"medicine, including surgery, dentistry, veterinary medicine, and pharmaceutical chemistry\"\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[Industrial and Commercial Panel|Industrial and Commercial]]\n| 9  || 3\n| 47 || 1\n|align=\"left\"| \"Industry and commerce, including banking, finance, accountancy, engineering, and architecture\"\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[Labour Panel|Labour]]\n| 11 || 4\n| 2  || 7\n|align=\"left\"| \"Labour, whether [[trade union|organised]] or unorganised\"\n|-class=\"sortbottom\"\n! Total\n| 43  || \u2014\n| 113 || \u2014 \n| \u2014\n|}\n\n==Nominations==\nCandidates must be Irish citizens over the age of 21.  They can be nominated by two methods: by Oireachtas members or by nominating bodies. Nominating bodies are organisations that are connected to the particular vocation; for example, the [[Irish Congress of Trade Unions]] (ICTU) can nominate in the Labour panel, and the [[Royal Irish Academy]] can nominate in the Cultural and Education panel.\n\nAs the electorate is restricted to elected councillors, [[Teachta D\u00e1la|TD]]s and senators, the political parties have a great influence in the nomination procedures. The main political parties are aware of how many seats they will win after the [[D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann|D\u00e1il]] election and will endorse candidates that they deem to have a chance of election to the D\u00e1il in the next general election. The nominating bodies tend to nominate party members. Even where non-party candidates get on the ballot paper, it is very rare that these candidates are successful.\n\n===Knowledge and practical experience===\nThere is no statutory definition of what constitutes a sufficient degree of \"knowledge and practical experience\" of an interest or service to be eligible for nomination to the relevant panel.<ref name=\"groves2018\">{{cite web |last1=Groves |first1=Martin |title=Third Meeting |nopp=y |url=https://assets.gov.ie/3593/301118151408-17c7dc50bc56471da257862ca08cdf67.pdf#page=5 |editor=Seanad Reform Implementation Group |accessdate=5 April 2020 |page=Appendix: Presentation |date=12 June 2018}}</ref> The question is decided by the [[clerk (legislature)|clerk]] of the Seanad, but may be be referred by him, or appealed by the candidate, to a judge of the [[High Court]] appointed as \"judicial referee\".<ref name=\"judicialreferee\">1947 act \u00a7\u00a736(2)(b)(ii), 38</ref> No further [[judicial review]] is permitted.<ref name=\"judicialreferee\"/> In 2018 clerk Martin Groves said that \"legislative guidelines would be of assistance to the returning officer and, I am sure, to candidates also\".<ref name=\"groves2018\"/> Before the [[Members of the 12th Seanad|1969 Seanad election]], outgoing Labour-panel senators [[John Ormonde]] and [[S\u00e9amus Dolan]] sought a pre-emptive High Court declaration that they were qualified, being members of a union, the [[Irish National Teachers' Organisation]] (INTO), which was itself affiliated to the ICTU.<ref name=\"it19690709\">{{cite news |title=Outgoing Senators Seek Declaration |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/archive/1969/0709/Pg011.html#Ar01100 |url-access=subscription |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=The Irish Times |date=9 July 1969 |page=11}}</ref> The Seanad clerk, Se\u00e1n MacGabhann, argued that as the INTO was itself a nominating body on the Cultural and Educational Panel, that was the panel on which they would be qualified.<ref name=\"it19690709\"/> Justice [[Denis Pringle]] ruling in favour the plaintiffs, stated that it did not matter if they were better qualified for a different panel, and that, as regards the Labour Panel, while merely being in a union was insufficient, a candidate did not require \"specialised\" knowledge, and the plaintiff's testimony had established their qualifications.<ref>{{cite news |title=Senators win in election action|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/archive/1969/0710/Pg007.html#Ar00704 |url-access=subscription |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=The Irish Times |date=10 July 1969 |page=7}}</ref><ref name=\"groves2018\"/> MacGabhann commented that, while an application form with detailed evidence similar to the plaintiffs' testimony might have satisfied him, a form simply making a bare assertion of knowledge and practical experience would not.<ref name=\"it19690709\"/> In 2014, [[Fine Gael]] minister [[Heather Humphreys]] nominated John McNulty to the board of the [[Irish Museum of Modern Art]] (IMMA) shortly before Fine Gael nominated him to [[Gerard Craughwell#John McNulty|a by-election]] on the Oireachtas subpanel of the Cultural and Educational Panel. The IMMA nomination was seen as an attempt to bolster McNulty's tenuous qualifications, and the ensuing controversy impelled him to withdraw his candidacy.{{#tag:ref|His name remained from the ballot paper, but he urged electors not to vote for him.<ref name=\"mcgee2014/>|group=\"n\"}}<ref name=\"mcgee2014\">{{cite news |last1=McGee |first1=Harry |title=Why is the John McNulty affair so important? |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/why-is-the-john-mcnulty-affair-so-important-1.1951624 |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=The Irish Times |date=4 October 2014 |language=en}}</ref> In the [[2020 Seanad election]], Paul Hayes was excluded from the Agricultural panel on the basis that, although he had the required \"knowledge\" of fishing, he lacked \"practical experience\"; Hayes suggested that with more time he could have supplied sufficient documentation to support his case.<ref>{{cite news |last1=O'Mahony |first1=Kieran |title=Hayes disappointed as Seanad nomination bids fail |url=https://www.southernstar.ie/news/hayes-disappointed-as-seanad-nomination-bids-fail-4202457 |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=The Southern Star |date=25 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===<!-- [[Completion of panels]] redirects here-->Completion of panels===\nThe \"completion of panels\" occurs in public on a specified date after nominations close, when the clerk of the Seanad, assisted by the judicial referee, excludes invalid nomination papers and unqualified nominees, and allows candidates nominated on multiple panels or subpanels to select which one to go forward on.<ref>{{cite web |title=Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947 s.36 |url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1947/act/42/section/36/enacted/en/html |website=electronic Irish Statute Book (eISB) |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> This creates a list of provisional subpanels. The minimum number of nominees for each subpanel is two plus the maximum number to be elected from the subpanel. If there are too few candidates on a provisional subpanel, the [[Taoiseach]] must nominate extra candidates to complete the panel.<ref>{{cite web |title=Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947 s.37 |url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1947/act/42/section/37/enacted/en/html |website=electronic Irish Statute Book (eISB) |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> In the [[21st Seanad|1997 Seanad election]], [[Bertie Ahern]] was obliged to nominate four candidates across three Oireachtas sub-panels, none of whom polled well in the ensuing election.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Coakley |first1=John |last2=Manning |first2=Maurice |editor-last1=Marsh |editor-first1=Michael |title=How Ireland Voted 1997 |chapter=The Senate Elections |date=2018 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-0-429-96854-9 |page=203 |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=mwDFDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA203 |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Whereas [[Nominated members of Seanad \u00c9ireann|appointed directly to the Seanad]] must be by a Taoiseach elected after a [[D\u00e1il election results|D\u00e1il general election]], nomination of candidates to complete a panel may be by an ''acting'' Taoiseach. For example, in 2020 [[Leo Varadkar]] was acting Taoiseach after [[2020 Irish general election|the D\u00e1il election]]; in [[2020 Irish Seanad election|the ensuing Seanad election]], Oireachtas members only nominated eight candidates to their subpanel of the Labour panel, so Varadkar nominated one more to bring the total up to the minimum of nine.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Panels of candidates prepared by the Seanad Returning Officer pursuant to Section 43 of the Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947, as amended by the Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1954. |journal=Iris Oifigi\u00fail |date=10 March 2020 |issue=20A [Supplement] |page=6 |url=https://data.oireachtas.ie/ie/oireachtas/electoralProcess/electoralRoll/seanad/2020/2020-03-10_seanad-general-election-2020-panels-of-candidates_en.pdf#page=6}}; {{cite news |last1=O'Halloran |first1=Marie |title=FG\u2019s Mary Seery Kearney added to ticket to contest Seanad election |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/fg-s-mary-seery-kearney-added-to-ticket-to-contest-seanad-election-1.4198771 |date=10 March 2020 |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=The Irish Times |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Voting==\nIn all panel elections [[postal voting]] is used. The [[clerk (legislature)|clerk]] of the Seanad is the [[returning officer]] of the count, during which each ballot is given the value of 1,000 to aid the transfer of fractions of votes. The [[electoral college]] is the same for all of the vocational panels but varies between general and [[by-election]]s. \n\nAt a Seanad general election the voters are members of [[Local government in the Republic of Ireland|city and county councils]], the newly elected D\u00e1il and the outgoing Seanad; {{as of|2020|lc=y}} these number 949, 160, and 60 respectively, discounting any vacancies.{{#tag:ref|Typically, some local councillors and members of the old Seanad will have just been elected to the new D\u00e1il, vacating their former seats. In the case of a senator appointed by a Taoiseach, the outgoing acting Taoiseach will nominate a replacement in time for the panel election.<ref>{{cite news |last1=O'Halloran |first1=Marie |title=Former Labour TDs to compete for Seanad seats Aodh\u00e1n \u00d3 Riord\u00e1in in competition with outgoing senators for nomination |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/oireachtas/former-labour-tds-to-compete-for-seanad-seats-1.2571697 |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=The Irish Times |date=14 March 2016 |page=2}}</ref> Typically, local councils likewise co-opt replacements in time,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Flaherty |first1=Rachel |title=Rush to fill vacant seats created by councillors elected to D\u00e1il |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/archive/2016/0314/Pg002.html#Ar00203 |url-access=subscription |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=The Irush Times |date=14 March 2016 |page=2}}</ref> but no by-elections are held to replace outgoing panel or university senators.|group=\"n\"}} At a by-election the voters are the current members of the D\u00e1il and Seanad.<ref>1947 act [http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1954/act/1/section/11/enacted/en/html s.58A(8) inserted by s.11 of 1954 act], and [http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1947/act/42/section/69/enacted/en/html#sec69 s.69]</ref>\n\nAt a general election each panel is elected separately, the ballot listing nominees from both subpanels collated together in alphabetical order of surname. Voting is by the [[single transferable vote]] (STV), with the modification that a minimum number from each subpanel must be elected.\n\nBy-elections to fill a casual vacancy use [[instant runoff voting]]; if there are multiple vacancies on the same subpanel, separate parallel by-elections are held instead of a single multiple-seat STV by-election.<ref>1947 act s.58</ref> By-election nominations are from the same subpanel as the departed senator; no body can nominate multiple candidates.<ref>1947 act [http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1954/act/1/section/11/enacted/en/html s.58A(1)(b) inserted by s.11 of 1954 act]</ref> A by-election must be called within 180 days of a vacancy arising.<ref>[http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1947/act/42/section/56/enacted/en/html Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947 s.56(1)]</ref>\n\n==Influence==\nIn practice, the vocational element is largely notional.<ref name=\"Coakley2011\"/> Seanad standing orders make no distinction between senators elected from a panel and other senators, or among different panels.<ref>{{cite web |title=Standing Orders relative to Public Business |url=https://data.oireachtas.ie/ie/oireachtas/parliamentaryBusiness/standingOrders/seanad/2017/2017-09-29_seanad-eireann-standing-orders-relative-to-public-business-2017_en.pdf |publisher=Seanad \u00c9ireann |accessdate=3 April 2020 |date=2017}}</ref> For example, of the four senators on the Oireachtas joint committee on Agriculture, Food and the Marine in 2017, only one had been elected from the Agricultural Panel; two were from other panels, while the fourth was a Taoiseach's appointee.<ref>{{cite press release |title=Agriculture Committee to discuss tillage and malt industries |url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/press-centre/press-releases/20171016-agriculture-committee-to-discuss-tillage-and-malt-industries/ |website=www.oireachtas.ie |publisher=Oireachtas |accessdate=3 April 2020 |language=en-ie |date=16 October 2017}}; {{cite web |title=Names Of The Members Nominated And Of The Members Elected |url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/debates/debate/seanad/2016-06-08/5/ |website=Seanad \u00c9ireann (25th Seanad) debates |publisher=Oireachtas |accessdate=3 April 2020 |language=en-ie |date=8 June 2016}}</ref> The fact that the electorate is composed mainly of officials elected in party-political elections means the candidates they favour are also party-political rather than vocationally oriented.<ref name=\"Murphy2016\">{{cite book |last1=Murphy |first1=Mary C. |editor1-last=Gallagher |editor1-first=Michael |editor2-last=Marsh |editor2-first=Michael |title=How Ireland Voted 2016: The Election that Nobody Won |date=2016 |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |isbn=9783319408880 |pages=227\u2013253 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DKVlDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA227  |chapter=The Seanad Election: Second Chamber, Second Chance |doi=10.1007/978-3-319-40889-7_10}}</ref> Candidates from the \"outside\" (nominating bodies) panel tend to win the minimum number of seats on each panel; those elected are also mainly party based.<ref name=\"Murphy2016\"/> Since the [[Post-2008 Irish economic downturn|2008 recession]] there has been an increased proportion of [[independent politician]]s elected at local and D\u00e1il elections, which in turn has led to some independent senators returned from the panel elections;<ref name=\"Murphy2016\"/> some but not all of these have a greater focus on the functional areas of their panel.\n\n==History==\nThe vocational aspect of the Seanad's constitution was a reflection of the influence of [[corporatism]] on [[Catholic social teaching]] of the 1930s, as outlined in the encyclical ''[[Quadragesimo anno]]''. This in turn influenced [[\u00c9amon de Valera]]'s thinking during the [[Adoption of the Constitution of Ireland|drafting of the 1937 Constitution]].<ref name=\"odonoghue2019\">{{cite book |first1=Martin |last1=O'Donoghue |title=Reforming Senates: Upper Legislative Houses in North Atlantic Small Powers 1800\u2013present |date=2019 |publisher=Routledge |location=London |series=Routledge Studies in Modern History |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2fS2DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT212 |isbn=9780367339685 |pages=204\u2013214 |chapter=Vocational voices or puppets of the Lower House? Irish senators, 1938-1948.}}</ref> The place of the Seanad in the new constitution was first discussed by a 1936 commission, which produced a majority and minority report, with dissenters from both.<ref name=\"odonoghue2019\"/>\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|+1936 Second House of the Oireachtas Commission recommendations<ref name=\"DL056798\">{{cite book |url=http://opac.oireachtas.ie/AWData/Library3/Library2/DL056798.pdf#page=11 |author=Second House of the Oireachtas Commission |date=November 1936 |series=Official publications |volume=P.2475 |title=Report |nopp=y |pages=Chapter III [majority report] pp.9\u201311, \u00a7\u00a717, 21\u201325; Chapter X [minority report] pp.30\u201333, \u00a7\u00a714\u201317 |location=Dublin |publisher=Stationery Office |oclc=863521464}}</ref>\n|-\n! Report \n! Fraction elected \n! Sectors of interest\n! Candidates nominated by\n! Electors\n|-\n! Majority\n| 30 of 45\n| \"National Language and Culture, the Arts, Agriculture (in all its forms) and Fisheries, Industry and Commerce, Finance, Health and Social Welfare, Foreign Affairs, Education, Law, Labour, Public Administration (including Town and Country Planning).\"\n| A committee (not necessarily [[Teachta D\u00e1la|TD]]s) elected by TDs using proportional representation\n| D\u00e1il election candidates, [[Weighted voting|weighted]] by first-preference vote\n|-\n! Minority\n| 40 of 50\n| \"(1) Farming and Fisheries, (2) Labour, (3) Industry and Commerce, (4) Education and the learned Professions.\"\n| Largely by specified functional organisations; partly by the relevant government minister.\n| D\u00e1il members\n|}\n\nDe Valera's 1937 Seanad took more from the minority report.<ref name=\"odonoghue2019\"/> The original electoral method differed in several ways from that used since 1947:<ref name=\"Byrne2013\">{{cite web |last1=Byrne |first1=Elaine |title=Past Reforms and Present Policy: examining the Seanad Electoral(Panel Members) Act, 1947 |url=http://historyhub.ie/past-reforms-present-policy |website=History Hub |publisher=University College Dublin |accessdate=31 March 2020 |date=2013}}</ref>\n* There was a single STV ballot paper listing all candidates for all panels in order of surname.<ref>[http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1937/act/43/section/40/enacted/en/html#sec40 Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1937 s.40(1)]</ref> The requirement for specific numbers of winners from each of five panels (and ten sub-panels) was preserved, greatly complicating the task for voters filling in the large ballot, and for eliminating candidates during the STV count process.\n* Instead of all county councillors voting directly for the panel, each council elected seven of its members to act as \"electors\".<ref>[http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1937/act/43/section/37/enacted/en/html#sec37 Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1937 s.37]</ref>\n\nFor the [[Members of the 2nd Seanad|April 1938 Seanad election]], there were only 330 voters (24 of the 354 electors boycotted) which in a 43-seat ballot gave a quota of just eight votes to be elected.<ref name=\"Byrne2013\"/> There were rumours of [[vote buying]] after the first three Seanad election and finally two convictions after the [[Members of the 5th Seanad|1944 Seanad election]].<ref name=\"Byrne2013\"/> The Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1937 was therefore repealed and replaced by the Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947, which is still in force with minor amendments.<ref name=\"Byrne2013\"/>\n\n==Reform proposals==\nSeanad reform proposals may be divided into those requiring [[Amendments to the Constitution of Ireland|amending the Constitution of Ireland]] via [[referendum]], and those limited to amendment of statute law within the existing constitutional parameters. Those in the former group typically suggest abolishing the vocational aspect of the Seanad as ineffectual and based on outdated political thinking.<ref name=\"Coakley2011\">{{cite book |chapter-url=http://www.nui.ie/elections/referendum/docs/ck1y_arCl3.pdf#page=4 |chapter=The Final Seanad Election? |page=243 |first=John |last=Coakley |editor1-last=Gallagher |editor1-first=Michael |editor2-last=Marsh |editor2-first=Michael |title=How Ireland Voted 2011:  The Full Story of Ireland's Earthquake Election |date=2011 |isbn=978-0-230-34881-3 |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |accessdate=6 April 2020 |quote=These three reports acknowledged the impossibility of giving effect to any meaningful form of vocational representation }}</ref> Those in the latter group typically suggest altering the nomination process and the franchise; both the 2015 [[Maurice Manning|Manning]] report and the 2018 report of the Seanad Reform Implementation Group recommended that 13 panel senators continue to be elected on the current limited franchise, and the other 30 be popularly elected: all citizens over 18 could register for one of the five panels or one of the university constituencies.<ref>{{cite book |author1=Seanad Reform Implementation Group |title=Report of the Seanad Reform Implementation Group |date=December 2018 |url=https://assets.gov.ie/5245/211218143426-25949b1b57ce47d5aff3eb83402fb99e.pdf#page=8 |accessdate=6 April 2020 |chapter=5. Recommendations of the Implementation Group}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[1969 French constitutional referendum]] \u2014 rejected proposal to merge the [[French Economic, Social and Environmental Council|Economic, Social and Environmental Council]] into the [[Senate (France)|Senate]]\n* [[Functional constituency]] \u2014 in Hong Kong and Macao\n\n==References==\n===Footnotes===\n{{reflist|group=\"n\"}}\n\n===Sources===\n* {{cite web |title=Constitution of Ireland |pages=Articles 18\u201319 |nopp=y |url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/cons/en/html#article18 |website=electronic Irish Statute Book (eISB) |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}\n* {{cite web |title=Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947  |url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1947/act/42/enacted/en/index.html |website=electronic Irish Statute Book (eISB) |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}\n* {{cite web |title=Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1954 |url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1954/act/1/enacted/en/html |website=electronic Irish Statute Book (eISB) |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/publications/?author=seanad-eireann&topic%5B0%5D=election-results&topic%5B1%5D=elections Seanad election details since 2002], Oireachtas website\n\n{{Seanad \u00c9ireann}}\n\n[[Category:Seanad constituencies]]\n[[Category:Corporatism]]\n[[Category:Local authorities in the Republic of Ireland]]\n", "text_old": "A '''vocational panel''' ({{lang-ga|rolla gairm bheatha}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Olltoghch\u00e1n an tSeanaid, 2020 |url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/ga/election-results/seanad-general-election-2020/ |publisher=Oireachtas |accessdate=3 April 2020 |language=ga |date=3 April 2020 |quote=Foilseofar na tortha\u00ed comhairimh is d\u00e9ana\u00ed do na c\u00faig rolla gairm bheatha anseo d\u00edreach tar \u00e9is toradh gach comhairimh a fh\u00f3gairt.}}</ref>) is any of five lists of candidates from which are elected a total of 43 of the 60{{#tag:ref|Of the other 17 senators, 6 are elected from [[University constituency|university constituencies]] and [[Nominated members of Seanad \u00c9ireann|11 are appointed]] by the [[Taoiseach]] ([[prime minister]]).|group=\"n\"}} senators in [[Seanad \u00c9ireann]], the [[upper house]] of the [[Oireachtas]] ([[parliament]]) of [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]. Each panel corresponds to a grouping of \"interests and services\" ([[profession]]s or [[vocation]]s) of which candidates are required to have \"knowledge and practical experience\". The panels are nominated partly by Oireachtas members and partly by vocational organisations. From each panel, between five and eleven senators are [[Indirect election|elected indirectly]], by Oireachtas members and [[Local government in the Republic of Ireland|local councillors]], using the [[single transferable vote]]. The broad requirements are specified by Article 18 of the [[Constitution of Ireland]] and the implementation details by [[acts of the Oireachtas]], principally the Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947, and associated [[statutory instrument]]s.<ref>{{cite web |title=Commencement, Amendments, SIs made under the Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947 |url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/isbc/1947_42.html |website=Irish Statute Book |accessdate=3 April 2020 |date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Interests and services, and subpanels==\nArticle 18.7.1\u00b0 of the Constitution defines the five panels and specifies that each shall elect between five and eleven senators. The 1947 Act defines the numbers of senators to be elected from each of the panels, and also provides for the division of each panel into two sub-panels: the nominating bodies sub-panel and the Oireachtas sub-panel, with a minimum number from each sub-panel.\t \n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: right;\"\n|+Senate vocational panels\n!rowspan=2|Panel\n!colspan=2|Senators\n!colspan=2|Nominating bodies (as of 2020)\n!rowspan=2 class=\"unsortable\"|\"Interests and services\" represented<ref>[http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1947/act/42/section/3/enacted/en/html#sec3 Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947 s.3]</ref>\n|-\n!Total  !!Min. per<br/>sub-panel\n!Number<ref>{{cite web |title=Register of Nominating Bodies as revised at the annual revision and signed by the Seanad Returning Officer in pursuance of section 19 of the Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947, as amended. |url=https://data.oireachtas.ie/ie/oireachtas/electoralProcess/nominatingBodies/seanad/2019/2019-07-24_register-of-nominating-bodies-2019_en.pdf |publisher=Oireachtas |accessdate=1 April 2020 |date=24 July 2019}}</ref> \n!Max nominees<br/>per body<ref>[http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1954/act/1/section/7/enacted/en/html s.26(2) of the 1947 act as amended by s.7 of the 1954 act]</ref>\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[Administrative Panel|Administrative]]\n| 7  || 3\n| 20 || 1\n|align=\"left\"| \"Public administration and social services, including voluntary social activities\"\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[Agricultural Panel|Agricultural]]\n| 11 || 4\n| 10 || 2\n|align=\"left\"| \"Agriculture and allied interests, and fisheries\"\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[Cultural and Educational Panel|Cultural and Educational]]\n| 5  || 2\n| 34 || 1 \n|align=\"left\"| \"The national language {{bracket|i.e. [[Irish language|Irish]]}} and culture, literature, art, education\" and \"such [[profession]]al interests as may be defined by law\", namely \"law\" and \"medicine, including surgery, dentistry, veterinary medicine, and pharmaceutical chemistry\"\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[Industrial and Commercial Panel|Industrial and Commercial]]\n| 9  || 3\n| 47 || 1\n|align=\"left\"| \"Industry and commerce, including banking, finance, accountancy, engineering, and architecture\"\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[Labour Panel|Labour]]\n| 11 || 4\n| 2  || 7\n|align=\"left\"| \"Labour, whether [[trade union|organised]] or unorganised\"\n|-class=\"sortbottom\"\n! Total\n| 43  || \u2014\n| 113 || \u2014 \n| \u2014\n|}\n\n==Nominations==\nCandidates must be Irish citizens over the age of 21.  They can be nominated by two methods: by Oireachtas members or by nominating bodies. Nominating bodies are organisations that are connected to the particular vocation; for example, the [[Irish Congress of Trade Unions]] (ICTU) can nominate in the Labour panel, and the [[Royal Irish Academy]] can nominate in the Cultural and Education panel.\n\nAs the electorate is restricted to elected councillors, [[Teachta D\u00e1la|TD]]s and senators, the political parties have a great influence in the nomination procedures. The main political parties are aware of how many seats they will win after the [[D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann|D\u00e1il]] election and will endorse candidates that they deem to have a chance of election to the D\u00e1il in the next general election. The nominating bodies tend to nominate party members. Even where non-party candidates get on the ballot paper, it is very rare that these candidates are successful.\n\n===Knowledge and practical experience===\nThere is no statutory definition of what constitutes a sufficient degree of \"knowledge and practical experience\" of an interest or service to be eligible for nomination to the relevant panel.<ref name=\"groves2018\">{{cite web |last1=Groves |first1=Martin |title=Third Meeting |nopp=y |url=https://assets.gov.ie/3593/301118151408-17c7dc50bc56471da257862ca08cdf67.pdf#page=5 |editor=Seanad Reform Implementation Group |accessdate=5 April 2020 |page=Appendix: Presentation |date=12 June 2018}}</ref> The question is decided by the [[clerk (legislature)|clerk]] of the Seanad, but may be be referred by him, or appealed by the candidate, to a judge of the [[High Court]] appointed as \"judicial referee\".<ref name=\"judicialreferee\">1947 act \u00a7\u00a736(2)(b)(ii), 38</ref> No further [[judicial review]] is permitted.<ref name=\"judicialreferee\"/> In 2018 clerk Martin Groves said that \"legislative guidelines would be of assistance to the returning officer and, I am sure, to candidates also\".<ref name=\"groves2018\"/> Before the [[Members of the 12th Seanad|1969 Seanad election]], outgoing Labour-panel senators [[John Ormonde]] and [[S\u00e9amus Dolan]] sought a pre-emptive High Court declaration that they were qualified, being members of a union, the [[Irish National Teachers' Organisation]] (INTO), which was itself affiliated to the ICTU.<ref name=\"it19690709\">{{cite news |title=Outgoing Senators Seek Declaration |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/archive/1969/0709/Pg011.html#Ar01100 |url-access=subscription |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=The Irish Times |date=9 July 1969 |page=11}}</ref> The Seanad clerk, Se\u00e1n MacGabhann, argued that as the INTO was itself a nominating body on the Cultural and Educational Panel, that was the panel on which they would be qualified.<ref name=\"it19690709\"/> Justice [[Denis Pringle]] ruling in favour the plaintiffs, stated that it did not matter if they were better qualified for a different panel, and that, as regards the Labour Panel, while merely being in a union was insufficient, a candidate did not require \"specialised\" knowledge, and the plaintiff's testimony had established their qualifications.<ref>{{cite news |title=Senators win in election action|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/archive/1969/0710/Pg007.html#Ar00704 |url-access=subscription |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=The Irish Times |date=10 July 1969 |page=7}}</ref><ref name=\"groves2018\"/> MacGabhann commented that, while an application form with detailed evidence similar to the plaintiffs' testimony might have satisfied him, a form simply making a bare assertion of knowledge and practical experience would not.<ref name=\"it19690709\"/> In 2014, [[Fine Gael]] minister [[Heather Humphreys]] nominated John McNulty to the board of the [[Irish Museum of Modern Art]] (IMMA) shortly before Fine Gael nominated him to [[Gerard Craughwell#John McNulty|a by-election]] on the Oireachtas subpanel of the Cultural and Educational Panel. The IMMA nomination was seen as an attempt to bolster McNulty's tenuous qualifications, and the ensuing controversy impelled him to withdraw his candidacy.{{#tag:ref|His name remained from the ballot paper, but he urged electors not to vote for him.<ref name=\"mcgee2014/>|group=\"n\"}}<ref name=\"mcgee2014\">{{cite news |last1=McGee |first1=Harry |title=Why is the John McNulty affair so important? |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/why-is-the-john-mcnulty-affair-so-important-1.1951624 |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=The Irish Times |date=4 October 2014 |language=en}}</ref> In the [[2020 Seanad election]], Paul Hayes was excluded from the Agricultural panel on the basis that, although he had the required \"knowledge\" of fishing, he lacked \"practical experience\"; Hayes suggested that with more time he could have supplied sufficient documentation to support his case.<ref>{{cite news |last1=O'Mahony |first1=Kieran |title=Hayes disappointed as Seanad nomination bids fail |url=https://www.southernstar.ie/news/hayes-disappointed-as-seanad-nomination-bids-fail-4202457 |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=The Southern Star |date=25 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===<!-- [[Completion of panels]] redirects here-->Completion of panels===\nThe \"completion of panels\" occurs in public on a specified date after nominations close, when the clerk of the Seanad, assisted by the judicial referee, excludes invalid nomination papers and unqualified nominees, and allows candidates nominated on multiple panels or subpanels to select which one to go forward on.<ref>{{cite web |title=Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947 s.36 |url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1947/act/42/section/36/enacted/en/html |website=electronic Irish Statute Book (eISB) |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> This creates a list of provisional subpanels. The minimum number of nominees for each subpanel is two plus the maximum number to be elected from the subpanel. If there are too few candidates on a provisional subpanel, the [[Taoiseach]] must nominate extra candidates to complete the panel.<ref>{{cite web |title=Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947 s.37 |url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1947/act/42/section/37/enacted/en/html |website=electronic Irish Statute Book (eISB) |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> In the [[21st Seanad|1997 Seanad election]], [[Bertie Ahern]] was obliged to nominate four candidates across three Oireachtas sub-panels, none of whom polled well in the ensuing election.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Coakley |first1=John |last2=Manning |first2=Maurice |editor-last1=Marsh |editor-first1=Michael |title=How Ireland Voted 1997 |chapter=The Senate Elections |date=2018 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-0-429-96854-9 |page=203 |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=mwDFDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA203 |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Whereas [[Nominated members of Seanad \u00c9ireann|appointed directly to the Seanad]] must be by a Taoiseach elected after a [[D\u00e1il election results|D\u00e1il general election]], nomination of candidates to complete a panel may be by an ''acting'' Taoiseach. For example, in 2020 [[Leo Varadkar]] was acting Taoiseach after [[2020 Irish general election|the D\u00e1il election]]; in [[2020 Irish Seanad election|the ensuing Seanad election]], Oireachtas members only nominated eight candidates to their subpanel of the Labour panel, so Varadkar nominated one more to bring the total up to the minimum of nine.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Panels of candidates prepared by the Seanad Returning Officer pursuant to Section 43 of the Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947, as amended by the Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1954. |journal=Iris Oifigi\u00fail |date=10 March 2020 |issue=20A [Supplement] |page=6 |url=https://data.oireachtas.ie/ie/oireachtas/electoralProcess/electoralRoll/seanad/2020/2020-03-10_seanad-general-election-2020-panels-of-candidates_en.pdf#page=6}}; {{cite news |last1=O'Halloran |first1=Marie |title=FG\u2019s Mary Seery Kearney added to ticket to contest Seanad election |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/fg-s-mary-seery-kearney-added-to-ticket-to-contest-seanad-election-1.4198771 |date=10 March 2020 |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=The Irish Times |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Voting==\nIn all panel elections [[postal voting]] is used. The [[clerk (legislature)|clerk]] of the Seanad is the [[returning officer]] of the count, during which each ballot is given the value of 1,000 to aid the transfer of fractions of votes. The [[electoral college]] is the same for all of the vocational panels but varies between general and [[by-election]]s. \n\nAt a Seanad general election the voters are members of [[Local government in the Republic of Ireland|city and county councils]], the newly elected D\u00e1il and the outgoing Seanad; {{as of|2020|lc=y}} these number 949, 160, and 60 respectively, discounting any vacancies.{{#tag:ref|Typically, some local councillors and members of the old Seanad will have just been elected to the new D\u00e1il, vacating their former seats. In the case of a senator appointed by a Taoiseach, the outgoing acting Taoiseach will nominate a replacement in time for the panel election.<ref>{{cite news |last1=O'Halloran |first1=Marie |title=Former Labour TDs to compete for Seanad seats Aodh\u00e1n \u00d3 Riord\u00e1in in competition with outgoing senators for nomination |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/oireachtas/former-labour-tds-to-compete-for-seanad-seats-1.2571697 |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=The Irish Times |date=14 March 2016 |page=2}}</ref> Typically, local councils likewise co-opt replacements in time,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Flaherty |first1=Rachel |title=Rush to fill vacant seats created by councillors elected to D\u00e1il |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/archive/2016/0314/Pg002.html#Ar00203 |url-access=subscription |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=The Irush Times |date=14 March 2016 |page=2}}</ref> but no by-elections are held to replace outgoing panel or university senators.|group=\"n\"}} At a by-election the voters are the current members of the D\u00e1il and Seanad.<ref>1947 act [http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1954/act/1/section/11/enacted/en/html s.58A(8) inserted by s.11 of 1954 act], and [http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1947/act/42/section/69/enacted/en/html#sec69 s.69]</ref>\n\nAt a general election each panel is elected separately, the ballot listing nominees from both subpanels collated together in alphabetical order of surname. Voting is by the [[single transferable vote]] (STV), with the modification that a minimum number from each subpanel must be elected.\n\nBy-elections to fill a casual vacancy use [[instant runoff voting]]; if there are multiple vacancies on the same subpanel, separate parallel by-elections are held instead of a single multiple-seat STV by-election.<ref>1947 act s.58</ref> By-election nominations are from the same subpanel as the departed senator; no body can nominate multiple candidates.<ref>1947 act [http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1954/act/1/section/11/enacted/en/html s.58A(1)(b) inserted by s.11 of 1954 act]</ref> A by-election must be called within 180 days of a vacancy arising.<ref>[http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1947/act/42/section/56/enacted/en/html Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947 s.56(1)]</ref>\n\n==Influence==\nIn practice, the vocational element is largely notional.<ref name=\"Coakley2011\"/> Seanad standing orders make no distinction between senators elected from a panel and other senators, or among different panels.<ref>{{cite web |title=Standing Orders relative to Public Business |url=https://data.oireachtas.ie/ie/oireachtas/parliamentaryBusiness/standingOrders/seanad/2017/2017-09-29_seanad-eireann-standing-orders-relative-to-public-business-2017_en.pdf |publisher=Seanad \u00c9ireann |accessdate=3 April 2020 |date=2017}}</ref> For example, of the four senators on the Oireachtas joint committee on Agriculture, Food and the Marine in 2017, only one had been elected from the Agricultural Panel; two were from other panels, while the fourth was a Taoiseach's appointee.<ref>{{cite press release |title=Agriculture Committee to discuss tillage and malt industries |url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/press-centre/press-releases/20171016-agriculture-committee-to-discuss-tillage-and-malt-industries/ |website=www.oireachtas.ie |publisher=Oireachtas |accessdate=3 April 2020 |language=en-ie |date=16 October 2017}}; {{cite web |title=Names Of The Members Nominated And Of The Members Elected |url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/debates/debate/seanad/2016-06-08/5/ |website=Seanad \u00c9ireann (25th Seanad) debates |publisher=Oireachtas |accessdate=3 April 2020 |language=en-ie |date=8 June 2016}}</ref> The fact that the electorate is composed mainly of officials elected in party-political elections means the candidates they favour are also party-political rather than vocationally oriented.<ref name=\"Murphy2016\">{{cite book |last1=Murphy |first1=Mary C. |editor1-last=Gallagher |editor1-first=Michael |editor2-last=Marsh |editor2-first=Michael |title=How Ireland Voted 2016: The Election that Nobody Won |date=2016 |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |isbn=9783319408880 |pages=227\u2013253 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DKVlDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA227  |chapter=The Seanad Election: Second Chamber, Second Chance |doi=10.1007/978-3-319-40889-7_10}}</ref> Candidates from the \"outside\" (nominating bodies) panel tend to win the minimum number of seats on each panel; those elected are also mainly party based.<ref name=\"Murphy2016\"/> Since the [[Post-2008 Irish economic downturn|2008 recession]] there has been an increased proportion of [[independent politician]]s elected at local and D\u00e1il elections, which in turn has led to some independent senators returned from the panel elections;<ref name=\"Murphy2016\"/> some but not all of these have a greater focus on the functional areas of their panel.\n\n==History==\nThe vocational aspect of the Seanad's constitution was a reflection of the influence of [[corporatism]] on [[Catholic social teaching]] of the 1930s, as outlined in the encyclical ''[[Quadragesimo anno]]''. This in turn influenced [[\u00c9amon de Valera]]'s thinking during the [[Adoption of the Constitution of Ireland|drafting of the 1937 Constitution]].<ref name=\"odonoghue2019\">{{cite book |first1=Martin |last1=O'Donoghue |title=Reforming Senates: Upper Legislative Houses in North Atlantic Small Powers 1800\u2013present |date=2019 |publisher=Routledge |location=London |series=Routledge Studies in Modern History |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2fS2DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT212 |isbn=9780367339685 |pages=204\u2013214 |chapter=Vocational voices or puppets of the Lower House? Irish senators, 1938-1948.}}</ref> The place of the Seanad in the new constitution was first discussed by a 1936 commission, which produced a majority and minority report, with dissenters from both.<ref name=\"odonoghue2019\"/>\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|+1936 Second House of the Oireachtas Commission recommendations<ref name=\"DL056798\">{{cite book |url=http://opac.oireachtas.ie/AWData/Library3/Library2/DL056798.pdf#page=11 |author=Second House of the Oireachtas Commission |date=November 1936 |series=Official publications |volume=P.2475 |title=Report |nopp=y |pages=Chapter III [majority report] pp.9\u201311, \u00a7\u00a717, 21\u201325; Chapter X [minority report] pp.30\u201333, \u00a7\u00a714\u201317 |location=Dublin |publisher=Stationery Office |oclc=863521464}}</ref>\n|-\n! Report \n! Fraction elected \n! Sectors of interest\n! Candidates nominated by\n! Electors\n|-\n! Majority\n| 30 of 45\n| \"National Language and Culture, the Arts, Agriculture (in all its forms) and Fisheries, Industry and Commerce, Finance, Health and Social Welfare, Foreign Affairs, Education, Law, Labour, Public Administration (including Town and Country Planning).\"\n| A committee (not necessarily [[Teachta D\u00e1la|TD]]s) elected by TDs using proportional representation\n| D\u00e1il election candidates, [[Weighted voting|weighted]] by first-preference vote\n|-\n! Minority\n| 40 of 50\n| \"(1) Farming and Fisheries, (2) Labour, (3) Industry and Commerce, (4) Education and the learned Professions.\"\n| Largely by specified functional organisations; partly by the relevant government minister.\n| D\u00e1il members\n|}\n\nDe Valera's 1937 Seanad took more from the minority report.<ref name=\"odonoghue2019\"/> The original electoral method differed in several ways from that used since 1947:<ref name=\"Byrne2013\">{{cite web |last1=Byrne |first1=Elaine |title=Past Reforms and Present Policy: examining the Seanad Electoral(Panel Members) Act, 1947 |url=http://historyhub.ie/past-reforms-present-policy |website=History Hub |publisher=University College Dublin |accessdate=31 March 2020 |date=2013}}</ref>\n* There was a single STV ballot paper listing all candidates for all panels in order of surname.<ref>[http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1937/act/43/section/40/enacted/en/html#sec40 Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1937 s.40(1)]</ref> The requirement for specific numbers of winners from each of five panels (and ten sub-panels) was preserved, greatly complicating the task for voters filling in the large ballot, and for eliminating candidates during the STV count process.\n* Instead of all county councillors voting directly for the panel, each council elected seven of its members to act as \"electors\".<ref>[http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1937/act/43/section/37/enacted/en/html#sec37 Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1937 s.37]</ref>\n\nFor the [[Members of the 2nd Seanad|April 1938 Seanad election]], there were only 330 voters (24 of the 354 electors boycotted) which in a 43-seat ballot gave a quota of just eight votes to be elected.<ref name=\"Byrne2013\"/> There were rumours of [[vote buying]] after the first three Seanad election and finally two convictions after the [[Members of the 5th Seanad|1944 Seanad election]].<ref name=\"Byrne2013\"/> The Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1937 was therefore repealed and replaced by the Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947, which is still in force with minor amendments.<ref name=\"Byrne2013\"/>\n\n==Reform proposals==\nSeanad reform proposals may be divided into those requiring [[Amendments to the Constitution of Ireland|amending the Constitution of Ireland]] via [[referendum]], and those limited to amendment of statute law within the existing constitutional parameters. Those in the former group typically suggest abolishing the vocational aspect of the Seanad as ineffectual and based on outdated political thinking.<ref name=\"Coakley2011\">{{cite book |chapter-url=http://www.nui.ie/elections/referendum/docs/ck1y_arCl3.pdf#page=4 |chapter=The Final Seanad Election? |page=243 |first=John |last=Coakley |editor1-last=Gallagher |editor1-first=Michael |editor2-last=Marsh |editor2-first=Michael |title=How Ireland Voted 2011:  The Full Story of Ireland's Earthquake Election |date=2011 |isbn=978-0-230-34881-3 |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |accessdate=6 April 2020 |quote=These three reports acknowledged the impossibility of giving effect to any meaningful form of vocational representation }}</ref> Those in the latter group typically suggest altering the nomination process and the franchise; both the 2015 [[Maurice Manning|Manning]] report and the 2018 report of the Seanad Reform Implementation Group recommended that 13 panel senators continue to be elected on the current limited franchise, and the other 30 be popularly elected: all citizens over 18 could register for one of the five panels or one of the university constituencies.<ref>{{cite book |author1=Seanad Reform Implementation Group |title=Report of the Seanad Reform Implementation Group |date=December 2018 |url=https://assets.gov.ie/5245/211218143426-25949b1b57ce47d5aff3eb83402fb99e.pdf#page=8 |accessdate=6 April 2020 |chapter=5. Recommendations of the Implementation Group}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[1969 French constitutional referendum]] \u2014 rejected proposal to merge the [[French Economic, Social and Environmental Council|Economic, Social and Environmental Council]] into the [[Senate (France)|Senate]]\n* [[Functional constituency]] \u2014 in Hong Kong and Macao\n\n==References==\n===Footnotes===\n{{reflist|group=\"n\"}}\n\n===Sources===\n* {{cite web |title=Constitution of Ireland |pages=Articles 18\u201319 |nopp=y |url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/cons/en/html#article18 |website=electronic Irish Statute Book (eISB) |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}\n* {{cite web |title=Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1947  |url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1947/act/42/enacted/en/index.html |website=electronic Irish Statute Book (eISB) |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}\n* {{cite web |title=Seanad Electoral (Panel Members) Act 1954 |url=http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1954/act/1/enacted/en/html |website=electronic Irish Statute Book (eISB) |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/publications/?author=seanad-eireann&topic%5B0%5D=election-results&topic%5B1%5D=elections Seanad election details since 2002], Oireachtas website\n\n{{Seanad \u00c9ireann}}\n\n[[Category:Seanad constituencies]]\n[[Category:Corporatism]]\n[[Category:Local authorities in the Republic of Ireland]]\n", "name_user": "Jnestorius", "label": "safe", "comment": "case act", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vocational_panel"}
{"title_page": "Magdalen College, Oxford", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Magdalen College||Magdalen College (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox residential college\n| name           = Magdalen College\n| full_name      = The College of St Mary Magdalen in the University of Oxford\n| university     = [[University of Oxford|Oxford]]\n| photo          = File:Magdalen-may-morning-2007-panorama.jpg\n| caption        = Magdalen College during [[May Morning]], 2007, showing the Tower and Chapel exterior. \n| scarf          = {{scarf|{{cells|3|#000}}{{cells|3|white}}{{cells|3|#000}}{{cells|3|white}}{{cells|3|#000}}}}\n| latin_name     = Collegium Beatae Mariae Magdalenae\n| motto          = ''Floreat Magdalena''\n| named_for      = [[Mary Magdalene]]\n| established    = 1458\n| sister_college = [[Magdalene College, Cambridge]]\n| president      = Sir [[David Clary]] FRS\n| undergraduates = 411<ref>{{cite web|title = Student numbers December 2013|publisher = University of Oxford|url = http://www.ox.ac.uk/about/facts-and-figures/student-numbers}}</ref> (2013)\n| graduates      = 159\n| endowment =  \u00a3273.2&nbsp;million <small>(2018)</small><ref name=\"magdalen1718\">{{cite web|url=http://d307gmaoxpdmsg.cloudfront.net/collegeaccounts1718/Magdalen.pdf|title=Magdalen College : Report and Financial Statements for the Year Ended 31 July 2018|website= ox.ac.uk |page=26|access-date=5 March 2019}}</ref>\n| location       = [[Longwall Street]] and [[High Street, Oxford|High Street]]\n| coordinates    = {{coord|51.752374|-1.247077|display=inline,title}}\n| location_map   = Oxford (central)\n| shield         = [[File:Magdalen College Oxford Coat Of Arms (Motto).svg|150px]]\n| blazon         = ''Lozengy ermine and sable, on a chief of the second three lilies argent slipped and seeded or''\n| homepage       = {{URL|http://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/}}\n| boat_club      = [http://www.magdalenboatclub.co.uk/ Boatclub website]\n}}\n\n'''Magdalen College''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|m|\u0254\u02d0|d|l|\u1d7b|n}} {{Respell|MAWD|lin}})<ref name=Names>{{cite web|work=First Names Dictionary on AskOxford.com|title=Magdalen (Name)|url=http://www.askoxford.com/firstnames/magdalen?view=uk|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607031814/http://www.askoxford.com/firstnames/magdalen?view=uk|archivedate=7 June 2011}}</ref> is a [[Colleges of the University of Oxford|constituent college]] of the [[University of Oxford]]. It was founded in 1458 by [[William of Waynflete]].<ref name=\"College History\">{{cite web|url= http://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/discover-magdalen/history-of-college|title= College History| publisher=magd.ox.ac.uk|access-date=22 March 2019}}</ref> Today, it is one of the wealthiest colleges, with a [[financial endowment]] of \u00a3273.2 million as of 2018,<ref name=\"magdalen1718\"/> and one of the strongest academically, setting the record for the highest [[Norrington Table|Norrington Score]] in 2010 and topping the table twice since then.<ref name=\"norrtable\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ox.ac.uk/about/facts-and-figures/undergraduate-degree-classifications|title=Undergraduate Degree Classifications {{!}} University of Oxford|website=www.ox.ac.uk|accessdate=13 September 2019}}</ref> It is home to several of the University's distinguished [[Chair (academic)|chairs]], including the [[Serena Professor of Italian#Serena Professors at Oxford|Agnelli-Serena Professorship]], the [[Sherardian Professor of Botany|Sherardian Professorship]], and the four [[Waynflete Professorship]]s.\n\nThe large, square [[Magdalen Tower, Oxford|Magdalen Tower]] is an [[Oxford]] landmark, and it is a tradition, dating to the days of [[Henry VII of England|Henry VII]], that the college choir sings from the top of it at 6&nbsp;a.m. on [[May Morning]].<ref name=\"world and its people\">{{Cite book\n|last = Dunton\n|first = Larkin\n|title = The World and Its People\n|publisher = Silver, Burdett\n|year = 1896\n|page = 55}}</ref> The college stands next to the [[River Cherwell]] and the [[University of Oxford Botanic Garden|Oxford botanic garden]], and within its grounds has a [[deer]] park and [[Addison's Walk]].\n\n==History==\n=== Foundation ===\nMagdalen College was founded in 1458 by [[William of Waynflete]], Bishop of [[Winchester, England|Winchester]] and Lord Chancellor <ref name=\"College History\" /> and named after [[St Mary Magdalene]]. The College succeeded a [[Colleges of the University of Oxford#Medieval Halls|university hall]] called Magdalen Hall, founded by Waynflete in 1448, and from which the college drew most of its earliest scholars.<ref name=\"BHO magdalen\" /> This first Magdalen Hall was suppressed when the college was founded; though the name was revived by a second Magdalen Hall, established in the college's grounds around 1490, which in the 19th century would move to Catte Street and become [[Hertford College, Oxford|Hertford College]].<ref name=\"Magdalen Hall\">{{cite web|url=http://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/libraries-and-archives/archives/magdalen-hall/|title=Magdalen Hall| publisher=magd.ox.ac.uk|access-date=21 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"brockliss85\">{{cite book |title=The University of Oxford: A History |page=85 |last=Brockliss |first=Lawrence W. B. |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-924356-3|year=2016 }}</ref> \nAlso established by Waynflete on the college site was a Grammar School, now [[Magdalen College School, Oxford|Magdalen College School]], an [[independent school (United Kingdom)|independent school]] located nearby on the other side of the Cherwell. Waynflete was assisted by a large bequest from Sir [[John Fastolf]], who wished to fund a religious college.<ref name=\"fastolf\">{{cite journal |title=Memorandum Quod: John Fastolf and the Founding of Magdalen College |year=2003 |journal=Magdalen College Record |last=Rose |first=Jonathan |pages=98\u2013105|ssrn=1426349 }}</ref>\n\nMagdalen College took over the site of St John the Baptist Hospital, alongside the [[River Cherwell|Cherwell]], initially using the hospital's buildings until new construction was completed between 1470\u20131480.<ref name=\"BHO sjh\" /> At incorporation in 1458, the college consisted of a president and six scholars. In 1487 when the Founder's Statutes were written, the foundation consisted of a President, forty fellows, thirty [[demyship|demies]], four chaplain priests, eight clerks, sixteen choristers, and appointed to the Grammar School, a Master and an usher.<ref name=\"BHO magdalen\" />\n\nThe founder's statutes included provision for a choral foundation of men and boys (a tradition that has continued to the present day) and made reference to the pronunciation of the name of the college in English. The college's name is pronounced like the adjective [[maudlin]] because the late medieval English name of Mary Magdalene was Maudelen, derived from the Old French Madelaine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.etymonline.com/word/maudlin|publisher=Online Etymology Dictionary|title=Maudlin (adj.)|access-date=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===English Civil War===\n\nOxford and Magdalen College were supporters of the [[Cavalier|Royalist]] cause during the [[English Civil War]]. In 1642, Magdalen College donated over 296 [[Pound (mass)|lbs]] of plate to fund the war effort - the largest donation by weight of any Oxford college.<ref name=\"plate\">{{cite book |title=Heraldry, Pageantry and Social Display in Medieval England |editor1-first=Peter R. |editor1-last=Coss |editor2-first=Maurice |editor2-last=Keen |chapter=7. Medieval Founders' Relics: Royal and Episcopal Patronage at Oxford and Cambridge Colleges|last=Campbell |first=Marian |date=2003 |publisher=Boydell Press}}</ref> Magdalen College, commanding a position on the banks of the Cherwell that overlooked [[Magdalen Bridge]] and the road from London, had tactical significance for the King's forces. Royalist ordnance was parked in the Magdalen's Grove, and [[Prince Rupert]] is thought to have quartered in the college.<ref name=\"BHO magdalen\" /> During the first [[Siege of Oxford]], [[Charles I of England|Charles I]] surveyed the battle from [[Magdalen Tower]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Walker|first=Sir Edward|author-link=Edward Walker (officer of arms)|year=1705|title=Historical Discourses, Upon Several Occasions|location=London|pages=16\u201321|nopp=y|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=d-ExAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA16#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>\n\n===Expulsion of the Fellows===\n[[File:The Expulsion of the Fellows, 1687 - Joseph Tonneau (1884).jpg|thumb|''The Expulsion of the Fellows, 1687'' by Joseph Tonneau (1884).]]\nDuring the 1680s, [[James II of England|King James II]] made several moves to reintroduce [[Roman Catholicism|Catholicism]] into the then [[Anglican]] university.<ref name=\"brockliss208210\">{{cite book |title=The University of Oxford: A History |pages=208\u2013210 |last=Brockliss |first=Lawrence W. B. |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-924356-3|year=2016 }}</ref> In 1687, he attempted to install [[Anthony Farmer]] as [[Master (college)|president]] of Magdalen. The [[fellow]]s rejected this, not just because Farmer was reputedly a Catholic and had a tarnished reputation, but also as he was not a fellow of the college, and therefore ineligible under the statutes.<ref name=\"brockliss208210\" /><ref name=\"BHO magdalen\" /> The fellows elected instead one of their own, [[John Hough (bishop)|John Hough]]. James eventually offered a compromise candidate in the form of the moderate [[Samuel Parker (bishop of Oxford)|Bishop of Oxford, Samuel Parker]],<ref name=\"brockliss208210\" /> but he too was rejected by the fellows as they considered the role filled.<ref name=\"corrie\">{{cite book |title=Brief Historical Notices of the Interference of the Crown with the Affairs of the English Universities |pages=70\u201385 |last=Corrie |first=George Elwes |year=1839 |publisher=J. & J. J. Deighton}}</ref><ref name=\"restorationbuttery\">{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/libraries-and-archives/treasure-of-the-month/news/buttery-book-and-restoration/ |title=Illuminating Magdalen: A Magdalen College Buttery Book and the Restoration of the Fellows of Magdalen |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |access-date=2 February 2020 |date=30 October 2015}}</ref> Parker was admitted by force<ref name=\"BHO magdalen\" /> and the fellows and [[Demyship|demies]] (scholars) who had defied the king were expelled, replaced by the king's choice of Catholics or moderate Anglicans. Parker died in 1688 and was replaced by [[Bonaventure Giffard]], a Catholic under whose tenure the Chapel converted to Catholicism. The expulsion of the fellows marked a turning point in the University's relationship with the Crown: Brockliss writes, \"the royalist and Anglican University established at the Restoration had had to make a choice and it had chosen Anglicanism.\"<ref name=\"brockliss208210\" /> James' interference with the college fed resentment in Anglicans who used it as evidence that his rule was autocratic.<ref name=\"brockliss208210\" /><ref name=\"restorationbuttery\" /> On 25 October 1688, shortly before the [[Glorious Revolution]] and overthrow of James II by [[William III of England|William of Orange]], James' appointments were reversed and Hough and the expelled fellows were restored to the college.<ref name=\"brockliss208210\" /><ref name=\"restorationbuttery\" /> This event is marked every year at a special banquet, the Restoration Dinner, for Magdalen fellows, demies, and academic clerks.<ref name=\"restorationbuttery\" />\n\n===20th-21st centuries===\n\nMagdalen's prominence since the mid-20th century owes much to such famous fellows as [[C. S. Lewis]] and [[A. J. P. Taylor]], and its academic success to the work of such dons as [[Thomas Dewar Weldon]].<ref>[[R.W. Johnson]], ''Look Back in Laughter: Oxford's Postwar Golden Age'', Threshold Press, 2015.</ref> During [[World War II]], [[RAF Maintenance Command]] was headquartered at Magdalen.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sofo.org.uk/colleges |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-11-06 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20121224193959/http://www.sofo.org.uk/colleges |archivedate=24 December 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nMagdalen College owns and manages the [[Oxford Science Park]] to the south of Oxford, a science and technology park home to over 100 companies. The Oxford Science Park opened in 1991, with Magdalen as part owner. The college acquired the rest of the ownership in 2016.<ref name=\"OSP history\">{{cite web |url=https://oxfordsp.com/our-story/ |title=Our Story |publisher=Oxford Science Park |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"OSP 2016\">{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/news/magdalen-acquires-100-of-oxford-science-park/ |title=Magdalen Acquires 100% of Oxford Science Park |date=12 January 2016 |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nLike many of Oxford's colleges, Magdalen admitted its first mixed-sex cohort in 1979, after more than half a millennium as a men-only institution.<ref name=\"College History\"/> Between 2015 and 2017, 47.2% of UK undergraduates admitted to Magdalen were from state schools; 12.2% were of BME heritage and 0.7% were black.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ox.ac.uk/sites/files/oxford/Annual%20Admissions%20Statistical%20Report%202018.pdf|title=Annual Admissions Statistical Report May 2018|website=www.ox.ac.uk}}</ref> Of the 300 undergraduate offers made by Magdalen between 2017 and 2019, 25 (one in twelve) went to pupils from Eton College or Westminster School.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/01/12/one-12-offers-made-single-oxford-college-have-gone-pupils-two/|title=One in 12 offers made by a single Oxford college have gone to pupils from two elite private schools}}</ref> In 2015, Magdalen topped Oxford's [[Norrington Table]] of college undergraduate examination results, and its average score over the 2006\u20132016 period is the best among the colleges.\n\n==Buildings==\n[[File:Magdalen College Oxford campus map.svg|thumb|Map of Magdalen College buildings and grounds, marked out in black.]]\nThe college grounds stretch north and east from the college, and include most of the area bounded by [[Longwall Street]], the [[High Street, Oxford|High Street]] (where the [[porter's lodge]] is located), and [[St Clement's, Oxford|St Clement's]]. The college features a variety of architectural styles, and has been described as \"a medieval nucleus with two incomplete additions, one from the eighteenth and one from the nineteenth century\".<ref name=\"unbuiltoxford\" />\n\nThe college is organised around five quads. The irregularly shaped St John's Quad is the first on entering the college, and includes the Outdoor Pulpit and old Grammar Hall. It connects to the Great Quad (the Cloister) via the Perpendicular Gothic [[Founders Tower]], which is richly decorated with carvings and pinnacles and has carved bosses in its vault. The Chaplain's Quad runs along the side of the Chapel and Hall, to the foot of the [[Magdalen Tower|Great Tower]]. St Swithun's Quad and Longwall Quad (which contains the Library) date from the late 19th and early 20th centuries, and make up the southwest corner of the college.\n\n===Original buildings===\nThe college is built on the site of St John the Baptist Hospital, which was dissolved in 1457 and its property granted to William of Waynflete.<ref name=\"BHO sjh\">'Hospitals: St John the Baptist, Oxford', in A History of the County of Oxford: Volume 2, ed. William Page (London, 1907), pp. 158-159. British History Online http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/oxon/vol2/pp158-159 [accessed 5 February 2020].</ref> Some of the hospital buildings were reused by the college, and the kitchens survive today as the college bar, the Old Kitchen Bar.<ref name=\"BHO magdalen\">\"Magdalen College\", in ''A History of the County of Oxford: Volume 3'', the University of Oxford, ed. H. E. Salter and Mary D. Lobel (London, 1954), pp. 193-207. British History Online http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/oxon/vol3/pp193-207 [accessed 5 February 2020].</ref><ref name=\"okb\">{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/conferences/old-kitchen-bar/ |title=Old Kitchen Bar |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |access-date=5 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nNew construction began in 1470 with the erection of a wall around the site by mason [[William Orchard (architect)|William Orchard]]. Following this, Orchard also worked on the chapel, hall, and the cloister, including the Muniment and [[Founders Tower|Founder's Tower]]s, with work completed around 1480.<ref name=\"BHO magdalen\" />\n\n===Cloister===\n[[File:Magdalen College, Oxford (7958644740).jpg|thumb|View across the Cloister. The far side is the hall (left) and chapel, behind is the Great Tower.]]\nThe Cloister or Great Quad is the \"medieval nucleus\" of the college. It was constructed between 1474 and 1480, also by Orchard, although several modifications were made later. Access to the Cloister from St John's Quad is via the [[Founders Tower|Founder's Tower]] or Muniment Tower. The chapel and the hall make up the southern side of the quad. It is also home to the junior, middle, and senior common rooms, and the old library.\n\nIn 1508, [[grotesques]] known as hieroglyphics were added to the Cloister. These are thought to be allegorical, and include four hieroglyphics in front of the old library that represent scholarly subjects: science, medicine, law, and theology.<ref name=\"grotesques\">{{citation |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/libraries-and-archives/treasure-of-the-month/news/library-hieroglyphics/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200110205526/https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/libraries-and-archives/treasure-of-the-month/news/library-hieroglyphics/ |title=Library Hieroglyphics|archive-date=10 January 2020 |date=29 July 2016 |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford}}</ref><ref name=\"slatterguide\">{{cite book |title=The Oxford University and City Guide |last=Slatter |first=H |year=1834 |pages=32\u201333 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=aSRbAAAAcAAJ&dq=magdalen+cloister+boxers}}</ref> The other hieroglyphics have been assigned symbolism relating to virtues that should be encouraged by the college (e.g. the lion and pelican grotesques in front of the Senior Common Room representing courage and parental affection) or vices that should be avoided (the [[manticore]], boxers, and [[lamia]] in front of the Junior Common Room, representing pride, contention, and lust).<ref name=\"slatterguide\" /> In 2017, repair work was undertaken to restore the severely damaged boxers statue.<ref name=\"boxers statue\">{{cite web |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205210132/https://www.alexwenham.co.uk/boxers-statue-magdalen-college-oxford/ |url=https://www.alexwenham.co.uk/boxers-statue-magdalen-college-oxford/ |title=Boxers Statue, Magdalen College Oxford |access-date=5 February 2020 |archive-date=5 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1822, the north side of the Cloister was knocked down, ostensibly due to disrepair. This decision was controversial, provoking protests from the fellows and in the contemporary press, and it was rebuilt shortly afterwards.<ref name=\"unbuiltoxford\" /><ref name=\"BHO magdalen\" />\n\nIn the early 1900s, renovations were performed, and it was returned to a more medieval character. Student rooms were installed in the (very large) roof space in the 1980s.\n\n===Chapel===\n[[File:Magdalen College Chapel Interior, Oxford, UK - Diliff.jpg|thumb|The interior of the chapel, showing Wyatt's plaster roof]]\n\nThe chapel is a [[place of worship]] for members of the college and others in the University of Oxford community and beyond. As a [[High Anglican]] chapel, its tradition is influenced by the [[Catholic Revival]] in the [[Church of England]]. Said and sung services are held daily during term.<ref name=\"Services\">{{cite web|url=http://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/chapel-and-choir/services|title=Chapel Services|publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford}}</ref> The choir sings Choral [[Evening Prayer (Anglican)|Evensong]] or Evening Prayer every day at 6:00 pm except on Mondays.<ref name=\"Services\"/> On Sundays, a Sung Eucharist is offered in the morning at 11:00 am, whilst [[Compline]] (Night Prayer) is sung several times per term.<ref name=\"Services\"/> Mass is also sung on major holy days.<ref name=\"Services\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/chapel-and-choir|title=Chapel & Choir|publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford}}</ref>\n\nThe chapel itself is a grade I [[listed building]] built between 1474\u20131480.<ref name=\"chapellisted\">{{cite web|url=https://historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1369672|title=MAGDALEN COLLEGE, CHAPEL, GREAT QUADRANGLE|publisher=Historic England}}</ref> The roof, giving the impression of a stone vaulted ceiling, is in fact a facsimile made from plaster added in 1790 by [[James Wyatt]]. Wyatt's redevelopment of the chapel included a number of modifications to make it more Gothic in character, but other than the ceiling, Wyatt's contributions were removed during a later redesign in 1828.<ref name=\"chapellisted\" /><ref name=\"unbuiltoxford\" /><ref name=\"georgiangothic\">{{cite book|title=Georgian Gothic: Medievalist Architecture, Furniture and Interiors, 1730-1840|first=Peter|last=Lindfield|pages=168\u2013169|isbn=9781783271276|publisher=Boydell & Brewer|year=2016}}</ref>\n\nThe [[stained glass]] windows facing St John's Quad feature a ''[[grisaille]]'' depiction of the [[Last Judgement]]. These windows, dating from 1792, are a reconstruction by [[Francis Eginton]] of an earlier 17th-century window that was destroyed in a storm.<ref name=\"indpressurection\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/the-resurrection-at-magdalen-college-1279624.html |title=The resurrection at Magdalen College |last=Popham |first=Peter |date=20 February 1997 |work=The Independent |access-date=2 February 2020}}</ref> It had been uninstalled during [[World War II]] to protect it from damage, and was only restored in the 1990s. Much of the glass had been thought lost, until it was rediscovered in the ventilation tunnels under the New Building.<ref name=\"indpressurection\" />\n\n===Magdalen Tower===\n[[File:UK-2014-Oxford-Magdalen College 08.jpg|right|thumb|Magdalen College Tower.]]\n{{further|Magdalen Tower}}\nConstruction of Magdalen's Great Tower began in 1492 by another mason, William Raynold. It might have been intended to replace an existing bellfry remaining from the hospital, and probably was originally envisioned to stand alone. By the time it was completed in 1509, additional buildings had been built either side, creating the roughly triangular Chaplain's quad between the chapel and the High.<ref name=\"BHO magdalen\" />\n\nThe tower contains a peal of ten bells hung for [[Change ringing|English change ringing]]. They were cast at a number of different [[foundry|foundries]] and the heaviest, weighing 17 [[hundredweight|cwt]], was cast in 1623.<ref>[http://dove.cccbr.org.uk/detail.php?DoveID=OXFORD+CMA Magdalen College Bells], Dove's Guide for Church Bell Ringers.</ref>\n\nThe tower is 144 feet tall and an imposing landmark on the eastern approaches to the city centre.<ref name=\"websitecollegebuildings\" /> It has been the model for other towers, including Mitchell Tower of the [[University of Chicago]],<ref name=\"mitchell\">{{cite journal|title=Architectural Details|date=December 2002|publisher=University of Chicago|url=http://magazine.uchicago.edu/0212/alumni/arch.html|accessdate=April 30, 2006|journal=The University of Chicago Magazine|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060518050733/http://magazine.uchicago.edu/0212/alumni/arch.html|archive-date=May 18, 2006|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Manhattan]]'s [[First Presbyterian Church (Manhattan)|First Presbyterian Church]],<ref>{{Cite book|author-link  = David W. Dunlap |author-last  = Dunlap |author-first = David W. |year = 2004 |title  = From Abyssinian to Zion: A Guide to Manhattan's Houses of Worship |location = New York |publisher = [[Columbia University Press]] |isbn = 0-231-12543-7}}</ref> and All Saints' Church in [[Churchill, Oxfordshire]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Sherwood |first1=Jennifer |last2=Pevsner |first2=Nikolaus |authorlink2=Nikolaus Pevsner |year=1974 |title=Oxfordshire |series=[[Pevsner Architectural Guides#Buildings of England|The Buildings of England]]}}</ref> It forms the centre of the [[May Morning]] celebrations in Oxford.\n\n===The New Building===\n[[File:Oxford magdalen college new building.jpg|thumb|right|The New Building.]]\nDuring the 18th and 19th centuries, there were numerous attempts made to redesign the site to better suit the College's needs.<ref name=\"unbuiltoxford\">{{cite book|last=Colvin|first=Sir Howard|authorlink=Howard Colvin|title=Unbuilt Oxford|publisher=[[Yale University Press]]|isbn=0-300-03126-2|year=1983|chapter-url-access=registration|chapter=VII Indecision at Magdalen|pages=[https://archive.org/details/unbuiltoxford0000colv/page/78 78-104]|chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/unbuiltoxford0000colv/page/78}}</ref> The New Building began construction in 1733 as a part of [[Edward Holdsworth]]'s designs from 1731. It is built in a [[Palladian architecture|Palladian style]], and features a [[colonnade]].\n\nIt was conceived as one side of a new \"Great Quadrangle\", and in anticipation of this the building's ends had been left unfinished. However, Holdsworth's full vision was never completed. The idea was revisited several times by later architects, including by architects [[James Wyatt]]\u2014who plans (never realised) included partially demolishing the existing, Medieval quad (the Cloister) and refinishing the neoclassical New Building in a [[Gothic revival architecture|Georgian Gothic]] style\u2014and [[John Buckler]].<ref name=\"unbuiltoxford\" /><ref name=\"georgiangothic\" /> In the 19th Century, [[John Nash (architect)|John Nash]] and [[Humphrey Repton]] both submitted designs for new, open quadrangles that incorporated the New Building.<ref name=\"unbuiltoxford\" />\n\nUltimately, the idea of integrating the New Building into a new quad was abandoned, and the ends of the building were finally completed in 1824 with two returns designed by [[Thomas Harrison (architect)|Thomas Harrison]].<ref name=\"unbuiltoxford\" /> Today, it stands apart from the Cloister, overlooking four [[croquet]] lawns on one side and the Grove deer park on the other. It is used for accommodation for undergraduates and fellows, including historically [[Edward Gibbon]] and [[C. S. Lewis]], and also houses the wine cellar.<ref name=\"ugliving\">{{cite web|url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/living-here/undergraduate-living-here/|title=As an Undergraduate|publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford}}</ref>\n\n===Daubeny laboratory===\n[[File:Daubeny lab plate, Magdalen College Oxford.png|thumb|Illustration of the Daubeny Laboratory as it looked c. 1870.]]\nOpposite the main college site and overlooking the [[University of Oxford Botanic Garden|Botanic Garden]] is the 19th century Daubeny Laboratory.<ref name=\"websitecollegebuildings\" />\n\nThe Garden had been established between 1622 and 1633 as a [[physic garden]] (that is, a garden to study the medicinal value of plants) on land inherited by Magdalen from St. John's Hospital.<ref name=\"historyOfDaubenyLab\">{{cite book|title=A history of the Daubeny Laboratory, Magdalen College, Oxford |url=https://archive.org/details/historyofdaubeny00guntuoft/page/i/mode/2up|url-access=registration|date=1904|last=Gunter|first=Robert Theodore}}</ref> The Daubeny Laboratory, and neighbouring Professor's House, were founded by the [[polymath]] and Magdalen fellow [[Charles Daubeny]] after he was appointed to the [[Sherardian Professor of Botany|Sherardian Chair of Botany]] in 1834.<ref name=\"historyOfDaubenyLab\" />\n\nDaubeny set about a number of additions to the location, erecting new glasshouses and in 1836 creating an on-site residence for the Professor of Botany. This replaced an earlier residence that had been demolished in 1795 when the road was widened. The new residence was an extension of the library, which had been created out of a glasshouse by an earlier Sherardian professor, [[John Sibthorp]], to house the Sherard [[herbarium]]. After Daubeny's death, this was assimilated to house the growing collection.<ref name=\"historyOfDaubenyLab\" /><ref name=\"sherardHerbarium\">{{cite web |url=https://herbaria.plants.ox.ac.uk/bol/sherard/DBnotes |title=Notes on the Sherard Herbarium database |access-date=3 February 2020 |publisher=Department of Plant Sciences, University of Oxford}}</ref> Later, it became accommodation for graduate students, the Professor's House, while the Sherard Herbarium is now part of the Fielding-Druce Herbarium held in the [[Department of Plant Sciences, University of Oxford|Department of Plant Sciences]].<ref name=\"FDHerbarium\">{{cite web |url=https://herbaria.plants.ox.ac.uk/bol/oxford/OXF |title=Fielding-Druce Herbarium |access-date=3 February 2020 |publisher=Department of Plant Sciences, University of Oxford}}</ref>\n\nDaubeny, who was also the [[Aldrichian Chairs|Aldrichian Professor of Chemistry]], had found the chemistry laboratory in the basement of the old [[Ashmolean Museum]], what is now the [[History of Science Museum, Oxford|History of Science Museum]], to be \"notoriously unworthy of a great University\" and desired a better science facility. He petitioned the College to be allowed to build one, and the Daubeny laboratory was completed in 1848.<ref name=\"historyOfDaubenyLab\" /><ref name=\"brockliss313314\">{{cite book |title=The University of Oxford: A History |pages=313\u2013314 |last=Brockliss |first=Lawrence W. B. |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-924356-3|year=2016 }}</ref> The Daubeny Laboratory was preceded by the anatomy school and laboratory at [[Christ Church, Oxford|Christ Church]] which opened in 1767, and would be followed later in the century by other college laboratories including the [[Balliol-Trinity Laboratories]].<ref name=\"chemistry\">{{cite book|title=Chemistry at Oxford: A History from 1600 to 2005|author1=Robert Joseph Paton Williams |author2=Allan Chapman |author3=John Shipley Rowlinson |page=275 | publisher=Royal Society of Chemistry |date=6 November 2008|isbn= 978-0854041398 }}</ref> Daubeny's laboratory was a two-storey room with benches and cupboards encircled by a gallery, and became the principal chemistry lab for the University. In 1902, due to growing student numbers and poor ventilation, the laboratory trappings were removed and it was refitted as a lecture hall.<ref name=\"historyOfDaubenyLab\" /> In 1973, most of the Daubeny Laboratory building was reconfigured into graduate student accommodation.<ref name=\"magdPapersDaubeny\">{{cite web |url=https://archive-cat.magd.ox.ac.uk/records/FA19 |title=PAPERS ON BUILDINGS IN THE BOTANICAL GARDENS, c. 1800-200 |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford, archive catelogue |access-date=3 February 2020}}</ref> The Daubeny lab itself is now a conference space.\n\n===St Swithun's quad===\n[[File:Magdalen College, Oxford-8086510626.jpg|thumb|A view from the Great Tower of St Swithun's Quad, and behind it Longwall Quad.]]\n\nIn 1880\u20131884, the college extended westwards onto the former site of [[Magdalen Hall]]. The hall was an independent university hall that developed from Magdalen College School, not the earlier Magdalen Hall founded by William Waynflete.<ref name=\"Magdalen Hall\" /> Most of Magdalen Hall's buildings were destroyed by fire in 1820, though the Grammar Hall survived and was restored by Joseph Parkinson.<ref name=\"unbuiltoxford\" /> The hall moved to Catte Street in 1822 and was incorporated as [[Hertford College, Oxford|Hertford College]] in 1874.<ref name=\"Magdalen Hall\" />\n\nThe new construction, [[Swithun|St Swithun]]'s quad<ref name=\"websitecollegebuildings\">{{cite web|url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/discover-magdalen/history-of-college/history-of-the-college-buildings/ |title=The College Buildings |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |access-date=3 February 2020}}</ref> (sometimes given as St. Swithin's quad<ref name=\"unbuiltoxford\" /><ref name=\"swithlist\">{{cite web|url=https://historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1046707 |title=MAGDALEN COLLEGE, ST SWITHINS QUADRANGLE |publisher=Historic England |access-date=3 February 2020}}</ref>), was designed by [[George Frederick Bodley]] and [[Thomas Garner]] in keeping with the Gothic style. They had originally designed three sides of a square, though only the south and west sides were built. In 1928, [[Giles Gilbert Scott]] extended the building north and westwards, forming the adjacent Longwall quad.<ref name=\"unbuiltoxford\" />\n\n===Modern buildings and acquisitions===\n[[File:Magdalen college oxford grove buildings.jpg|thumb|The Grove Buildings, including the auditorium (left), were completed in 1999.]]\nSeveral new additions to the college were made in the late 20th century. The Waynflete Building, which is located across Magdalen Bridge from the main college site, was designed by [[Booth, Ledeboer, and Pinckheard]] and completed in 1964.<ref name=\"RIBA Waynflete\">{{cite web|url=https://www.architecture.com/image-library/RIBApix/gallery-product/poster/waynflete-building-magdalen-college-oxford/posterid/RIBA11414.html|title=Waynflete Building, Magdalen College, Oxford|publisher=architecture.com|accessdate=20 December 2018}}</ref> Magdalen has a number of additional annexes near to the main site for accommodation, including in Cowley Place and [[Longwall Street]].\n\nThe Grove Buildings, located north of Longwall quad between Longwall Street and the Grove, were built in 1994-1999 by [[Porphyrios Associates]]. They are home to accommodation, Magdalen's 160-seat auditorium, and the Denning Law Library.<ref name=\"websitecollegebuildings\" /><ref name=\"auditorium\">{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/conferences/grove-auditorium/ |title=Grove Auditorium |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |access-date=6 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"libraries\" /> During term time, the auditorium hosts film screenings organised by the Magdalen Film Society.<ref name=\"mfilms\">{{cite web |url=https://www.mfsoxford.com/ |title=Magdalen Film Society |access-date=6 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nAlong Addison's Walk is the Holywell Ford site, where most of the graduate accommodation is located. Holywell Ford house was built by [[Clapton Crabb Rolfe]] in 1888 on the location of an older mill, and was acquired by Magdalen in the 1970s.<ref name=\"holywell ford\">{{cite web |url=http://www.oxfordhistory.org.uk/holywell/misc/holywell_mill.html |publisher=Oxford History |title=Holywell Mill and the Holly Well, Oxford |last=Jenkins |first=Stephanie |access-date=6 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920185626/http://www.oxfordhistory.org.uk/holywell/misc/holywell_mill.html |archive-date=20 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"he holywell\">{{cite web |url=https://historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1369449 |title=Hollywell Ford |publisher=Historic England |access-date=6 February 2020}}</ref> Additional blocks of accommodation were built in 1994-5 by RH Partnership Ltd.<ref name=\"websitecollegebuildings\" />\n\n===Libraries===\n[[File:03-Magdalen-College.jpg|thumb|The redeveloped Longwall Quad. The main Longwall Library building is on the left.]]\nIn addition to the University's central and departmental libraries, Oxford's colleges maintain their own libraries. The original college library, the Old Library, is located in the Cloister and accessed via Founder's Tower or the President's Lodgings. It contains a large collection of manuscripts from before the 19th century. Consultation of material is typically by appointment, although the Old Library itself may be visited by the public during certain exhibitions.<ref name=\"libraries\">{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/libraries-and-archives/libraries/ |title=Magdalen's Libraries |website=Magdalen College}}</ref><ref name=\"womenlibraryexhibition\">{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/libraries-and-archives/news/new-exhibition-opening-in-september-women-and-power-a-magdalen-story/ |title=New exhibition opening in September: \"Women and Power? A Magdalen Story\" |website=Magdalen College Library and Archives}}</ref>\n\nIn 1931, the New Library, now called the Longwall Library, was established in the former [[Magdalen College School, Oxford|Magdalen College School]] building in Longwall Quad and became the college's main library for students. It was opened by [[Edward VIII]] when he was a student at Magdalen.<ref name=\"telegraphWilliam\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/05/11/prince-william-follows-in-edward-viiis-footsteps-by-opening-new/ |last=Rayner |first=Gordon |date=11 May 2016 |title=Prince William follows in Edward VIII's footsteps by opening new library at Oxford's Magdalen College |work=The Telegraph}}</ref> It was renovated between 2014 and 2016 by [[Wright & Wright Architects]] and reopened by [[Prince William, Duke of Cambridge]].<ref name=\"archdaily\">{{cite web |url=https://www.archdaily.com/882330/longwall-library-magdalen-college-wright-and-wright-architects |title=Longwall Library - Magdalen College / Wright & Wright Architects |website=Arch Daily}}</ref><ref name=\"telegraphWilliam\" />\n\nIn addition, the college maintains the Denning Law Library in the Grove building, a reference library for Magdalen's law students, and the specialist Daubeny and McFarlane collections of 19th century scientific works and medieval history works respectively. Items from the Daubeny and McFarlane libraries may be brought to the Longwall Library for consultation on request.<ref name=\"libraries\" />\n\n==Grounds==\n\n===The Grove===\n[[File:Magdalen Deer.jpg|thumb|right|The deer in the Grove]]\nThe Grove or deer park is large meadow which occupies most of the north west of the college's grounds, from the New Building and the Grove Buildings to Holywell Ford. During the winter and spring, it is the home of a herd of [[fallow deer]]. It is possible to view the meadow and the deer from the path between New Buildings and Grove Quad, and also from the archway in New Buildings.\n\nIn the 16th century, long before the introduction of the deer, the grove consisted of gardens, orchards, and [[bowling green]]s. During the [[English Civil War|Civil War]], it was used to house a regiment of soldiers. At one point in the 19th century it was home to three traction engines belonging to the works department of the college.  By the 20th century it had become well-wooded with many large trees, but most of them were lost to [[Dutch elm disease]] in the 1970s.\n\n===Water meadow and Addison's Walk===\n[[File:Magdalen college oxford water meadow flooded 1.jpg|thumb|Water meadow after winter flooding. The New Building is visible side on in the background.]]\nThe water meadow is a [[flood-meadow]] to the eastern side of the College, bounded on all sides by the [[River Cherwell|Cherwell]]. In wet winters, some or all of the meadow may flood, as the meadow is lower lying than the surrounding path. All around the edge of the meadow is a tree-lined path, [[Addison's Walk]], named for the fellow [[Joseph Addison]] (1672-1719), which connects to Holywell Ford and the Fellows' Garden.<ref name=\"flora and fauna grounds\" />\n\nAddison's Walk is popular with College members and visitors. [[C. S. Lewis]] wrote a poem about the walk, ''Chanson d'Aventure'' or ''What the Bird Said Early in the Year'', which is commemorated on a plaque near the gate to Holywell Ford.<ref name=\"flora and fauna grounds\">{{cite web |url=http://florafauna.magd.ox.ac.uk/magdalen-grounds/ |title=Magdalen Grounds - Flora and Fauna |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206200223/http://florafauna.magd.ox.ac.uk/magdalen-grounds/ |archive-date=6 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"addisons lewis1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cslewisinstitute.org/What_the_Bird_Said_Early_in_the_Year_FullArticle |title=Knowing & Doing Summer 2015 - What the Bird Said Early in the Year |publisher=C. S. Lewis Institute |last=Kohm |first=Joseph A. |year=2015 |access-date=6 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"addisons lewis2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.thegospelcoalition.org/blogs/justin-taylor/c-s-lewiss-poem-what-the-bird-said-early-in-the-year/ |title=C.S. Lewis's Poem, \"What the Bird Said Early In The Year\" |publisher=The Gospel Coalition |last=Taylor |first=Justin |date=25 February 2016 |access-date=6 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThanks to the frequent flooding, the meadow is one of the few places in the [[UK]] that the snake's head fritillary, ''[[Fritillaria meleagris]]'', may be seen growing wild.<ref name=\"telegraph fm\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/gardening/plants/10741803/Fritillaries-dont-forget-these-lilies-of-the-field.html |title=Fritillaries: don't forget these lilies of the field |last=Slade |first=Naomi |date=6 April 2014 |work=The Telegraph}}</ref> These flowers grow in very few places, and have been recorded growing in the meadow since around 1785.<ref name=\"telegraph fm\" /> Once the flowering has finished, the deer herd is moved in for the summer and autumn.\n\n===Bat Willow meadow and the Fellows' Garden===\n[[File:Magdalen college oxford fellows garden.jpg|thumb|The Fellows' Garden.]]\nFurther east of the water meadow are Bat Willow meadow and the Fellows' Garden. They are separated from the water meadow and each other by other branches of the Cherwell, and may be accessed from Addison's Walk. Bat Willow meadow features ''Y'', a 10 metre high sculpture of a branching tree by [[Mark Wallinger]], commissioned for the College's 550th anniversary in 2008.<ref name=\"wallinger news\">{{cite news |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/news/new-mark-wallinger-sculpture-unveiled/ |title=New Mark Wallinger sculpture unveiled |date=22 July 2008 |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |access-date=8 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"wallinger microsite\">{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/wallinger/further.html |title=Y by Mark Wallinger |access-date=8 February 2020 |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford}}</ref> Due to their age and infection with [[honey fungus]], the [[willow]] trees were cut down in 2018 and replanted, and the wood used to make [[cricket bats]].<ref name=\"bat willow\">{{cite news |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/news/replanting-bat-willow-meadow/ |title=Replanting Bat Willow Meadow |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |date=31 October 2018 |access-date=8 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Fellows' Garden is located further north along the bank of the Cherwell than Bat Willow meadow, directly behind the [[Oxford Centre for Islamic Studies]]. This long and narrow garden follows the Cherwell to the edge of the [[University Parks]]. In spring, the ground is covered with flowers. In summer, there are some flowers, many different shrubs, and the varied trees provide dappled cover from the sun.\n\nFurther north is [[Magdalen Ground|Magdalen's sports ground]].\n\n==Choir==\n[[File:William Holman Hunt - May Morning on Magdalen College, Oxford, Ancient Annual Ceremony - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|''May Morning on Magdalen Tower'' by [[William Holman Hunt]] (1890).]]\nMagdalen is one of the three choral foundations in Oxford, meaning that the formation of the choir was part of the statutes of the college, the other choral foundations being [[New College, Oxford|New College]] and [[Christ Church, Oxford|Christ Church]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ox.ac.uk/admissions/undergraduate_courses/applying_to_oxford/choral_organ/choralorgan.html|title=Choral and organ scholarships|publisher=University of Oxford}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ox.ac.uk/admissions/undergraduate_courses/applying_to_oxford/choral_organ/choral.html|title=Choral scholarships|publisher=University of Oxford|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130902104027/http://www.ox.ac.uk/admissions/undergraduate_courses/applying_to_oxford/choral_organ/choral.html|archivedate=2013-09-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.music.ox.ac.uk/admissions/organ-and-choral-scholarships1/Organandchoralscholarships-main-page.html|title=Organ and Choral Scholarships|publisher=Oxford University Faculty of Music|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130423132522/http://www.music.ox.ac.uk/admissions/organ-and-choral-scholarships1/Organandchoralscholarships-main-page.html|archivedate=2013-04-23}}</ref>\n\nThe choir consists of 12 [[Clerk (choral)|academical clerks]], or choral scholars, who are students at the college, and 16 boys aged seven to thirteen (some of whom stay on until age fourteen), all of whom have scholarships at [[Magdalen College School, Oxford|Magdalen College School]]. The school was founded for this purpose but has long since become an independent public school.\n\nThe choristers' day begins at 7:30, with an early morning practice before school. There is further practice immediately after school, followed by Choral Evensong six nights a week, in term; the Tuesday service is sung by the boys only, and the Friday service only by the Academical Clerks. On Sundays there is a practice at 9:30 am followed by Eucharist, then a further afternoon practice followed by Evensong which ends at 7:00 pm. As of September 2010, the choristers no longer sing on most Saturday evenings following the formation of the Consort of Voices, a mixed voice choir which sings on most Saturdays in full term.\n\nThe choir records regularly. In 2005, it was nominated for a [[Grammy Award]] for its [[Compact disc|CD]], ''With a Merrie Noyse'', of music by [[Orlando Gibbons]]. Other recent works include the BBC's ''[[The Blue Planet]]'' and Paul McCartney's classical piece ''[[Ecce Cor Meum]]''. The choir has numerous college duties as well as a recording and touring schedule. Traditionally the choir sings at college [[Gaudy|Gaudies]] and at other special events throughout the year, as well as performing on social occasions such as Carols by Candlelight before Christmas and the famous [[May Morning]].\n\n===May Morning===\n{{main|May Morning}}\nAnnually at 6 a.m. on 1 May, the choir perform [[Hymnus Eucharisticus]] from the top of Magdalen's Tower to crowds below on Madgalen Bridge and the High Street. This tradition dates back 500 years, and forms the central event in Oxford's [[May Morning]] celebration.\n\n===Organists===\n{{See also|Organ scholar}}\nThe choir has had many well-known organists, such as [[Daniel Purcell]], Sir [[John Stainer]] (1860\u20131872) and [[Bernard Rose (musician)|Bernard Rose]] (1957\u20131981). Among the other notable former directors and masters of the choir, who hold the title of ''Informator Choristarum'', are [[John Sheppard (composer)|John Sheppard]] (1543\u2013c.1552), Sir [[William McKie (musician)|William McKie]], [[Haldane Campbell Stewart]] and the composer [[Grayston Ives|Bill Ives]] (1991\u20132009), possibly better known as a former King's Singer. A disc of his music, ''Listen Sweet Dove'', is amongst the choir's releases.\n\nThe current Informator Choristarum, since January 2017, is [[Mark Williams (organist)|Mark Williams]]. He succeeded Daniel Hyde, who had been organ scholar at King's College Cambridge, following Hyde's appointment as Organist and Director of Music of [[Saint Thomas Church (Manhattan)|Saint Thomas Church, New York]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/news/new-appointments-to-chapel-and-choir/|title=New Appointments to Chapel and Choir \u2013 Magdalen College Oxford|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nPast organ scholars include [[Dudley Moore]], Matthew Martin and [[Paul Brough (conductor)|Paul Brough]]. Past academical clerks include [[John Mark Ainsley]], [[Harry Christophers]] (founder and director of [[The Sixteen]]), [[James Whitbourn]], [[Robin Blaze]], [[Roderick Williams]] and conductor/composer [[Gregory Rose (musician)|Gregory Rose]].\n\n==Student life==\n\n===Accommodation===\n[[File:Magdalen college oxford holywell ford.jpg|thumb|Holywell Ford, as seen from Addison's Walk. Holywell Ford house and annexes are used as accommodation for graduate students.]]\nUndergraduate students of the college are guaranteed accommodation during term for their entire degree, typically in the Waynflete building in their first year and \"inside-walls\" in the Cloister, St Swithun's Quad, the New Building and so on in subsequent years. Graduate students are guaranteed at least two years of accommodation. Unlike undergraduates, graduates are not required to move out between terms and typically live \"outside walls\", including in Holywell Ford, the Daubeny Laboratory, and Professor's House.<ref name=\"ug living\">{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/living-here/undergraduate-living-here/ |title=As an Undergraduate |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"pg living\">{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/living-here/graduate-living-here/ |title=As a Graduate |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccommodation charges are inclusive of heating, power, and internet access, and weekly cleaning by the college [[Bedder|scouts]] (housekeepers), but does not include catering. Three cafeteria style meals a day are served in the hall, and other food is available in the Old Kitchen Bar.<ref name=\"ug living\" /><ref name=\"pg living\" />\n\nIn addition to a dinner cafeteria service served in the hall, three [[Formal (university)|Formal Halls]] are held a week during term time. These are three course sit-down dinners and require college members to wear their [[academic gown|gowns]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/glossary_page_item/formal-hall/ |title=Formal Hall |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford}}</ref> Additional banquets commemorate special occasions, including the Restoration Dinner.<ref name=\"restorationbuttery\" /><ref name=\"mcr activities\">{{cite web |url=http://magdmcr.co.uk/mcractivities/ |title=Activities |publisher=Magdalen College MCR |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Events and societies===\n[[File:Magdalen College Dining Hall, Oxford, UK - Diliff.jpg|thumb|Magdalen College dining hall, where students can eat meals, also hosts regular formal banquets.]]\nThe body of undergraduate and graduate students are known as the junior and middle common rooms (JCR and MCR) respectively. They each elect committees of students annually to organise welfare events, socials, and banquets.<ref name=\"student life\">{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/living-here/student-life/ |title=Student Life |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"mcr activities\" />\n\nIn addition to clubs and societies associated with the [[Oxford University Student Union]] operated at the university level, Magdalen members may also participate in several college societies.<ref name=\"magd societies\">{{cite web |url=http://magdmcr.co.uk/college-societies/ |title=Societies |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref> The Atkin Society and the Sherrington Society are two subject-specific societies, for law students and medicine students respectively. They organise talks and social events. The Atkin society is named for lawyer [[James Atkin, Baron Atkin]], a former demy at Magdalen, and also organises an annual [[moot court]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/living-here/societies/the-atkin-society/ |title=The Atkin Society |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref> The Sherrington Society is named after Nobel laureate Sir [[Charles Scott Sherrington]], former Waynflete Professor of Physiology.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/living-here/societies/the-sherrington-society/ |title=The Atkin Society |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref> The college also has a poetry discussion forum called the Florio Society, named for 16th century college alumnus [[John Florio]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/living-here/societies/the-florio-society/ |title=The Florio Society |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nA number of other societies put on events throughout the year. These include the Magdalen Players, a drama society; the Magdalen Music Society; and the Magdalen Film Society, which screens films during term time in the Grove Auditorium.<ref name=\"magd societies\" /><ref name=\"mfilms\" /> The Magdalen College Music Society is a chapter of the [[Oxford University Music Society]] and incorporates a non-auditioned mixed choir, a [[chamber orchestra]], and a saxophone ensemble. The society performs recitals in college on Thursdays during term time.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://oums.org/colleges/magdalen/ |title=Magdalen College Music Society |publisher=Oxford University Music Society |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Magdalen College Trust is an independent charity that is funded by annual subscriptions from students and fellows. It encourages college members to engage in charity work, and funds charitable causes.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/living-here/societies/the-magdalen-college-trust/ |title=The Magdalen College Trust |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://apps.charitycommission.gov.uk/Showcharity/RegisterOfCharities/CharityWithoutPartB.aspx?RegisteredCharityNumber=1161056&SubsidiaryNumber=0 |title=1161056 - MAGDALEN COLLEGE TRUST CIO |publisher=Charity Commission |accessdate=22 February 2020}}\n</ref>\n\n===Academia===\nIn the [[Norrington Table]]'s history Magdalen has been top three times, in 2010, 2012 and 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Magdalen top of the 2012 Norrington Table|url=http://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/nested_content/listings/home_-_news/news/magdalen-top-of-the-2012-norrington-table|publisher=Magdalen College|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120823094744/http://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/nested_content/listings/home_-_news/news/magdalen-top-of-the-2012-norrington-table|archivedate=2012-08-23}}</ref> When over half its finalists achieved firsts in 2010, it claimed the record for the highest ever Norrington Score.<ref>{{cite web|title=Magdalen top of the Norrington table|url=http://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/nested_content/listings/archived-news/events/magdalen-top-of-norrington-table|publisher=Magdalen College|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120823111640/http://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/nested_content/listings/archived-news/events/magdalen-top-of-norrington-table|archivedate=2012-08-23}}</ref>\n\nMagdalen College students set the record in the ''[[University Challenge]]'' television competition, winning on four occasions (1997, 1998, 2004, and 2011).<ref>[http://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/nested_content/listings/home_-_events/events/magdalen-wins-university-challenge-for-a-record-fourth-time Magdalen Wins University Challenge for a Record Fourth Time \u2013 Magdalen College<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110424040443/http://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/nested_content/listings/home_-_events/events/magdalen-wins-university-challenge-for-a-record-fourth-time |date=2011-04-24 }}</ref>\n\n===Sports===\nMagdalen members have access to a variety of sports facilities. The sports grounds, accessible from the main college via Addison's Walk, include pitches for cricket, soccer, hockey, and rugby; also available on site are tennis courts and squash courts. In addition, the college buys gym membership at the Iffley Road sports complex on behalf of all its students. The college keeps a boathouse on [[The Isis]] (the length of the [[Thames]] as it passes through Oxford) for the [[Magdalen College Boat Club]] (MCBC).<ref name=\"student life\" />\n\nThe MCBC, a [[rowing (sport)|rowing]] club, was founded in 1859. It participates in the two annual Oxford [[bumps race]]s, [[Eights Week]] and [[Torpids]]. In recent history, the MCBC mens rowers won Eights Week between 2004 and 2007, and the Torpids most recently in 2008 (for the mens rowers) and 2016 (women's).<ref name=\"mcbc history\">{{cite web |url=http://magdalenboatclub.co.uk/about-the-club.html |title=About the MCBC |publisher=Magdalen College Boat Club |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"bumps chart\">{{cite web |url=http://eodg.atm.ox.ac.uk/user/dudhia/rowing/bumps/ |title=Oxford Bump Charts |first=Anu |last=Dudhia |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs well as the MCBC, Magdalen College is represented by teams in football, hockey, rugby, netball, cricket, lacrosse, squash and pool, amongst others.<ref name=\"student life\" />\n\n==College stamp==\nA college stamp was issued in the 1960s and the 1970s to prepay local delivery of mail by the college porters. It was short-lived and only a few stamps exist. One on cover is known and is detailed in the ''Great Britain Philatelic Society Journal''.<ref>''Journal of the Great Britain Philatelic Society'', Volume 48, Number 4, July/August 2010, and Volume 49, Number 4, July/August 2011</ref>\n\n==Notable members==\n:''See also: [[List of alumni of Magdalen College, Oxford]] and [[:Category:Fellows of Magdalen College, Oxford]]''\n\n===Politics===\n[[File:Cardinal Thomas Wolsey.jpg|thumb|Portrait of Magdalen alumnus Cardinal Thomas Wolsey.]]\nMagdalen College has taught members of several royal families. These include [[Edward VIII|King Edward VIII]], who attended while [[Prince of Wales]] from 1912\u20131914, after which he left without graduating;<ref name=\"edward 8\">{{cite book |title=King Edward VIII |last=Ziegler |first=Philip |year=1991 |publisher=Knopf |chapter=The Youth |chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/kingedwardviii00zieg}}</ref> [[Jigme Khesar Namgyel Wangchuck]], the king of [[Bhutan]], who read for an MPhil in politics in 2000;<ref>{{cite web|title=His Royal Highness Crown Prince Dasho Jigme Khesar Namgyel Wangchuck|publisher=RAOnline|url=http://www.raonline.ch/pages/bt/pol/bt_polpenlop01.html|accessdate=6 November 2008}}</ref> and [[Al-Muhtadee Billah|Crown Prince Haji Al-Muhtadee Billah]], first in line to the throne of [[Brunei]], who enrolled in the Foreign Service Programme (now known as the Diplomatic Studies Programme) in 1995 under an assumed name.<ref name=\"THE billah\">{{cite news |url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/prince-is-given-special-favour/155639.article |title=Prince is given special favour |date=8 December 2000 |publisher=Times Higher Education}}</ref><ref name=\"indp billah\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/no-need-for-a-wedding-list-5351132.html |title=No need for a wedding list... |date=8 September 2004 |last=McGirck |first=Jan |publisher=Independent}}</ref>\n\nAmong the political figures taught at Magdalen was Cardinal [[Thomas Wolsey]], who studied theology. He graduated at 15, uncommonly early even for the time, but remained in Oxford for further study and eventually became a Fellow of Magdalen.<ref name=\"naked Wolsey\">{{cite book |title=Naked to mine enemies; the life of Cardinal Wolsey |last=Ferguson |first=Charles W. |year=1958 |publisher=Time Inc. |chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/nakedtomineenemi01ferg |chapter=3}}</ref> Wolsey rose from humble origins to become [[Lord Chancellor]] and the [[Archbishop of York]], obtaining great political power and becoming adviser to [[Henry VIII of England|King Henry VIII]]. Wolsey left a lasting legacy in Oxford by founding Cardinal College, which Henry VIII would complete and refound as [[Christ Church, Oxford|Christ Church]] after Wolsey's fall from power.<ref name=\"BHO christ church\">'Christ Church', in A History of the County of Oxford: Volume 3, the University of Oxford, ed. H E Salter and Mary D Lobel (London, 1954), pp. 228-238. British History Online http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/oxon/vol3/pp228-238 [accessed 16 February 2020].</ref>\n\nMore recent Magdalen alumni to become politicians include [[Malcolm Fraser]], former [[Prime Minister of Australia]], and [[John Turner]], former [[Prime Minister of Canada]].<ref name=\"magd famous alumni\">{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/discover-magdalen/history-of-college/famous-alumni/ |title=Famous Alumni |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref> Many [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|members of the UK Parliament]] have been alumni of Magdalen. In the current [[House of Commons]] sit alumni [[Jeremy Hunt (politician)|Jeremy Hunt]] MP and [[John Redwood]] MP.<ref>{{cite news |last=Walker |first=Tim |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/jeremy-hunt-rough-ride-for-the-smooth-operator-2017277.html |title=Jeremy Hunt: Rough ride for the smooth operator&nbsp;\u2013 Profiles&nbsp;\u2013 People |work=[[The Independent]] |date=3 July 2010 |accessdate=27 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.asc.ox.ac.uk/person/55?m1=3&m2=0 |title=The Rt Hon Sir John Redwood |publisher=All Souls College, Oxford |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref> In the [[House of Lords]] sit alumni [[William Hague|William Hague, Baron Hague of Richmond]], former [[Leader of the Conservative Party (UK)|Leader of the Conservative Party]]; [[Dido Harding|Dido Harding, Baroness Harding of Winscombe]]; [[John Hutton, Baron Hutton of Furness]]; [[Michael Jay, Baron Jay of Ewelme]]; [[Matt Ridley|Matt Ridley, 5th Viscount Ridley]]; and [[Stewart Wood, Baron Wood of Anfield]], former Tutorial Fellow.<ref name=\"magd famous alumni\" />\n\n===Arts===\n====Literature====\n[[File:Oscar Wilde portrait.jpg|thumb|Oscar Wilde.]]\n[[Joseph Addison]], for whom Addison's walk is named, was a Fellow of Magdalen during the 17th century. He is known for his play ''[[Cato, a Tragedy]]'' based on the life of [[Cato the Younger]] at the end of the [[Roman Republic]]. Popular with the American [[Founding Fathers]], the play may have served as a literary inspiration for the [[American Revolution]].<ref name=\"cato\">{{cite news |title=On Life, Liberty and Other Quotable Matters |last=Miller |first=John J. |date=2 July 2011 |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702304314404576411721705429718 |publisher=The Wall Street Journal}} {{pay}}</ref>\n\nThe 19th century poet, playwright, and [[Aestheticism|aesthete]] [[Oscar Wilde]] read [[Greats]] at Magdalen from 1874 to 1878. During this time, he won the University's Newdigate English Verse Prize and graduated with a [[British undergraduate degree classification#Variations of first-class honours|double first]].<ref name=\"alumni wilde\">{{cite web |url=https://www.alumni.ox.ac.uk/quad/article/when-oscar-wilde-came-oxford |title=When Oscar Wilde Came to Oxford |last=Mendelssohn |first=Mich\u00e8le |publisher=Oxford Alumni |date=17 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc wilde\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/history/historic_figures/wilde_oscar.shtml |title=Oscar Wilde (1854 - 1900) |publisher=BBC History |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref> After his time at Magdalen, he became famous for his works including ''[[The Picture of Dorian Gray]]'' and ''[[The Importance of Being Earnest]]''.\n\nWilde began an affair in 1891 with [[Lord Alfred Douglas|Alfred Douglas]], who was then himself a student at Magdalen. The disapproval of Douglas' father over Wilde's relationship with his son led to Wilde's prosecution and conviction in 1895 for [[Labouchere Amendment|\"gross indecency\"]], that is to say, homosexual behaviour, and a sentence to two years hard labour.<ref name=\"alumni wilde\" /><ref name=\"bbc wilde\" /> Wilde described \"the two great turning-points in my life were when my father sent me to Oxford, and when society sent me to prison\".<ref name=\"alumni wilde\" /> After his release from prison, Wilde moved to France and spent the last three years of his life in poverty. He was posthumously pardoned in 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/01/31/turings-law-thousands-convicted-gay-bisexual-men-receive-posthumous/ |title = Turing's Law: Oscar Wilde among 50,000 convicted gay men granted posthumous pardons |date = 31 January 2017 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] }}</ref>\n\nThe prolific author Sir [[Compton Mackenzie]] OBE, who wrote over one hundred novels, plays, and biographies, read modern history at Magdalen.<ref name=\"britannica mackenzie\">{{britannica |id=354846 |title=Compton Mackenzie}}</ref> He is known for his fiction, including ''[[Sinister Street]]''\u2014which features [[List of fictional Oxford colleges|St. Mary's College, Oxford]] as a stand-in for Magdalen<ref>{{cite book |title=My Life and Times |volume=2 |last=MacKenzie |first=Compton |year=1964 |publisher=Chatto & Windus}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Sylvia & Michael on Sinister Street |last=Platzer |first=David |year=2019 |journal=New Criterion |volume=37 |issue=6}}</ref>\u2014and ''[[The Monarch of the Glen (novel)|Monarch of the Glen]]''. Compton Mackenzie co-founded the [[Scottish National Party]] and was knighted in 1952.<ref name=\"britannica mackenzie\" />\n\n[[C. S. Lewis]], writer and alumnus of [[University College, Oxford|University College]], was a Fellow and English tutor at Magdalen for 29 years, from 1925 to 1954. Lewis was one of the [[Inklings]], an informal writing society that also included [[J. R. R. Tolkien]] and would meet in Lewis' rooms at Magdalen.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Oxford Inklings: Lewis, Tolkien and their circle |first=Colin |last=Duriez |year=2015 |publisher=Lion Books |chapter=Preface}}</ref> Under Lewis' tutelage was the future [[Poet Laureate of the United Kingdom|Poet Laureate]] Sir [[John Betjeman]]. Though Betjeman failed the maths portion of the entrance exams, he was offered a place to read English on the strength of his poetry, which had impressed the President of Magdalen and former [[Oxford Professor of Poetry|Professor of Poetry]] Sir [[Thomas Herbert Warren]]. Lewis and Betjeman had a difficult relationship and Betjeman struggled academically. Betjeman left having failed to obtain a degree in 1928, but was made a [[doctor of letters]] by the university in 1974.<ref name=\"betjeman\">{{cite journal |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090417002131/http://www.oxfordtoday.ox.ac.uk/2005-06/v18n3/05.shtml |archive-date=17 April 2009 |url=http://www.oxfordtoday.ox.ac.uk/2005-06/v18n3/05.shtml |title=The dilettante and the dons |year=2006 |journal=Oxford Today |volume=18 |issue=3}}</ref>\n\n[[Seamus Heaney]], who received the [[Nobel Prize in Literature]] in 1995, was a Fellow of Magdalen from 1989 to 1994.<ref name=\"heaney\">{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/discover-magdalen/history-of-college/famous-alumni/professor-seamus-heaney/ |title=Professor Seamus Heaney |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Theatre====\n[[File:Katie Mitchell, 2016.jpg|thumb|Director Katie Mitchell in 2016.]]\nThe director [[Peter Brook]] CBE is both an alumnus and honorary Fellow of Magdalen. He was described in 2008 as \"our greatest living theatre director\".<ref name=\"indp brook\">{{cite news |last=Taylor |first=Paul |title=Peter Brook: The director who wrote the book |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/theatre-dance/features/peter-brook-the-director-who-wrote-the-book-919192.html |accessdate=16 February 2020 |publisher=The Independent |date=5 September 2008}}</ref> Fellow director [[Katie Mitchell]] OBE read English at Magdalen, and is known for her collaborations with [[Martin Crimp]]. In 2017, she received the [[President's Medal (British Academy)|President's Medal]] of the [[British Academy]] for her work in contemporary theatre and opera, and she has been described as British theatre's \"king in exile\".<ref name=\"katie mitchell\">{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/alumni-news/katie-mitchell-wins-british-academy-award/ |title=Katie Mitchell wins British Academy Award |date=5 October 2017 |accessdate= 16 February 2020 |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford}}</ref><ref name=\"katie mitchell2\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2016/jan/14/british-theatre-queen-exile-katie-mitchell |title=Katie Mitchell, British theatre's queen in exile |last=Higgins |first=Charlotte |date=14 January 2016 |work=The Guardian |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Music====\nIn 1957, the [[organ (music)|organist]] and composer [[Bernard Rose (musician)|Bernard Rose]] OBE was appointed Magdalen's Informator Choristarum, choir master.<ref name=\"indp bernardrose\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary-bernard-rose-1312755.html |title=Obituary: Bernard Rose |date=3 December 1996 |last=Dunnett |first=Roderic |work=Independent}}</ref> Among his students were [[Harry Christophers]] CBE, a composer and an artistic director for the [[Handel and Haydn Society]] who was an [[Choral scholar|academical clerk]] and later honorary Fellow at Magdalen;<ref name=\"harrychristophers\">{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/news/harry-christophers-becomes-honorary-fellow/ |title=Harry Christophers becomes Honorary Fellow |date=8 May 2009 |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford}}</ref> and [[Dudley Moore]] CBE, comedic actor and jazz musician, who studied at Magdalen on an [[organ scholar]]ship.<ref name=\"indp bernardrose\" /><ref name=\"telegraph dudleymoore\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1389041/Dudley-Moore.html |title=Dudley Moore |date=28 March 2002 |work=The Telegraph}}</ref>\n\n[[Andrew Lloyd Webber|Andrew Lloyd Webber, Baron Lloyd-Webber]], composer of [[musicals]] including ''[[Evita (musical)|Evita]]'' and ''[[The Phantom of the Opera]]'', studied history at Magdalen for a term in 1965, before dropping out to pursue music at the [[Royal Academy of Music]].<ref>{{cite book |title=How to Analzye the Works of Andrew Lloyd Webber |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LISu9S6HyqgC&pg=PA13 |last=Marsico |first=Katie |year=2010 |pages=13\u201314 |publisher=ABDO|isbn = 9781616135331}}</ref> Andrew Lloyd Webber has received a number of awards for his work, including a lifetime achievement [[Tony Award]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thestage.co.uk/news/2018/andrew-lloyd-webber-receive-lifetime-achievement-prize-years-tony-awards/ |title=Andrew Lloyd Webber to receive lifetime achievement prize at this year's Tony Awards |work=The Stage |last=Hemey |first=Matthew |date=23 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Humanities===\n[[File:Hormuzd.Rassam.reclined.jpg|right|250px|thumb|Hormuzd Rassam in Mosul c. 1854.]]\n[[Hormuzd Rassam]], the native [[Assyriologist]], studied at Magdalen for 18 months between accompanying archaeologist Sir [[Austen Henry Layard]] on his first and second expeditions. When Layard retired from archaeology, the [[British Museum]] appointed Rassam to continue on his own. Rassam made several important discoveries: in 1853 at [[Nineveh]], Rassam discovered the clay tablets that contained the ''[[Epic of Gilgamesh]]''; in 1879 he discovered the [[Cyrus Cylinder]] in the ruins of [[Babylon]]; and in 1880-1881 he uncovered the city of [[Sippar]]. He was the first Middle Eastern archaeologist, but his contributions were dismissed by some of his contemporaries and by the end of his life, his name had been removed from plaques and visitor guides at the British Museum. Layard would describe him as \"one whose services have never been acknowledged\".<ref name=\"bbc Rassam\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-31941827 |title=The men who uncovered Assyria |last=Adamson |first=Daniel Silas |date=22 March 2015 |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe economist [[Michael Spence|A. Michael Spence]] attended Magdalen on a Rhodes Scholarship, and graduated with a BA in mathematics in 1967. In 2001, he shared the [[Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences]] for his work on [[Information flow (information theory)|information flows]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.nobelprize.org/prizes/economic-sciences/2001/spence/biographical/|title=A. Michael Spence|work=Les Prix Nobel|editor=Tore Fr\u00e4ngsmyr|publisher=Nobel Foundation, Nobel Media AB|accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref> He is an honorary fellow at Magdalen.<ref name=\"people at magd\">{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/people-at-magdalen/ |title=People at Magdalen |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nPhilosopher [[A. C. Grayling]] CBE read for his DPhil at Magdalen, completing his studies in 1981. In 2011, he founded the [[New College of the Humanities at Northeastern|New College of the Humanities]].<ref name=\"indp acgrayling\">{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/education/education-news/professor-a-c-grayling-whatever-happened-to-the-most-hated-man-in-academia-8894704.html |title=Professor A C Grayling: Whatever happened to the most hated man in academia? |last=Garner |first=Richard |date=21 October 2013 |work=Independent}}</ref> An [[analytic philosophy|analytic philosopher]], Grayling is known for his criticism of religion, including in his 2013 book ''[[The God Argument]]'', and his arguments for voting reform, as in his 2017 book ''Democracy and Its Crises''.\n\n[[Niall Ferguson]], a well-known historian, also studied at Magdalen.\n\n===Sciences===\n[[File:Peter Brian Medawar.jpg|thumb|Peter Medawar, Nobel laureate and organ transplant pioneer.]]\nMagdalen counts among its alumni several recipients of the [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine]]. Sir [[Howard Florey]] was an Australian pharmacologist who studied at Magdalen on a [[Rhodes Scholarship]], graduating in 1924. He shared the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1945 for the development of [[penicillin]].<ref name=\"florey\">{{cite web |title=Sir Howard Florey Biographical, from Nobel Lectures |publisher=Elsevier |url=https://www.nobelprize.org/prizes/medicine/1945/florey/biographical/ |year=1964 |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref> Sir [[Peter Medawar]] CBE read for a BA in zoology at Magdalen, receiving a first, and later for a DPhil, supervised by Florey. His research into tissue grafting and immune rejection led to the discover of [[acquired immune tolerance]] and became the basis of organ transplantation. For this work, he shared the 1960 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine.<ref name=\"medawar\">{{cite web |title=Sir Peter Medawar Biographical, from Nobel Lectures |publisher=Elsevier |url=https://www.nobelprize.org/prizes/medicine/1960/medawar/biographical/ |year=1964 |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nLike Florey before him, Australian neurophysiologist Sir [[John Eccles (neurophysiologist)|John Eccles]] also came to Magdalen on a Rhodes Scholarship, where he read for his [[DPhil]]. He was taught by an earlier neurophysiologist who received the Nobel in 1932, Sir [[Charles Scott Sherrington]], who held the [[Waynflete Professorship]] in Physiology at Magdalen. In 1963 Eccles received the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for his research into [[synapse]]s. Eccles was also known for his contributions to philosophy, writing on the [[mind-body problem]] and becoming an honorary member of the [[American Philosophical Society]].<ref name=\"eccles\">{{cite web |title=Sir John Eccles Biographical, from Nobel Lectures |publisher=Elsevier |url=https://www.nobelprize.org/prizes/medicine/1963/eccles/biographical/ |year=1972 |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nSir [[Peter J. Ratcliffe]] held the [[Nuffield Professor of Clinical Medicine|Nuffield Professorship of Clinical Medicine]] between 2003 and 2006, and is still a supernumerary fellow at Magdalen.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/member-of-staff/peter-ratcliffe/ |title=Professor Sir Peter Ratcliffe |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref> He shared the 2019 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for his work on the oxygen sensing of cells.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nobelprize.org/prizes/medicine/2019/summary/ |title=The Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine 2019 |publisher=Nobel Media AB |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref> Other former Nuffield Professors of Clinical Medicine include Sir [[David Weatherall]], who founded the Weatherall Institute of Molecular Medicine in 1989,<ref name=\"weatherall obit\">{{cite journal |url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(19)30113-8/fulltext |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(19)30113-8 |title=David John Weatherall |last=Watts |first=Geoff |year=2019 |volume=393 |issue=10169 |page=314 |journal=The Lancet}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imm.ox.ac.uk/about |title=About us |publisher=MRC Weatherall Institute of Molecular Medicine |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref> and Sir [[John Bell (physician)|John Bell]] GBE, who is also an alumnus of the college.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.roche.com/about/governance/board_of_directors/board_of_directors-bell.htm |title=Prof. Sir John Irving Bell |publisher=F. Hoffmann-La Roche Ltd |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref> The current holder of the chair is [[Richard Cornall]], who was appointed in 2019.<ref name=\"richard cornall\">{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/news/new-nuffield-professor-of-clinical-medicine/ |title=New Nuffield Professor of Clinical Medicine |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |accessdate=1 March 2020 |date=8 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nTwo Fellows of Magdalen have been awarded the [[Nobel Prize in Physics]]: [[Erwin Schr\u00f6dinger]] in 1933, while he was a Fellow;<ref name=\"magd shrodinger\">{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/discover-magdalen/history-of-college/famous-alumni/dr-erwin-schrodinger/ |title=Dr Erwin Schr\u00f6dinger |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref> and [[Anthony James Leggett]] KBE in 2003, who had been a Fellow from 1963 to 1967.<ref name=\"magd leggett\">{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/discover-magdalen/history-of-college/famous-alumni/professor-anthony-leggett/ |title=Professor Anthony Leggett |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nDue to Magdalen's close relationship with Oxford's Botanic Garden and as the home of the [[Sherardian Professor of Botany|Sherardian Chair of Botany]], Magdalen has been associated with many accomplished botanists. Historic Sherardian Professors include [[John Sibthorp]], in whose name the [[Sibthorpian Professor of Plant Sciences|Sibthorpian Professorship of Rural Economy]], later known as the Sibthorpian Professorship of Plant Sciences, was founded; and [[Charles Daubeny]], who also held the [[Aldrichian Chairs|Aldrichian Chair of Chemistry]] and founded the Daubeny laboratory.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://plants.jstor.org/stable/10.5555/al.ap.person.bm000153994 |title=Sibthorp, John (1758-1796) |work=Global Plants}}</ref><ref name=\"historyOfDaubenyLab\" /> The Sherardian Chair has been held since 2009 by [[Liam Dolan]], who studies the emergence of land plants.<ref name=\"dolan rs\">{{cite web |url=https://royalsociety.org/people/liam-dolan-11347/ |title=Liam Dolan |publisher=The Royal Society - Fellows Directory |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"dolan\">{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/member-of-staff/liam-dolan/ |title=Professor Liam Dolan |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nLikewise, many distinguished scientists have held Waynflete Professorships at Magdalen. These include the mathematician [[J. H. C. Whitehead]], who held the Waynflete Professorship of Pure Mathematics between 1947 and 1960. During this time, he was also the president of the [[London Mathematical Society]], which established the [[Whitehead Prize|Whitehead]] and [[Senior Whitehead Prize|Senior Whitehead]] prizes in his honour. He is remembered for his fundamental contributions to topology.<ref name=\"whitehead\">{{cite journal |journal=Nature |year=1960 |title=Prof. J. H. C. Whitehead, F.R.S. (obituary) |last=James |first=I. N. |volume=186 |issue=932 |doi=10.1038/186932a0 }}</ref><ref name=\"lms whitehead prizes\">{{cite web |url=https://www.lms.ac.uk/prizes/lms-prize-regulations |title=LMS prizes - details and regulations |publisher=London Mathematical Society |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref> The chair was held from 1984 until he retired in 2006 by [[Daniel Quillen]], who received the [[Fields Medal]] for his work in [[algebraic K-theory]].<ref name=\"indp quillen\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2011/jun/23/daniel-quillen-obituary |title=Daniel Quillen obituary |first=Graeme |last=Segal |date=23 June 2011 |work=The Independent |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref> It is currently held by [[Ben Green (mathematician)|Ben Green]].<ref name=\"bengreen\">{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/member-of-staff/ben-green/ |title=Professor Ben Green |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery heights=\"200px\" widths=\"250px\">\nFile:Magdalen College - statues in the cloister.jpg|Two of the Cloister's hieroglyphics, the lion and the pelican, in front of the Senior Common Room.\nFile:Magdalen College cloister.jpg|Panorama across the Cloister. On the left is the Founder's Tower. \nFile:Magdalen College, view from the cloister.jpg|View of Founder's Tower from the Cloister.\nFile:Magdalen College, Oxford-15320233952.jpg|View of Founder's Tower from St. John's Quad. \nFile:Magdalen College, Oxford.jpg|The Cloister\nFile:Oxford - panoramio (38).jpg|View of the Great Tower from the Daubeny Laboratory, across [[High Street, Oxford|the High]]. \nFile:Magdalen Cloisters and New Buildings.jpg|Position of the New Building and lawns behind the Cloister\nFile:Oxford magdalen college lodgings.jpg|View of the Cloister and Great Tower from the New Building\nFile:Magdalen_College,_view_of_cloisters_from_Addison's_Walk,_Oct_2016.jpg|The Great Tower and cloister, viewed from Addison's Walk\nFile:Oxford magdalen college cour.jpg|St. John's Quad, showing (left to right) the gate to St. Swithun's quad, the Grammar Hall, and the President's Lodgings.\nFile:UK-2014-Oxford-Magdalen College 02.jpg|Gateway to St. Swithun's Quad (St. Swithun's Tower). \nFile:Magdalen College Oxford Old Grammar Hall.jpg|The old Grammar Hall\nFile:UK-2014-Oxford-Magdalen College 01.jpg|The President's Lodgings and Pride of India tree.\nFile:Magdalen College Muniment Tower.JPG|Muniment Tower.\nFile:Magdalen College - view on the tower and the chapel.jpg| St. John's Quad, showing (left to right) the President's Lodgings, Founder's Tower, Muniment Tower, the chapel, and the Great Tower behind.  \nFile:Ancient Door, Magdalen College, Oxford by Henry Fox Talbot.jpg|''Ancient Door, Magdalen College, Oxford'' by [[Henry Fox Talbot]], circa 1843, showing the western door to the chapel beneath the window depicting the Last Judgment.\nFile:Oxford magdalen college chapelle int.JPG|Interior of the chapel.\nFile:Arthur Foxton Ferguson - Academic Clerkship Magdalen College Oxford ca. 1898 (fourth from left in back row).jpg|The choir of Magdalen College ca. 1898\nFile:Oxford MagdalenCollege Gate&Ranges.jpg|Gate between the High and St. John's Quad. The Porter's Lodge is on the right.\nFile:Longwall Street, Oxford, looking south.jpg|Boundary wall along Longwall Street. \nFile:Magdalen college oxford waynflete building.jpg|The Waynflete Building, on the east side of Magdalen Bridge.\nFile:Y sculpture.jpg|''Y'' by Mark Wallinger in Bat Willow Meadow</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Magdalen College, Oxford}}\n* [http://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/ Official site]\n* [http://www.chem.ox.ac.uk/oxfordtour/magdalencollege/ Virtual Tour of Magdalen College]\n* [http://www.magdalencollegechoir.com Website of Magdalen College Choir]\n* [http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Gazetteer/Places/Europe/Great_Britain/England/Oxfordshire/Oxford/_Texts/FLEOXF/1*.html Fletcher's History of Oxford: Magdalen College]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060820005730/http://www.ofchoristers.net/Chapters/OxfordMagdelen.htm A history of the choristers of Magdalen Chapel, Oxford]\n* [http://magdmcr.co.uk/ Website of Magdalen Middle Common Room]\n\n{{University of Oxford}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1458 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in the 15th century]]\n[[Category:Colleges of the University of Oxford]]\n[[Category:Grade I listed buildings in Oxford]]\n[[Category:Grade I listed educational buildings]]\n[[Category:Magdalen College, Oxford|*]]\n[[Category:Organisations based in Oxford with royal patronage]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures of the University of Oxford]]\n[[Category:Mary Magdalene]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Magdalen College||Magdalen College (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox residential college\n| name           = Magdalen College\n| full_name      = The College of St Mary Magdalen in the University of Oxford\n| university     = [[University of Oxford|Oxford]]\n| photo          = File:Magdalen-may-morning-2007-panorama.jpg\n| caption        = Magdalen College during [[May Morning]], 2007, showing the Tower and Chapel exterior. \n| scarf          = {{scarf|{{cells|3|#000}}{{cells|3|white}}{{cells|3|#000}}{{cells|3|white}}{{cells|3|#000}}}}\n| latin_name     = Collegium Beatae Mariae Magdalenae\n| motto          = ''Floreat Magdalena''\n| named_for      = [[Mary Magdalene]]\n| established    = 1458\n| sister_college = [[Magdalene College, Cambridge]]\n| president      = Sir [[David Clary]] FRS\n| undergraduates = 411<ref>{{cite web|title = Student numbers December 2013|publisher = University of Oxford|url = http://www.ox.ac.uk/about/facts-and-figures/student-numbers}}</ref> (2013)\n| graduates      = 159\n| endowment =  \u00a3273.2&nbsp;million <small>(2018)</small><ref name=\"magdalen1718\">{{cite web|url=http://d307gmaoxpdmsg.cloudfront.net/collegeaccounts1718/Magdalen.pdf|title=Magdalen College : Report and Financial Statements for the Year Ended 31 July 2018|website= ox.ac.uk |page=26|access-date=5 March 2019}}</ref>\n| location       = [[Longwall Street]] and [[High Street, Oxford|High Street]]\n| coordinates    = {{coord|51.752374|-1.247077|display=inline,title}}\n| location_map   = Oxford (central)\n| shield         = [[File:Magdalen College Oxford Coat Of Arms (Motto).svg|150px]]\n| blazon         = ''Lozengy ermine and sable, on a chief of the second three lilies argent slipped and seeded or''\n| homepage       = {{URL|http://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/}}\n| boat_club      = [http://www.magdalenboatclub.co.uk/ Boatclub website]\n}}\n\n'''Magdalen College''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|m|\u0254\u02d0|d|l|\u1d7b|n}} {{Respell|MAWD|lin}})<ref name=Names>{{cite web|work=First Names Dictionary on AskOxford.com|title=Magdalen (Name)|url=http://www.askoxford.com/firstnames/magdalen?view=uk|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607031814/http://www.askoxford.com/firstnames/magdalen?view=uk|archivedate=7 June 2011}}</ref> is a [[Colleges of the University of Oxford|constituent college]] of the [[University of Oxford]]. It was founded in 1458 by [[William of Waynflete]].<ref name=\"College History\">{{cite web|url= http://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/discover-magdalen/history-of-college|title= College History| publisher=magd.ox.ac.uk|access-date=22 March 2019}}</ref> Today, it is one of the wealthiest colleges, with a [[financial endowment]] of \u00a3273.2 million as of 2018,<ref name=\"magdalen1718\"/> and one of the strongest academically, setting the record for the highest [[Norrington Table|Norrington Score]] in 2010 and topping the table twice since then.<ref name=\"norrtable\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ox.ac.uk/about/facts-and-figures/undergraduate-degree-classifications|title=Undergraduate Degree Classifications {{!}} University of Oxford|website=www.ox.ac.uk|accessdate=13 September 2019}}</ref> It is home to several of the University's distinguished [[Chair (academic)|chairs]], including the [[Serena Professor of Italian#Serena Professors at Oxford|Agnelli-Serena Professorship]], the [[Sherardian Professor of Botany|Sherardian Professorship]], and the four [[Waynflete Professorship|Waynflete Professorships]].\n\nThe large, square [[Magdalen Tower, Oxford|Magdalen Tower]] is an [[Oxford]] landmark, and it is a tradition, dating to the days of [[Henry VII of England|Henry VII]], that the college choir sings from the top of it at 6&nbsp;a.m. on [[May Morning]].<ref name=\"world and its people\">{{Cite book\n|last = Dunton\n|first = Larkin\n|title = The World and Its People\n|publisher = Silver, Burdett\n|year = 1896\n|page = 55}}</ref> The college stands next to the [[River Cherwell]] and the [[University of Oxford Botanic Garden|Oxford botanic garden]], and within its grounds has a [[deer]] park and [[Addison's Walk]].\n\n==History==\n=== Foundation ===\nMagdalen College was founded in 1458 by [[William of Waynflete]], Bishop of [[Winchester, England|Winchester]] and Lord Chancellor <ref name=\"College History\" /> and named after [[St Mary Magdalene]]. The College succeeded a [[Colleges_of_the_University_of_Oxford#Medieval_Halls|university hall]] called Magdalen Hall, founded by Waynflete in 1448, and from which the college drew most of its earliest scholars.<ref name=\"BHO magdalen\" /> This first Magdalen Hall was suppressed when the college was founded; though the name was revived by a second Magdalen Hall, established in the college's grounds around 1490, which in the 19th century would move to Catte Street and become [[Hertford College, Oxford|Hertford College]].<ref name=\"Magdalen Hall\">{{cite web|url=http://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/libraries-and-archives/archives/magdalen-hall/|title=Magdalen Hall| publisher=magd.ox.ac.uk|access-date=21 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"brockliss85\">{{cite book |title=The University of Oxford: A History |page=85 |last=Brockliss |first=Lawrence W. B. |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-924356-3|year=2016 }}</ref> \nAlso established by Waynflete on the college site was a Grammar School, now [[Magdalen College School, Oxford|Magdalen College School]], an [[independent school (United Kingdom)|independent school]] located nearby on the other side of the Cherwell. Waynflete was assisted by a large bequest from Sir [[John Fastolf]], who wished to fund a religious college.<ref name=\"fastolf\">{{cite journal |title=Memorandum Quod: John Fastolf and the Founding of Magdalen College |year=2003 |journal=Magdalen College Record |last=Rose |first=Jonathan |pages=98\u2013105|ssrn=1426349 }}</ref> \n\nMagdalen College took over the site of St John the Baptist Hospital, alongside the [[River Cherwell|Cherwell]], initially using the hospital's buildings until new construction was completed between 1470-1480.<ref name=\"BHO sjh\" /> At incorporation in 1458, the college consisted of a president and six scholars. In 1487 when the Founder's Statutes were written, the foundation consisted of a President, forty fellows, thirty [[demyship|demies]], four chaplain priests, eight clerks, sixteen choristers, and appointed to the Grammar School, a Master and an usher.<ref name=\"BHO magdalen\" />\n\nThe founder's statutes included provision for a choral foundation of men and boys (a tradition that has continued to the present day) and made reference to the pronunciation of the name of the college in English. The college's name is pronounced like the adjective [[maudlin]] because the late medieval English name of Mary Magdalene was Maudelen, derived from the Old French Madelaine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.etymonline.com/word/maudlin|publisher=Online Etymology Dictionary|title=Maudlin (adj.)|access-date=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===English Civil War===\n\nOxford and Magdalen College were supporters of the [[Cavalier|Royalist]] cause during the [[English Civil War]]. In 1642, Magdalen College donated over 296 [[Pound (mass)|lbs]] of plate to fund the war effort - the largest donation by weight of any Oxford college.<ref name=\"plate\">{{cite book |title=Heraldry, Pageantry and Social Display in Medieval England |editor1-first=Peter R. |editor1-last=Coss |editor2-first=Maurice |editor2-last=Keen |chapter=7. Medieval Founders' Relics: Royal and Episcopal Patronage at Oxford and Cambridge Colleges|last=Campbell |first=Marian |date=2003 |publisher=Boydell Press}}</ref> Magdalen College, commanding a position on the banks of the Cherwell that overlooked [[Magdalen Bridge]] and the road from London, had tactical significance for the King's forces. Royalist ordnance was parked in the Magdalen's Grove, and [[Prince Rupert]] is thought to have quartered in the college.<ref name=\"BHO magdalen\" /> During the first [[Siege of Oxford]], [[Charles I of England|Charles I]] surveyed the battle from [[Magdalen Tower]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Walker|first=Sir Edward|author-link=Edward Walker (officer of arms)|year=1705|title=Historical Discourses, Upon Several Occasions|location=London|pages=16\u201321|nopp=y|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=d-ExAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA16#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>\n\n===Expulsion of the Fellows===\n[[File:The Expulsion of the Fellows, 1687 - Joseph Tonneau (1884).jpg|thumb|''The Expulsion of the Fellows, 1687'' by Joseph Tonneau (1884).]]\nDuring the 1680s, [[James II of England|King James II]] made several moves to reintroduce [[Roman Catholicism|Catholicism]] into the then [[Anglican]] university.<ref name=\"brockliss208210\">{{cite book |title=The University of Oxford: A History |pages=208\u2013210 |last=Brockliss |first=Lawrence W. B. |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-924356-3|year=2016 }}</ref> In 1687, he attempted to install [[Anthony Farmer]] as [[Master (college)|president]] of Magdalen. The [[fellow]]s rejected this, not just because Farmer was reputedly a Catholic and had a tarnished reputation, but also as he was not a fellow of the college, and therefore ineligible under the statutes.<ref name=\"brockliss208210\" /><ref name=\"BHO magdalen\" /> The fellows elected instead one of their own, [[John Hough (bishop)|John Hough]]. James eventually offered a compromise candidate in the form of the moderate [[Samuel Parker (bishop of Oxford)|Bishop of Oxford, Samuel Parker]],<ref name=\"brockliss208210\" /> but he too was rejected by the fellows as they considered the role filled.<ref name=\"corrie\">{{cite book |title=Brief Historical Notices of the Interference of the Crown with the Affairs of the English Universities |pages=70\u201385 |last=Corrie |first=George Elwes |year=1839 |publisher=J. & J. J. Deighton}}</ref><ref name=\"restorationbuttery\">{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/libraries-and-archives/treasure-of-the-month/news/buttery-book-and-restoration/ |title=Illuminating Magdalen: A Magdalen College Buttery Book and the Restoration of the Fellows of Magdalen |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |access-date=2 February 2020 |date=30 October 2015}}</ref> Parker was admitted by force<ref name=\"BHO magdalen\" /> and the fellows and [[Demyship|demies]] (scholars) who had defied the king were expelled, replaced by the king's choice of Catholics or moderate Anglicans. Parker died in 1688 and was replaced by [[Bonaventure Giffard]], a Catholic under whose tenure the Chapel converted to Catholicism. The expulsion of the fellows marked a turning point in the University's relationship with the Crown: Brockliss writes, \"the royalist and Anglican University established at the Restoration had had to make a choice and it had chosen Anglicanism.\"<ref name=\"brockliss208210\" /> James' interference with the college fed resentment in Anglicans who used it as evidence that his rule was autocratic.<ref name=\"brockliss208210\" /><ref name=\"restorationbuttery\" /> On 25 October 1688, shortly before the [[Glorious Revolution]] and overthrow of James II by [[William III of England|William of Orange]], James' appointments were reversed and Hough and the expelled fellows were restored to the college.<ref name=\"brockliss208210\" /><ref name=\"restorationbuttery\" /> This event is marked every year at a special banquet, the Restoration Dinner, for Magdalen fellows, demies, and academic clerks.<ref name=\"restorationbuttery\" />\n\n===20th-21st centuries===\n\nMagdalen's prominence since the mid-20th century owes much to such famous fellows as [[C. S. Lewis]] and [[A. J. P. Taylor]], and its academic success to the work of such dons as [[Thomas Dewar Weldon]].<ref>[[R.W. Johnson]], ''Look Back in Laughter: Oxford's Postwar Golden Age'', Threshold Press, 2015.</ref> During [[World War II]], [[RAF Maintenance Command]] was headquartered at Magdalen.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sofo.org.uk/colleges |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-11-06 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20121224193959/http://www.sofo.org.uk/colleges |archivedate=24 December 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>  \n\nMagdalen College owns and manages the [[Oxford Science Park]] to the south of Oxford, a science and technology park home to over 100 companies. The Oxford Science Park opened in 1991, with Magdalen as part owner. The college acquired the rest of the ownership in 2016.<ref name=\"OSP history\">{{cite web |url=https://oxfordsp.com/our-story/ |title=Our Story |publisher=Oxford Science Park |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"OSP 2016\">{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/news/magdalen-acquires-100-of-oxford-science-park/ |title=Magdalen Acquires 100% of Oxford Science Park |date=12 January 2016 |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref> \n\nLike many of Oxford's colleges, Magdalen admitted its first mixed-sex cohort in 1979, after more than half a millennium as a men-only institution.<ref name=\"College History\"/> Between 2015 and 2017, 47.2% of UK undergraduates admitted to Magdalen were from state schools; 12.2% were of BME heritage and 0.7% were black.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ox.ac.uk/sites/files/oxford/Annual%20Admissions%20Statistical%20Report%202018.pdf|title=Annual Admissions Statistical Report May 2018|website=www.ox.ac.uk}}</ref> Of the 300 undergraduate offers made by Magdalen between 2017 and 2019, 25 (one in twelve) went to pupils from Eton College or Westminster School.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/01/12/one-12-offers-made-single-oxford-college-have-gone-pupils-two/|title=One in 12 offers made by a single Oxford college have gone to pupils from two elite private schools}}</ref> In 2015, Magdalen topped Oxford's [[Norrington Table]] of college undergraduate examination results, and its average score over the 2006\u20132016 period is the best among the colleges.\n\n==Buildings==\n[[File:Magdalen College Oxford campus map.svg|thumb|Map of Magdalen College buildings and grounds, marked out in black.]]\nThe college grounds stretch north and east from the college, and include most of the area bounded by [[Longwall Street]], the [[High Street, Oxford|High Street]] (where the [[porter's lodge]] is located), and [[St Clement's, Oxford|St Clement's]]. The college features a variety of architectural styles, and has been described as \"a medieval nucleus with two incomplete additions, one from the eighteenth and one from the nineteenth century\".<ref name=\"unbuiltoxford\" /> \n\nThe college is organised around five quads. The irregularly shaped St John's Quad is the first on entering the college, and includes the Outdoor Pulpit and old Grammar Hall. It connects to the Great Quad (the Cloister) via the Perpendicular Gothic [[Founders Tower]], which is richly decorated with carvings and pinnacles and has carved bosses in its vault. The Chaplain's Quad runs along the side of the Chapel and Hall, to the foot of the [[Magdalen Tower|Great Tower]]. St Swithun's Quad and Longwall Quad (which contains the Library) date from the late 19th and early 20th centuries, and make up the southwest corner of the college. \n\n===Original buildings===\nThe college is built on the site of St John the Baptist Hospital, which was dissolved in 1457 and its property granted to William of Waynflete.<ref name=\"BHO sjh\">'Hospitals: St John the Baptist, Oxford', in A History of the County of Oxford: Volume 2, ed. William Page (London, 1907), pp. 158-159. British History Online http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/oxon/vol2/pp158-159 [accessed 5 February 2020].</ref> Some of the hospital buildings were reused by the college, and the kitchens survive today as the college bar, the Old Kitchen Bar.<ref name=\"BHO magdalen\">\"Magdalen College\", in ''A History of the County of Oxford: Volume 3'', the University of Oxford, ed. H. E. Salter and Mary D. Lobel (London, 1954), pp. 193-207. British History Online http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/oxon/vol3/pp193-207 [accessed 5 February 2020].</ref><ref name=\"okb\">{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/conferences/old-kitchen-bar/ |title=Old Kitchen Bar |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |access-date=5 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nNew construction began in 1470 with the erection of a wall around the site by mason [[William Orchard (architect)|William Orchard]]. Following this, Orchard also worked on the chapel, hall, and the cloister, including the Muniment and [[Founders Tower|Founder's Tower]]s, with work completed around 1480.<ref name=\"BHO magdalen\" />\n\n===Cloister===\n[[File:Magdalen College, Oxford (7958644740).jpg|thumb|View across the Cloister. The far side is the hall (left) and chapel, behind is the Great Tower.]]\nThe Cloister or Great Quad is the \"medieval nucleus\" of the college. It was constructed between 1474 and 1480, also by Orchard, although several modifications were made later. Access to the Cloister from St John's Quad is via the [[Founders Tower|Founder's Tower]] or Muniment Tower. The chapel and the hall make up the southern side of the quad. It is also home to the junior, middle, and senior common rooms, and the old library. \n\nIn 1508, [[grotesques]] known as hieroglyphics were added to the Cloister. These are thought to be allegorical, and include four hieroglyphics in front of the old library that represent scholarly subjects: science, medicine, law, and theology.<ref name=\"grotesques\">{{citation |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/libraries-and-archives/treasure-of-the-month/news/library-hieroglyphics/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200110205526/https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/libraries-and-archives/treasure-of-the-month/news/library-hieroglyphics/ |title=Library Hieroglyphics|archive-date=10 January 2020 |date=29 July 2016 |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford}}</ref><ref name=\"slatterguide\">{{cite book |title=The Oxford University and City Guide |last=Slatter |first=H |year=1834 |pages=32\u201333 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=aSRbAAAAcAAJ&dq=magdalen+cloister+boxers}}</ref> The other hieroglyphics have been assigned symbolism relating to virtues that should be encouraged by the college (e.g. the lion and pelican grotesques in front of the Senior Common Room representing courage and parental affection) or vices that should be avoided (the [[manticore]], boxers, and [[lamia]] in front of the Junior Common Room, representing pride, contention, and lust).<ref name=\"slatterguide\" /> In 2017, repair work was undertaken to restore the severely damaged boxers statue.<ref name=\"boxers statue\">{{cite web |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205210132/https://www.alexwenham.co.uk/boxers-statue-magdalen-college-oxford/ |url=https://www.alexwenham.co.uk/boxers-statue-magdalen-college-oxford/ |title=Boxers Statue, Magdalen College Oxford |access-date=5 February 2020 |archive-date=5 February 2020}}</ref> \n\nIn 1822, the north side of the Cloister was knocked down, ostensibly due to disrepair. This decision was controversial, provoking protests from the fellows and in the contemporary press, and it was rebuilt shortly afterwards.<ref name=\"unbuiltoxford\" /><ref name=\"BHO magdalen\" />\n\nIn the early 1900s, renovations were performed, and it was returned to a more medieval character. Student rooms were installed in the (very large) roof space in the 1980s.\n\n===Chapel===\n[[File:Magdalen College Chapel Interior, Oxford, UK - Diliff.jpg|thumb|The interior of the chapel, showing Wyatt's plaster roof]]\n\nThe chapel is a [[place of worship]] for members of the college and others in the University of Oxford community and beyond. As a [[High Anglican]] chapel, its tradition is influenced by the [[Catholic Revival]] in the [[Church of England]]. Said and sung services are held daily during term.<ref name=\"Services\">{{cite web|url=http://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/chapel-and-choir/services|title=Chapel Services|publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford}}</ref> The choir sings Choral [[Evening Prayer (Anglican)|Evensong]] or Evening Prayer every day at 6:00 pm except on Mondays.<ref name=\"Services\"/> On Sundays, a Sung Eucharist is offered in the morning at 11:00 am, whilst [[Compline]] (Night Prayer) is sung several times per term.<ref name=\"Services\"/> Mass is also sung on major holy days.<ref name=\"Services\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/chapel-and-choir|title=Chapel & Choir|publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford}}</ref>\n\nThe chapel itself is a grade I [[listed building]] built between 1474\u20131480.<ref name=\"chapellisted\">{{cite web|url=https://historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1369672|title=MAGDALEN COLLEGE, CHAPEL, GREAT QUADRANGLE|publisher=Historic England}}</ref> The roof, giving the impression of a stone vaulted ceiling, is in fact a facsimile made from plaster added in 1790 by [[James Wyatt]]. Wyatt's redevelopment of the chapel included a number of modifications to make it more Gothic in character, but other than the ceiling, Wyatt's contributions were removed during a later redesign in 1828.<ref name=\"chapellisted\" /><ref name=\"unbuiltoxford\" /><ref name=\"georgiangothic\">{{cite book|title=Georgian Gothic: Medievalist Architecture, Furniture and Interiors, 1730-1840|first=Peter|last=Lindfield|pages=168\u2013169|isbn=9781783271276|publisher=Boydell & Brewer|year=2016}}</ref>\n\nThe [[stained glass]] windows facing St John's Quad feature a ''[[grisaille]]'' depiction of the [[Last Judgement]]. These windows, dating from 1792, are a reconstruction by [[Francis Eginton]] of an earlier 17th-century window that was destroyed in a storm.<ref name=\"indpressurection\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/the-resurrection-at-magdalen-college-1279624.html |title=The resurrection at Magdalen College |last=Popham |first=Peter |date=20 February 1997 |work=The Independent |access-date=2 February 2020}}</ref> It had been uninstalled during [[World War II]] to protect it from damage, and was only restored in the 1990s. Much of the glass had been thought lost, until it was rediscovered in the ventilation tunnels under the New Building.<ref name=\"indpressurection\" />\n\n===Magdalen Tower===\n[[File:UK-2014-Oxford-Magdalen College 08.jpg|right|thumb|Magdalen College Tower.]]\n{{further|Magdalen Tower}}\nConstruction of Magdalen's Great Tower began in 1492 by another mason, William Raynold. It might have been intended to replace an existing bellfry remaining from the hospital, and probably was originally envisioned to stand alone. By the time it was completed in 1509, additional buildings had been built either side, creating the roughly triangular Chaplain's quad between the chapel and the High.<ref name=\"BHO magdalen\" /> \n\nThe tower contains a peal of ten bells hung for [[Change ringing|English change ringing]]. They were cast at a number of different [[foundry|foundries]] and the heaviest, weighing 17 [[hundredweight|cwt]], was cast in 1623.<ref>[http://dove.cccbr.org.uk/detail.php?DoveID=OXFORD+CMA Magdalen College Bells], Dove's Guide for Church Bell Ringers.</ref> \n\nThe tower is 144 feet tall and an imposing landmark on the eastern approaches to the city centre.<ref name=\"websitecollegebuildings\" /> It has been the model for other towers, including Mitchell Tower of the [[University of Chicago]],<ref name=\"mitchell\">{{cite journal|title=Architectural Details|date=December 2002|publisher=University of Chicago|url=http://magazine.uchicago.edu/0212/alumni/arch.html|accessdate=April 30, 2006|journal=The University of Chicago Magazine|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060518050733/http://magazine.uchicago.edu/0212/alumni/arch.html|archive-date=May 18, 2006|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Manhattan]]'s [[First Presbyterian Church (Manhattan)|First Presbyterian Church]],<ref>{{Cite book|author-link  = David W. Dunlap |author-last  = Dunlap |author-first = David W. |year = 2004 |title  = From Abyssinian to Zion: A Guide to Manhattan's Houses of Worship |location = New York |publisher = [[Columbia University Press]] |isbn = 0-231-12543-7}}</ref>, and All Saints' Church in [[Churchill, Oxfordshire]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Sherwood |first1=Jennifer |last2=Pevsner |first2=Nikolaus |authorlink2=Nikolaus Pevsner |year=1974 |title=Oxfordshire |series=[[Pevsner Architectural Guides#Buildings of England|The Buildings of England]]}}</ref> It forms the centre of the [[May Morning]] celebrations in Oxford.\n\n===The New Building===\n[[File:Oxford magdalen college new building.jpg|thumb|right|The New Building.]]\nDuring the 18th and 19th centuries, there were numerous attempts made to redesign the site to better suit the College's needs.<ref name=\"unbuiltoxford\">{{cite book|last=Colvin|first=Sir Howard|authorlink=Howard Colvin|title=Unbuilt Oxford|publisher=[[Yale University Press]]|isbn=0-300-03126-2|year=1983|chapter-url-access=registration|chapter=VII Indecision at Magdalen|pages=[https://archive.org/details/unbuiltoxford0000colv/page/78 78-104]|chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/unbuiltoxford0000colv/page/78}}</ref> The New Building began construction in 1733 as a part of [[Edward Holdsworth]]'s designs from 1731. It is built in a [[Palladian architecture|Palladian style]], and features a [[colonnade]].\n\nIt was conceived as one side of a new \"Great Quadrangle\", and in anticipation of this the building's ends had been left unfinished. However, Holdsworth's full vision was never completed. The idea was revisited several times by later architects, including by architects [[James Wyatt]]\u2014who plans (never realised) included partially demolishing the existing, Medieval quad (the Cloister) and refinishing the neoclassical New Building in a [[Gothic revival architecture|Georgian Gothic]] style\u2014and [[John Buckler]].<ref name=\"unbuiltoxford\" /><ref name=\"georgiangothic\" /> In the 19th Century, [[John Nash (architect)|John Nash]] and [[Humphrey Repton]] both submitted designs for new, open quadrangles that incorporated the New Building.<ref name=\"unbuiltoxford\" />\n\nUltimately, the idea of integrating the New Building into a new quad was abandoned, and the ends of the building were finally completed in 1824 with two returns designed by [[Thomas Harrison (architect)|Thomas Harrison]].<ref name=\"unbuiltoxford\" /> Today, it stands apart from the Cloister, overlooking four [[croquet]] lawns on one side and the Grove deer park on the other. It is used for accommodation for undergraduates and fellows, including historically [[Edward Gibbon]] and [[C. S. Lewis]], and also houses the wine cellar.<ref name=\"ugliving\">{{cite web|url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/living-here/undergraduate-living-here/|title=As an Undergraduate|publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford}}</ref>\n\n===Daubeny laboratory===\n[[File:Daubeny lab plate, Magdalen College Oxford.png|thumb|Illustration of the Daubeny Laboratory as it looked c. 1870.]]\nOpposite the main college site and overlooking the [[University of Oxford Botanic Garden|Botanic Garden]] is the 19th century Daubeny Laboratory.<ref name=\"websitecollegebuildings\" />\n\nThe Garden had been established between 1622 and 1633 as a [[physic garden]] (that is, a garden to study the medicinal value of plants) on land inherited by Magdalen from St. John's Hospital.<ref name=\"historyOfDaubenyLab\">{{cite book|title=A history of the Daubeny Laboratory, Magdalen College, Oxford |url=https://archive.org/details/historyofdaubeny00guntuoft/page/i/mode/2up|url-access=registration|date=1904|last=Gunter|first=Robert Theodore}}</ref> The Daubeny Laboratory, and neighbouring Professor's House, were founded by the [[polymath]] and Magdalen fellow [[Charles Daubeny]] after he was appointed to the [[Sherardian Professor of Botany|Sherardian Chair of Botany]] in 1834.<ref name=\"historyOfDaubenyLab\" />\n\nDaubeny set about a number of additions to the location, erecting new glasshouses and in 1836 creating an on-site residence for the Professor of Botany. This replaced an earlier residence that had been demolished in 1795 when the road was widened. The new residence was an extension of the library, which had been created out of a glasshouse by an earlier Sherardian professor, [[John Sibthorp]], to house the Sherard [[herbarium]]. After Daubeny's death, this was assimilated to house the growing collection.<ref name=\"historyOfDaubenyLab\" /><ref name=\"sherardHerbarium\">{{cite web |url=https://herbaria.plants.ox.ac.uk/bol/sherard/DBnotes |title=Notes on the Sherard Herbarium database |access-date=3 February 2020 |publisher=Department of Plant Sciences, University of Oxford}}</ref> Later, it became accommodation for graduate students, the Professor's House, while the Sherard Herbarium is now part of the Fielding-Druce Herbarium held in the [[Department of Plant Sciences, University of Oxford|Department of Plant Sciences]].<ref name=\"FDHerbarium\">{{cite web |url=https://herbaria.plants.ox.ac.uk/bol/oxford/OXF |title=Fielding-Druce Herbarium |access-date=3 February 2020 |publisher=Department of Plant Sciences, University of Oxford}}</ref>\n\nDaubeny, who was also the [[Aldrichian Chairs|Aldrichian Professor of Chemistry]], had found the chemistry laboratory in the basement of the old [[Ashmolean Museum]], what is now the [[History of Science Museum, Oxford|History of Science Museum]], to be \"notoriously unworthy of a great University\" and desired a better science facility. He petitioned the College to be allowed to build one, and the Daubeny laboratory was completed in 1848.<ref name=\"historyOfDaubenyLab\" /><ref name=\"brockliss313314\">{{cite book |title=The University of Oxford: A History |pages=313\u2013314 |last=Brockliss |first=Lawrence W. B. |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-924356-3|year=2016 }}</ref> The Daubeny Laboratory was preceded by the anatomy school and laboratory at [[Christ Church, Oxford|Christ Church]] which opened in 1767, and would be followed later in the century by other college laboratories including the [[Balliol-Trinity Laboratories]].<ref name=\"chemistry\">{{cite book|title=Chemistry at Oxford: A History from 1600 to 2005|author1=Robert Joseph Paton Williams |author2=Allan Chapman |author3=John Shipley Rowlinson |page=275 | publisher=Royal Society of Chemistry |date=6 November 2008|isbn= 978-0854041398 }}</ref> Daubeny's laboratory was a two-storey room with benches and cupboards encircled by a gallery, and became the principal chemistry lab for the University. In 1902, due to growing student numbers and poor ventilation, the laboratory trappings were removed and it was refitted as a lecture hall.<ref name=\"historyOfDaubenyLab\" /> In 1973, most of the Daubeny Laboratory building was reconfigured into graduate student accommodation.<ref name=\"magdPapersDaubeny\">{{cite web |url=https://archive-cat.magd.ox.ac.uk/records/FA19 |title=PAPERS ON BUILDINGS IN THE BOTANICAL GARDENS, c. 1800-200 |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford, archive catelogue |access-date=3 February 2020}}</ref> The Daubeny lab itself is now a conference space.\n\n===St Swithun's quad===\n[[File:Magdalen College, Oxford-8086510626.jpg|thumb|A view from the Great Tower of St Swithun's Quad, and behind it Longwall Quad.]]\n\nIn 1880\u20131884, the college extended westwards onto the former site of [[Magdalen Hall]]. The hall was an independent university hall that developed from Magdalen College School, not the earlier Magdalen Hall founded by William Waynflete.<ref name=\"Magdalen Hall\" /> Most of Magdalen Hall's buildings were destroyed by fire in 1820, though the Grammar Hall survived and was restored by Joseph Parkinson.<ref name=\"unbuiltoxford\" /> The hall moved to Catte Street in 1822 and was incorporated as [[Hertford College, Oxford|Hertford College]] in 1874.<ref name=\"Magdalen Hall\" />\n\nThe new construction, [[Swithun|St Swithun]]'s quad<ref name=\"websitecollegebuildings\">{{cite web|url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/discover-magdalen/history-of-college/history-of-the-college-buildings/ |title=The College Buildings |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |access-date=3 February 2020}}</ref> (sometimes given as St. Swithin's quad<ref name=\"unbuiltoxford\" /><ref name=\"swithlist\">{{cite web|url=https://historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1046707 |title=MAGDALEN COLLEGE, ST SWITHINS QUADRANGLE |publisher=Historic England |access-date=3 February 2020}}</ref>), was designed by [[George Frederick Bodley]] and [[Thomas Garner]] in keeping with the Gothic style. They had originally designed three sides of a square, though only the south and west sides were built. In 1928, [[Giles Gilbert Scott]] extended the building north and westwards, forming the adjacent Longwall quad.<ref name=\"unbuiltoxford\" />\n\n===Modern buildings and acquisitions===\n[[File:Magdalen college oxford grove buildings.jpg|thumb|The Grove Buildings, including the auditorium (left), were completed in 1999.]]\nSeveral new additions to the college were made in the late 20th century. The Waynflete Building, which is located across Magdalen Bridge from the main college site, was designed by [[Booth, Ledeboer, and Pinckheard]] and completed in 1964.<ref name=\"RIBA Waynflete\">{{cite web|url=https://www.architecture.com/image-library/RIBApix/gallery-product/poster/waynflete-building-magdalen-college-oxford/posterid/RIBA11414.html|title=Waynflete Building, Magdalen College, Oxford|publisher=architecture.com|accessdate=20 December 2018}}</ref> Magdalen has a number of additional annexes near to the main site for accommodation, including in Cowley Place and [[Longwall Street]]. \n\nThe Grove Buildings, located north of Longwall quad between Longwall Street and the Grove, were built in 1994-1999 by [[Porphyrios Associates]]. They are home to accommodation, Magdalen's 160-seat auditorium, and the Denning Law Library.<ref name=\"websitecollegebuildings\" /><ref name=\"auditorium\">{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/conferences/grove-auditorium/ |title=Grove Auditorium |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |access-date=6 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"libraries\" /> During term time, the auditorium hosts film screenings organised by the Magdalen Film Society.<ref name=\"mfilms\">{{cite web |url=https://www.mfsoxford.com/ |title=Magdalen Film Society |access-date=6 February 2020}}</ref> \n\nAlong Addison's Walk is the Holywell Ford site, where most of the graduate accommodation is located. Holywell Ford house was built by [[Clapton Crabb Rolfe]] in 1888 on the location of an older mill, and was acquired by Magdalen in the 1970s.<ref name=\"holywell ford\">{{cite web |url=http://www.oxfordhistory.org.uk/holywell/misc/holywell_mill.html |publisher=Oxford History |title=Holywell Mill and the Holly Well, Oxford |last=Jenkins |first=Stephanie |access-date=6 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920185626/http://www.oxfordhistory.org.uk/holywell/misc/holywell_mill.html |archive-date=20 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"he holywell\">{{cite web |url=https://historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1369449 |title=Hollywell Ford |publisher=Historic England |access-date=6 February 2020}}</ref> Additional blocks of accommodation were built in 1994-5 by RH Partnership Ltd.<ref name=\"websitecollegebuildings\" />\n\n===Libraries===\n[[File:03-Magdalen-College.jpg|thumb|The redeveloped Longwall Quad. The main Longwall Library building is on the left.]]\nIn addition to the University's central and departmental libraries, Oxford's colleges maintain their own libraries. The original college library, the Old Library, is located in the Cloister and accessed via Founder's Tower or the President's Lodgings. It contains a large collection of manuscripts from before the 19th century. Consultation of material is typically by appointment, although the Old Library itself may be visited by the public during certain exhibitions.<ref name=\"libraries\">{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/libraries-and-archives/libraries/ |title=Magdalen's Libraries |website=Magdalen College}}</ref><ref name=\"womenlibraryexhibition\">{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/libraries-and-archives/news/new-exhibition-opening-in-september-women-and-power-a-magdalen-story/ |title=New exhibition opening in September: \"Women and Power? A Magdalen Story\" |website=Magdalen College Library and Archives}}</ref> \n\nIn 1931, the New Library, now called the Longwall Library, was established in the former [[Magdalen College School, Oxford|Magdalen College School]] building in Longwall Quad and became the college's main library for students. It was opened by [[Edward VIII]] when he was a student at Magdalen.<ref name=\"telegraphWilliam\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/05/11/prince-william-follows-in-edward-viiis-footsteps-by-opening-new/ |last=Rayner |first=Gordon |date=11 May 2016 |title=Prince William follows in Edward VIII's footsteps by opening new library at Oxford's Magdalen College |work=The Telegraph}}</ref> It was renovated between 2014 and 2016 by [[Wright & Wright Architects]] and reopened by [[Prince William, Duke of Cambridge]].<ref name=\"archdaily\">{{cite web |url=https://www.archdaily.com/882330/longwall-library-magdalen-college-wright-and-wright-architects |title=Longwall Library - Magdalen College / Wright & Wright Architects |website=Arch Daily}}</ref><ref name=\"telegraphWilliam\" />\n\nIn addition, the college maintains the Denning Law Library in the Grove building, a reference library for Magdalen's law students, and the specialist Daubeny and McFarlane collections of 19th century scientific works and medieval history works respectively. Items from the Daubeny and McFarlane libraries may be brought to the Longwall Library for consultation on request.<ref name=\"libraries\" />\n\n==Grounds==\n\n===The Grove===\n[[File:Magdalen Deer.jpg|thumb|right|The deer in the Grove]]\nThe Grove or deer park is large meadow which occupies most of the north west of the college's grounds, from the New Building and the Grove Buildings to Holywell Ford. During the winter and spring, it is the home of a herd of [[fallow deer]]. It is possible to view the meadow and the deer from the path between New Buildings and Grove Quad, and also from the archway in New Buildings.\n\nIn the 16th century, long before the introduction of the deer, the grove consisted of gardens, orchards, and [[bowling green]]s. During the [[English Civil War|Civil War]], it was used to house a regiment of soldiers. At one point in the 19th century it was home to three traction engines belonging to the works department of the college.  By the 20th century it had become well-wooded with many large trees, but most of them were lost to [[Dutch elm disease]] in the 1970s.\n\n===Water meadow and Addison's Walk===\n[[File:Magdalen college oxford water meadow flooded 1.jpg|thumb|Water meadow after winter flooding. The New Building is visible side on in the background.]]\nThe water meadow is a [[flood-meadow]] to the eastern side of the College, bounded on all sides by the [[River Cherwell|Cherwell]]. In wet winters, some or all of the meadow may flood, as the meadow is lower lying than the surrounding path. All around the edge of the meadow is a tree-lined path, [[Addison's Walk]], named for the fellow [[Joseph Addison]] (1672-1719), which connects to Holywell Ford and the Fellows' Garden.<ref name=\"flora and fauna grounds\" />\n\nAddison's Walk is popular with College members and visitors. [[C. S. Lewis]] wrote a poem about the walk, ''Chanson d'Aventure'' or ''What the Bird Said Early in the Year'', which is commemorated on a plaque near the gate to Holywell Ford.<ref name=\"flora and fauna grounds\">{{cite web |url=http://florafauna.magd.ox.ac.uk/magdalen-grounds/ |title=Magdalen Grounds - Flora and Fauna |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206200223/http://florafauna.magd.ox.ac.uk/magdalen-grounds/ |archive-date=6 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"addisons lewis1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cslewisinstitute.org/What_the_Bird_Said_Early_in_the_Year_FullArticle |title=Knowing & Doing Summer 2015 - What the Bird Said Early in the Year |publisher=C. S. Lewis Institute |last=Kohm |first=Joseph A. |year=2015 |access-date=6 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"addisons lewis2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.thegospelcoalition.org/blogs/justin-taylor/c-s-lewiss-poem-what-the-bird-said-early-in-the-year/ |title=C.S. Lewis's Poem, \"What the Bird Said Early In The Year\" |publisher=The Gospel Coalition |last=Taylor |first=Justin |date=25 February 2016 |access-date=6 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThanks to the frequent flooding, the meadow is one of the few places in the [[UK]] that the snake's head fritillary, ''[[Fritillaria meleagris]]'', may be seen growing wild.<ref name=\"telegraph fm\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/gardening/plants/10741803/Fritillaries-dont-forget-these-lilies-of-the-field.html |title=Fritillaries: don't forget these lilies of the field |last=Slade |first=Naomi |date=6 April 2014 |work=The Telegraph}}</ref> These flowers grow in very few places, and have been recorded growing in the meadow since around 1785.<ref name=\"telegraph fm\" /> Once the flowering has finished, the deer herd is moved in for the summer and autumn.\n\n===Bat Willow meadow and the Fellows' Garden===\n[[File:Magdalen college oxford fellows garden.jpg|thumb|The Fellows' Garden.]]\nFurther east of the water meadow are Bat Willow meadow and the Fellows' Garden. They are separated from the water meadow and each other by other branches of the Cherwell, and may be accessed from Addison's Walk. Bat Willow meadow features ''Y'', a 10 metre high sculpture of a branching tree by [[Mark Wallinger]], commissioned for the College's 550th anniversary in 2008. <ref name=\"wallinger news\">{{cite news |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/news/new-mark-wallinger-sculpture-unveiled/ |title=New Mark Wallinger sculpture unveiled |date=22 July 2008 |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |access-date=8 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"wallinger microsite\">{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/wallinger/further.html |title=Y by Mark Wallinger |access-date=8 February 2020 |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford}}</ref> Due to their age and infection with [[honey fungus]], the [[willow]] trees were cut down in 2018 and replanted, and the wood used to make [[cricket bats]].<ref name=\"bat willow\">{{cite news |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/news/replanting-bat-willow-meadow/ |title=Replanting Bat Willow Meadow |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |date=31 October 2018 |access-date=8 February 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe Fellows' Garden is located further north along the bank of the Cherwell than Bat Willow meadow, directly behind the [[Oxford Centre for Islamic Studies]]. This long and narrow garden follows the Cherwell to the edge of the [[University Parks]]. In spring, the ground is covered with flowers. In summer, there are some flowers, many different shrubs, and the varied trees provide dappled cover from the sun. \n\nFurther north is [[Magdalen Ground|Magdalen's sports ground]].\n\n==Choir==\n[[File:William Holman Hunt - May Morning on Magdalen College, Oxford, Ancient Annual Ceremony - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|''May Morning on Magdalen Tower'' by [[William Holman Hunt]] (1890).]]\nMagdalen is one of the three choral foundations in Oxford, meaning that the formation of the choir was part of the statutes of the college, the other choral foundations being [[New College, Oxford|New College]] and [[Christ Church, Oxford|Christ Church]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ox.ac.uk/admissions/undergraduate_courses/applying_to_oxford/choral_organ/choralorgan.html|title=Choral and organ scholarships|publisher=University of Oxford}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ox.ac.uk/admissions/undergraduate_courses/applying_to_oxford/choral_organ/choral.html|title=Choral scholarships|publisher=University of Oxford|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130902104027/http://www.ox.ac.uk/admissions/undergraduate_courses/applying_to_oxford/choral_organ/choral.html|archivedate=2013-09-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.music.ox.ac.uk/admissions/organ-and-choral-scholarships1/Organandchoralscholarships-main-page.html|title=Organ and Choral Scholarships|publisher=Oxford University Faculty of Music|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130423132522/http://www.music.ox.ac.uk/admissions/organ-and-choral-scholarships1/Organandchoralscholarships-main-page.html|archivedate=2013-04-23}}</ref>\n\nThe choir consists of 12 [[Clerk (choral)|academical clerks]], or choral scholars, who are students at the college, and 16 boys aged seven to thirteen (some of whom stay on until age fourteen), all of whom have scholarships at [[Magdalen College School, Oxford|Magdalen College School]]. The school was founded for this purpose but has long since become an independent public school.\n\nThe choristers' day begins at 7:30, with an early morning practice before school. There is further practice immediately after school, followed by Choral Evensong six nights a week, in term; the Tuesday service is sung by the boys only, and the Friday service only by the Academical Clerks. On Sundays there is a practice at 9:30 am followed by Eucharist, then a further afternoon practice followed by Evensong which ends at 7:00 pm. As of September 2010, the choristers no longer sing on most Saturday evenings following the formation of the Consort of Voices, a mixed voice choir which sings on most Saturdays in full term.\n\nThe choir records regularly. In 2005, it was nominated for a [[Grammy Award]] for its [[Compact disc|CD]], ''With a Merrie Noyse'', of music by [[Orlando Gibbons]]. Other recent works include the BBC's ''[[The Blue Planet]]'' and Paul McCartney's classical piece ''[[Ecce Cor Meum]]''. The choir has numerous college duties as well as a recording and touring schedule. Traditionally the choir sings at college [[Gaudy|Gaudies]] and at other special events throughout the year, as well as performing on social occasions such as Carols by Candlelight before Christmas and the famous [[May Morning]]. \n\n===May Morning===\n{{main|May Morning}}\nAnnually at 6 a.m. on 1 May, the choir perform [[Hymnus Eucharisticus]] from the top of Magdalen's Tower to crowds below on Madgalen Bridge and the High Street. This tradition dates back 500 years, and forms the central event in Oxford's [[May Morning]] celebration. \n\n===Organists===\n{{See also|Organ scholar}}\nThe choir has had many well-known organists, such as [[Daniel Purcell]], Sir [[John Stainer]] (1860\u20131872) and [[Bernard Rose (musician)|Bernard Rose]] (1957\u20131981). Among the other notable former directors and masters of the choir, who hold the title of ''Informator Choristarum'', are [[John Sheppard (composer)|John Sheppard]] (1543\u2013c.1552), Sir [[William McKie (musician)|William McKie]], [[Haldane Campbell Stewart]] and the composer [[Grayston Ives|Bill Ives]] (1991\u20132009), possibly better known as a former King's Singer. A disc of his music, ''Listen Sweet Dove'', is amongst the choir's releases.\n\nThe current Informator Choristarum, since January 2017, is [[Mark Williams (organist)|Mark Williams]]. He succeeded Daniel Hyde, who had been organ scholar at King's College Cambridge, following Hyde's appointment as Organist and Director of Music of [[Saint Thomas Church (Manhattan)|Saint Thomas Church, New York]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/news/new-appointments-to-chapel-and-choir/|title=New Appointments to Chapel and Choir \u2013 Magdalen College Oxford|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nPast organ scholars include [[Dudley Moore]], Matthew Martin and [[Paul Brough (conductor)|Paul Brough]]. Past academical clerks include [[John Mark Ainsley]], [[Harry Christophers]] (founder and director of [[The Sixteen]]), [[James Whitbourn]], [[Robin Blaze]], [[Roderick Williams]] and conductor/composer [[Gregory Rose (musician)|Gregory Rose]].\n\n==Student life==\n\n===Accommodation===\n[[File:Magdalen college oxford holywell ford.jpg|thumb|Holywell Ford, as seen from Addison's Walk. Holywell Ford house and annexes are used as accommodation for graduate students.]]\nUndergraduate students of the college are guaranteed accommodation during term for their entire degree, typically in the Waynflete building in their first year and \"inside-walls\" in the Cloister, St Swithun's Quad, the New Building and so on in subsequent years. Graduate students are guaranteed at least two years of accommodation. Unlike undergraduates, graduates are not required to move out between terms and typically live \"outside walls\", including in Holywell Ford, the Daubeny Laboratory, and Professor's House.<ref name=\"ug living\">{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/living-here/undergraduate-living-here/ |title=As an Undergraduate |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"pg living\">{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/living-here/graduate-living-here/ |title=As a Graduate |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccommodation charges are inclusive of heating, power, and internet access, and weekly cleaning by the college [[Bedder|scouts]] (housekeepers), but does not include catering. Three cafeteria style meals a day are served in the hall, and other food is available in the Old Kitchen Bar.<ref name=\"ug living\" /><ref name=\"pg living\" />\n\nIn addition to a dinner cafeteria service served in the hall, three [[Formal (university)|Formal Halls]] are held a week during term time. These are three course sit-down dinners and require college members to wear their [[academic gown|gowns]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/glossary_page_item/formal-hall/ |title=Formal Hall |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford}}</ref> Additional banquets commemorate special occasions, including the Restoration Dinner.<ref name=\"restorationbuttery\" /><ref name=\"mcr activities\">{{cite web |url=http://magdmcr.co.uk/mcractivities/ |title=Activities |publisher=Magdalen College MCR |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Events and societies===\n[[File:Magdalen College Dining Hall, Oxford, UK - Diliff.jpg|thumb|Magdalen College dining hall, where students can eat meals, also hosts regular formal banquets.]]\nThe body of undergraduate and graduate students are known as the junior and middle common rooms (JCR and MCR) respectively. They each elect committees of students annually to organise welfare events, socials, and banquets.<ref name=\"student life\">{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/living-here/student-life/ |title=Student Life |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"mcr activities\" />\n\nIn addition to clubs and societies associated with the [[Oxford University Student Union]] operated at the university level, Magdalen members may also participate in several college societies.<ref name=\"magd societies\">{{cite web |url=http://magdmcr.co.uk/college-societies/ |title=Societies |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref> The Atkin Society and the Sherrington Society are two subject-specific societies, for law students and medicine students respectively. They organise talks and social events. The Atkin society is named for lawyer [[James Atkin, Baron Atkin]], a former demy at Magdalen, and also organises an annual [[moot court]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/living-here/societies/the-atkin-society/ |title=The Atkin Society |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref> The Sherrington Society is named after Nobel laureate Sir [[Charles Scott Sherrington]], former Waynflete Professor of Physiology.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/living-here/societies/the-sherrington-society/ |title=The Atkin Society |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref> The college also has a poetry discussion forum called the Florio Society, named for 16th century college alumnus [[John Florio]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/living-here/societies/the-florio-society/ |title=The Florio Society |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nA number of other societies put on events throughout the year. These include the Magdalen Players, a drama society; the Magdalen Music Society; and the Magdalen Film Society, which screens films during term time in the Grove Auditorium.<ref name=\"magd societies\" /><ref name=\"mfilms\" /> The Magdalen College Music Society is a chapter of the [[Oxford University Music Society]] and incorporates a non-auditioned mixed choir, a [[chamber orchestra]], and a saxophone ensemble. The society performs recitals in college on Thursdays during term time.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://oums.org/colleges/magdalen/ |title=Magdalen College Music Society |publisher=Oxford University Music Society |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Magdalen College Trust is an independent charity that is funded by annual subscriptions from students and fellows. It encourages college members to engage in charity work, and funds charitable causes.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/living-here/societies/the-magdalen-college-trust/ |title=The Magdalen College Trust |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://apps.charitycommission.gov.uk/Showcharity/RegisterOfCharities/CharityWithoutPartB.aspx?RegisteredCharityNumber=1161056&SubsidiaryNumber=0 |title=1161056 - MAGDALEN COLLEGE TRUST CIO |publisher=Charity Commission |accessdate=22 February 2020}}\n</ref>\n\n===Academia===\nIn the [[Norrington Table]]'s history Magdalen has been top three times, in 2010, 2012 and 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Magdalen top of the 2012 Norrington Table|url=http://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/nested_content/listings/home_-_news/news/magdalen-top-of-the-2012-norrington-table|publisher=Magdalen College|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120823094744/http://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/nested_content/listings/home_-_news/news/magdalen-top-of-the-2012-norrington-table|archivedate=2012-08-23}}</ref> When over half its finalists achieved firsts in 2010, it claimed the record for the highest ever Norrington Score.<ref>{{cite web|title=Magdalen top of the Norrington table|url=http://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/nested_content/listings/archived-news/events/magdalen-top-of-norrington-table|publisher=Magdalen College|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120823111640/http://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/nested_content/listings/archived-news/events/magdalen-top-of-norrington-table|archivedate=2012-08-23}}</ref>\n\nMagdalen College students set the record in the ''[[University Challenge]]'' television competition, winning on four occasions (1997, 1998, 2004, and 2011).<ref>[http://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/nested_content/listings/home_-_events/events/magdalen-wins-university-challenge-for-a-record-fourth-time Magdalen Wins University Challenge for a Record Fourth Time \u2013 Magdalen College<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110424040443/http://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/nested_content/listings/home_-_events/events/magdalen-wins-university-challenge-for-a-record-fourth-time |date=2011-04-24 }}</ref>\n\n===Sports===\nMagdalen members have access to a variety of sports facilities. The sports grounds, accessible from the main college via Addison's Walk, include pitches for cricket, soccer, hockey, and rugby; also available on site are tennis courts and squash courts. In addition, the college buys gym membership at the Iffley Road sports complex on behalf of all its students. The college keeps a boathouse on [[The Isis]] (the length of the [[Thames]] as it passes through Oxford) for the [[Magdalen College Boat Club]] (MCBC).<ref name=\"student life\" /> \n\nThe MCBC, a [[rowing (sport)|rowing]] club, was founded in 1859. It participates in the two annual Oxford [[bumps race]]s, [[Eights Week]] and [[Torpids]]. In recent history, the MCBC mens rowers won Eights Week between 2004 and 2007, and the Torpids most recently in 2008 (for the mens rowers) and 2016 (womens).<ref name=\"mcbc history\">{{cite web |url=http://magdalenboatclub.co.uk/about-the-club.html |title=About the MCBC |publisher=Magdalen College Boat Club |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"bumps chart\">{{cite web |url=http://eodg.atm.ox.ac.uk/user/dudhia/rowing/bumps/ |title=Oxford Bump Charts |first=Anu |last=Dudhia |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs well as the MCBC, Magdalen College is represented by teams in football, hockey, rugby, netball, cricket, lacrosse, squash and pool, amongst others.<ref name=\"student life\" />\n\n==College stamp==\nA college stamp was issued in the 1960s and the 1970s to prepay local delivery of mail by the college porters. It was short-lived and only a few stamps exist. One on cover is known and is detailed in the ''Great Britain Philatelic Society Journal''.<ref>''Journal of the Great Britain Philatelic Society'', Volume 48, Number 4, July/August 2010, and Volume 49, Number 4, July/August 2011</ref>\n\n==Notable members==\n:''See also: [[List of alumni of Magdalen College, Oxford]] and [[:Category:Fellows of Magdalen College, Oxford]]''\n===Politics===\n[[File:Cardinal Thomas Wolsey.jpg|thumb|Portrait of Magdalen alumnus Cardinal Thomas Wolsey.]]\nMagdalen College has taught members of several royal families. These include [[Edward VIII|King Edward VIII]], who attended while [[Prince of Wales]] from 1912-1914, after which he left without graduating;<ref name=\"edward 8\">{{cite book |title=King Edward VIII |last=Ziegler |first=Philip |year=1991 |publisher=Knopf |chapter=The Youth |chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/kingedwardviii00zieg}}</ref> [[Jigme Khesar Namgyel Wangchuck]], the king of [[Bhutan]], who read for an MPhil in politics in 2000;<ref>{{cite web|title=His Royal Highness Crown Prince Dasho Jigme Khesar Namgyel Wangchuck|publisher=RAOnline|url=http://www.raonline.ch/pages/bt/pol/bt_polpenlop01.html|accessdate=6 November 2008}}</ref> and [[Al-Muhtadee Billah|Crown Prince Haji Al-Muhtadee Billah]], first in line to the throne of [[Brunei]], who enrolled in the Foreign Service Programme (now known as the Diplomatic Studies Programme) in 1995 under an assumed name.<ref name=\"THE billah\">{{cite news |url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/prince-is-given-special-favour/155639.article |title=Prince is given special favour |date=8 December 2000 |publisher=Times Higher Education}}</ref><ref name=\"indp billah\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/no-need-for-a-wedding-list-5351132.html |title=No need for a wedding list... |date=8 September 2004 |last=McGirck |first=Jan |publisher=Independent}}</ref>\n\nAmong the political figures taught at Magdalen was Cardinal [[Thomas Wolsey]], who studied theology. He graduated at 15, uncommonly early even for the time, but remained in Oxford for further study and eventually became a Fellow of Magdalen.<ref name=\"naked Wolsey\">{{cite book |title=Naked to mine enemies; the life of Cardinal Wolsey |last=Ferguson |first=Charles W. |year=1958 |publisher=Time Inc. |chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/nakedtomineenemi01ferg |chapter=3}}</ref> Wolsey rose from humble origins to become [[Lord Chancellor]] and the [[Archbishop of York]], obtaining great political power and becoming adviser to [[Henry VIII of England|King Henry VIII]]. Wolsey left a lasting legacy in Oxford by founding Cardinal College, which Henry VIII would complete and refound as [[Christ Church, Oxford|Christ Church]] after Wolsey's fall from power.<ref name=\"BHO christ church\">'Christ Church', in A History of the County of Oxford: Volume 3, the University of Oxford, ed. H E Salter and Mary D Lobel (London, 1954), pp. 228-238. British History Online http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/oxon/vol3/pp228-238 [accessed 16 February 2020].</ref> \n\nMore recent Magdalen alumni to become politicians include [[Malcolm Fraser]], former [[Prime Minister of Australia]], and [[John Turner]], former [[Prime Minister of Canada]].<ref name=\"magd famous alumni\">{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/discover-magdalen/history-of-college/famous-alumni/ |title=Famous Alumni |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref> Many [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|members of the UK Parliament]] have been alumni of Magdalen. In the current [[House of Commons]] sit alumni [[Jeremy Hunt (politician)|Jeremy Hunt]] MP and [[John Redwood]] MP.<ref>{{cite news |last=Walker |first=Tim |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/jeremy-hunt-rough-ride-for-the-smooth-operator-2017277.html |title=Jeremy Hunt: Rough ride for the smooth operator&nbsp;\u2013 Profiles&nbsp;\u2013 People |work=[[The Independent]] |date=3 July 2010 |accessdate=27 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.asc.ox.ac.uk/person/55?m1=3&m2=0 |title=The Rt Hon Sir John Redwood |publisher=All Souls College, Oxford |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref> In the [[House of Lords]] sit alumni [[William Hague|William Hague, Baron Hague of Richmond]], former [[Leader of the Conservative Party (UK)|Leader of the Conservative Party]]; [[Dido Harding|Dido Harding, Baroness Harding of Winscombe]]; [[John Hutton, Baron Hutton of Furness]]; [[Michael Jay, Baron Jay of Ewelme]]; [[Matt Ridley|Matt Ridley, 5th Viscount Ridley]]; and [[Stewart Wood, Baron Wood of Anfield]], former Tutorial Fellow.<ref name=\"magd famous alumni\" />\n\n===Arts===\n====Literature====\n[[File:Oscar Wilde portrait.jpg|thumb|Oscar Wilde.]]\n[[Joseph Addison]], for whom Addison's walk is named, was a Fellow of Magdalen during the 17th century. He is known for his play ''[[Cato, a Tragedy]]'' based on the life of [[Cato the Younger]] at the end of the [[Roman Republic]]. Popular with the American [[Founding Fathers]], the play may have served as a literary inspiration for the [[American Revolution]].<ref name=\"cato\">{{cite news |title=On Life, Liberty and Other Quotable Matters |last=Miller |first=John J. |date=2 July 2011 |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702304314404576411721705429718 |publisher=The Wall Street Journal}} {{pay}}</ref>\n\nThe 19th century poet, playwright, and [[Aestheticism|aesthete]] [[Oscar Wilde]] read [[Greats]] at Magdalen from 1874 to 1878. During this time, he won the University\u2019s Newdigate English Verse Prize and graduated with a [[British_undergraduate_degree_classification#Variations_of_first-class_honours|double first]].<ref name=\"alumni wilde\">{{cite web |url=https://www.alumni.ox.ac.uk/quad/article/when-oscar-wilde-came-oxford |title=When Oscar Wilde Came to Oxford |last=Mendelssohn |first=Mich\u00e8le |publisher=Oxford Alumni |date=17 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc wilde\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/history/historic_figures/wilde_oscar.shtml |title=Oscar Wilde (1854 - 1900) |publisher=BBC History |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref> After his time at Magdalen, he became famous for his works including ''[[The Picture of Dorian Gray]]'' and ''[[The Importance of Being Earnest]]''. \n\nWilde began an affair in 1891 with [[Lord Alfred Douglas|Alfred Douglas]], who was then himself a student at Magdalen. The disapproval of Douglas' father over Wilde's relationship with his son led to Wilde's prosecution and conviction in 1895 for [[Labouchere Amendment|\"gross indecency\"]], that is to say, homosexual behaviour, and a sentence to two years hard labour.<ref name=\"alumni wilde\" /><ref name=\"bbc wilde\" /> Wilde described \"the two great turning-points in my life were when my father sent me to Oxford, and when society sent me to prison\".<ref name=\"alumni wilde\" /> After his release from prison, Wilde moved to France and spent the last three years of his life in poverty. He was posthumously pardoned in 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/01/31/turings-law-thousands-convicted-gay-bisexual-men-receive-posthumous/ |title = Turing's Law: Oscar Wilde among 50,000 convicted gay men granted posthumous pardons |date = 31 January 2017 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] }}</ref> \n\nThe prolific author Sir [[Compton Mackenzie]] OBE, who wrote over one hundred novels, plays, and biographies, read modern history at Magdalen.<ref name=\"britannica mackenzie\">{{britannica |id=354846 |title=Compton Mackenzie}}</ref> He is known for his fiction, including ''[[Sinister Street]]''\u2014which features [[List of fictional Oxford colleges|St. Mary's College, Oxford]] as a stand-in for Magdalen<ref>{{cite book |title=My Life and Times |volume=2 |last=MacKenzie |first=Compton |year=1964 |publisher=Chatto & Windus}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Sylvia & Michael on Sinister Street |last=Platzer |first=David |year=2019 |journal=New Criterion |volume=37 |issue=6}}</ref>\u2014and ''[[The Monarch of the Glen (novel)|Monarch of the Glen]]''. Compton Mackenzie co-founded the [[Scottish National Party]] and was knighted in 1952.<ref name=\"britannica mackenzie\" />\n\n[[C. S. Lewis]], writer and alumnus of [[University College, Oxford|University College]], was a Fellow and English tutor at Magdalen for 29 years, from 1925 to 1954. Lewis was one of the [[Inklings]], an informal writing society that also included [[J. R. R. Tolkien]] and would meet in Lewis' rooms at Magdalen.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Oxford Inklings: Lewis, Tolkien and their circle |first=Colin |last=Duriez |year=2015 |publisher=Lion Books |chapter=Preface}}</ref> Under Lewis' tutelage was the future [[Poet Laureate of the United Kingdom|Poet Laureate]] Sir [[John Betjeman]]. Though Betjeman failed the maths portion of the entrance exams, he was offered a place to read English on the strength of his poetry, which had impressed the President of Magdalen and former [[Oxford Professor of Poetry|Professor of Poetry]] Sir [[Thomas Herbert Warren]]. Lewis and Betjeman had a difficult relationship and Betjeman struggled academically. Betjeman left having failed to obtain a degree in 1928, but was made a [[doctor of letters]] by the university in 1974.<ref name=\"betjeman\">{{cite journal |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090417002131/http://www.oxfordtoday.ox.ac.uk/2005-06/v18n3/05.shtml |archive-date=17 April 2009 |url=http://www.oxfordtoday.ox.ac.uk/2005-06/v18n3/05.shtml |title=The dilettante and the dons |year=2006 |journal=Oxford Today |volume=18 |issue=3}}</ref>\n\n[[Seamus Heaney]], who received the [[Nobel Prize in Literature]] in 1995, was a Fellow of Magdalen from 1989 to 1994.<ref name=\"heaney\">{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/discover-magdalen/history-of-college/famous-alumni/professor-seamus-heaney/ |title=Professor Seamus Heaney |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Theatre====\n[[File:Katie Mitchell, 2016.jpg|thumb|Director Katie Mitchell in 2016.]]\nThe director [[Peter Brook]] CBE is both an alumnus and honorary Fellow of Magdalen. He was described in 2008 as \"our greatest living theatre director\".<ref name=\"indp brook\">{{cite news |last=Taylor |first=Paul |title=Peter Brook: The director who wrote the book |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/theatre-dance/features/peter-brook-the-director-who-wrote-the-book-919192.html |accessdate=16 February 2020 |publisher=The Independent |date=5 September 2008}}</ref> Fellow director [[Katie Mitchell]] OBE read English at Magdalen, and is known for her collaborations with [[Martin Crimp]]. In 2017, she received the [[President's Medal (British Academy)|President's Medal]] of the [[British Academy]] for her work in contemporary theatre and opera, and she has been described as British theatre's \"king in exile\".<ref name=\"katie mitchell\">{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/alumni-news/katie-mitchell-wins-british-academy-award/ |title=Katie Mitchell wins British Academy Award |date=5 October 2017 |accessdate= 16 February 2020 |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford}}</ref><ref name=\"katie mitchell2\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2016/jan/14/british-theatre-queen-exile-katie-mitchell |title=Katie Mitchell, British theatre's queen in exile |last=Higgins |first=Charlotte |date=14 January 2016 |work=The Guardian |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Music====\nIn 1957, the [[organ (music)|organist]] and composer [[Bernard Rose (musician)|Bernard Rose]] OBE was appointed Magdalen's Informator Choristarum, choir master.<ref name=\"indp bernardrose\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary-bernard-rose-1312755.html |title=Obituary: Bernard Rose |date=3 December 1996 |last=Dunnett |first=Roderic |work=Independent}}</ref> Among his students were [[Harry Christophers]] CBE, a composer and an artistic director for the [[Handel and Haydn Society]] who was an [[Choral scholar|academical clerk]] and later honorary Fellow at Magdalen;<ref name=\"harrychristophers\">{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/news/harry-christophers-becomes-honorary-fellow/ |title=Harry Christophers becomes Honorary Fellow |date=8 May 2009 |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford}}</ref> and [[Dudley Moore]] CBE, comedic actor and jazz musician, who studied at Magdalen on an [[organ scholar]]ship.<ref name=\"indp bernardrose\" /><ref name=\"telegraph dudleymoore\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1389041/Dudley-Moore.html |title=Dudley Moore |date=28 March 2002 |work=The Telegraph}}</ref>\n\n[[Andrew Lloyd Webber|Andrew Lloyd Webber, Baron Lloyd-Webber]], composer of [[musicals]] including ''[[Evita (musical)|Evita]]'' and ''[[The Phantom of the Opera]]'', studied history at Magdalen for a term in 1965, before dropping out to pursue music at the [[Royal Academy of Music]].<ref>{{cite book |title=How to Analzye the Works of Andrew Lloyd Webber |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LISu9S6HyqgC&pg=PA13 |last=Marsico |first=Katie |year=2010 |pages=13\u201314 |publisher=ABDO|isbn = 9781616135331}}</ref> Andrew Lloyd Webber has received a number of awards for his work, including a lifetime achievement [[Tony Award]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thestage.co.uk/news/2018/andrew-lloyd-webber-receive-lifetime-achievement-prize-years-tony-awards/ |title=Andrew Lloyd Webber to receive lifetime achievement prize at this year's Tony Awards |work=The Stage |last=Hemey |first=Matthew |date=23 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Humanities===\n[[File:Hormuzd.Rassam.reclined.jpg|right|250px|thumb|Hormuzd Rassam in Mosul c. 1854.]]\n[[Hormuzd Rassam]], the native [[Assyriologist]], studied at Magdalen for 18 months between accompanying archaeologist Sir [[Austen Henry Layard]] on his first and second expeditions. When Layard retired from archaeology, the [[British Museum]] appointed Rassam to continue on his own. Rassam made several important discoveries: in 1853 at [[Nineveh]], Rassam discovered the clay tablets that contained the ''[[Epic of Gilgamesh]]''; in 1879 he discovered the [[Cyrus Cylinder]] in the ruins of [[Babylon]]; and in 1880-1881 he uncovered the city of [[Sippar]]. He was the first Middle Eastern archaeologist, but his contributions were dismissed by some of his contemporaries and by the end of his life, his name had been removed from plaques and visitor guides at the British Museum. Layard would describe him as \"one whose services have never been acknowledged\".<ref name=\"bbc Rassam\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-31941827 |title=The men who uncovered Assyria |last=Adamson |first=Daniel Silas |date=22 March 2015 |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe economist [[Michael Spence|A. Michael Spence]] attended Magdalen on a Rhodes Scholarship, and graduated with a BA in mathematics in 1967. In 2001, he shared the [[Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences]] for his work on [[Information flow (information theory)|information flows]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.nobelprize.org/prizes/economic-sciences/2001/spence/biographical/|title=A. Michael Spence|work=Les Prix Nobel|editor=Tore Fr\u00e4ngsmyr|publisher=Nobel Foundation, Nobel Media AB|accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref> He is an honorary fellow at Magdalen.<ref name=\"people at magd\">{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/people-at-magdalen/ |title=People at Magdalen |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nPhilosopher [[A. C. Grayling]] CBE read for his DPhil at Magdalen, completing his studies in 1981. In 2011, he founded the [[New College of the Humanities at Northeastern|New College of the Humanities]].<ref name=\"indp acgrayling\">{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/education/education-news/professor-a-c-grayling-whatever-happened-to-the-most-hated-man-in-academia-8894704.html |title=Professor A C Grayling: Whatever happened to the most hated man in academia? |last=Garner |first=Richard |date=21 October 2013 |work=Independent}}</ref> An [[analytic philosophy|analytic philosopher]], Grayling is known for his criticism of religion, including in his 2013 book ''[[The God Argument]]'', and his arguments for voting reform, as in his 2017 book ''Democracy and Its Crises''.\n\n[[Niall Ferguson]], a well-known historian, also studied at Magdalen.\n\n===Sciences===\n[[File:Peter Brian Medawar.jpg|thumb|Peter Medawar, Nobel laureate and organ transplant pioneer.]]\nMagdalen counts among its alumni several recipients of the [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine]]. Sir [[Howard Florey]] was an Australian pharmacologist who studied at Magdalen on a [[Rhodes Scholarship]], graduating in 1924. He shared the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1945 for the development of [[penicillin]].<ref name=\"florey\">{{cite web |title=Sir Howard Florey Biographical, from Nobel Lectures |publisher=Elsevier |url=https://www.nobelprize.org/prizes/medicine/1945/florey/biographical/ |year=1964 |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref> Sir [[Peter Medawar]] CBE read for a BA in zoology at Magdalen, receiving a first, and later for a DPhil, supervised by Florey. His research into tissue grafting and immune rejection led to the discover of [[acquired immune tolerance]] and became the basis of organ transplantation. For this work, he shared the 1960 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine.<ref name=\"medawar\">{{cite web |title=Sir Peter Medawar Biographical, from Nobel Lectures |publisher=Elsevier |url=https://www.nobelprize.org/prizes/medicine/1960/medawar/biographical/ |year=1964 |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nLike Florey before him, Australian neurophysiologist Sir [[John Eccles (neurophysiologist)|John Eccles]] also came to Magdalen on a Rhodes Scholarship, where he read for his [[DPhil]]. He was taught by an earlier neurophysiologist who received the Nobel in 1932, Sir [[Charles Scott Sherrington]], who held the [[Waynflete Professorship]] in Physiology at Magdalen. In 1963 Eccles received the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for his research into [[synapse]]s. Eccles was also known for his contributions to philosophy, writing on the [[mind-body problem]] and becoming an honorary member of the [[American Philosophical Society]].<ref name=\"eccles\">{{cite web |title=Sir John Eccles Biographical, from Nobel Lectures |publisher=Elsevier |url=https://www.nobelprize.org/prizes/medicine/1963/eccles/biographical/ |year=1972 |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref> \n\nSir [[Peter J. Ratcliffe]] held the [[Nuffield Professor of Clinical Medicine|Nuffield Professorship of Clinical Medicine]] between 2003 and 2006, and is still a supernumerary fellow at Magdalen.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/member-of-staff/peter-ratcliffe/ |title=Professor Sir Peter Ratcliffe |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref> He shared the 2019 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for his work on the oxygen sensing of cells.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nobelprize.org/prizes/medicine/2019/summary/ |title=The Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine 2019 |publisher=Nobel Media AB |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref> Other former Nuffield Professors of Clinical Medicine include Sir [[David Weatherall]], who founded the Weatherall Institute of Molecular Medicine in 1989,<ref name=\"weatherall obit\">{{cite journal |url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(19)30113-8/fulltext |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(19)30113-8 |title=David John Weatherall |last=Watts |first=Geoff |year=2019 |volume=393 |issue=10169 |page=314 |journal=The Lancet}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imm.ox.ac.uk/about |title=About us |publisher=MRC Weatherall Institute of Molecular Medicine |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref> and Sir [[John Bell (physician)|John Bell]] GBE, who is also an alumnus of the college.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.roche.com/about/governance/board_of_directors/board_of_directors-bell.htm |title=Prof. Sir John Irving Bell |publisher=F. Hoffmann-La Roche Ltd |accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref> The current holder of the chair is [[Richard Cornall]], who was appointed in 2019.<ref name=\"richard cornall\">{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/news/new-nuffield-professor-of-clinical-medicine/ |title=New Nuffield Professor of Clinical Medicine |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |accessdate=1 March 2020 |date=8 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nTwo Fellows of Magdalen have been awarded the [[Nobel Prize in Physics]]: [[Erwin Schr\u00f6dinger]] in 1933, while he was a Fellow;<ref name=\"magd shrodinger\">{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/discover-magdalen/history-of-college/famous-alumni/dr-erwin-schrodinger/ |title=Dr Erwin Schr\u00f6dinger |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref> and [[Anthony James Leggett]] KBE in 2003, who had been a Fellow from 1963 to 1967.<ref name=\"magd leggett\">{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/discover-magdalen/history-of-college/famous-alumni/professor-anthony-leggett/ |title=Professor Anthony Leggett |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref> \n\nDue to Magdalen's close relationship with Oxford's Botanic Garden and as the home of the [[Sherardian Professor of Botany|Sherardian Chair of Botany]], Magdalen has been associated with many accomplished botanists. Historic Sherardian Professors include [[John Sibthorp]], in whose name the [[Sibthorpian Professor of Plant Sciences|Sibthorpian Professorship of Rural Economy]], later known as the Sibthorpian Professorship of Plant Sciences, was founded; and [[Charles Daubeny]], who also held the [[Aldrichian Chairs|Aldrichian Chair of Chemistry]] and founded the Daubeny laboratory.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://plants.jstor.org/stable/10.5555/al.ap.person.bm000153994 |title=Sibthorp, John (1758-1796) |work=Global Plants}}</ref><ref name=\"historyOfDaubenyLab\" /> The Sherardian Chair has been held since 2009 by [[Liam Dolan]], who studies the emergence of land plants.<ref name=\"dolan rs\">{{cite web |url=https://royalsociety.org/people/liam-dolan-11347/ |title=Liam Dolan |publisher=The Royal Society - Fellows Directory |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"dolan\">{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/member-of-staff/liam-dolan/ |title=Professor Liam Dolan |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nLikewise, many distinguished scientists have held Waynflete Professorships at Magdalen. These include the mathematician [[J. H. C. Whitehead]], who held the Waynflete Professorship of Pure Mathematics between 1947 and 1960. During this time, he was also the president of the [[London Mathematical Society]], which established the [[Whitehead Prize|Whitehead]] and [[Senior Whitehead Prize|Senior Whitehead]] prizes in his honour. He is remembered for his fundamental contributions to topology.<ref name=\"whitehead\">{{cite journal |journal=Nature |year=1960 |title=Prof. J. H. C. Whitehead, F.R.S. (obituary) |last=James |first=I. N. |volume=186 |issue=932 |doi=10.1038/186932a0 }}</ref><ref name=\"lms whitehead prizes\">{{cite web |url=https://www.lms.ac.uk/prizes/lms-prize-regulations |title=LMS prizes - details and regulations |publisher=London Mathematical Society |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref> The chair was held from 1984 until he retired in 2006 by [[Daniel Quillen]], who received the [[Fields Medal]] for his work in [[algebraic K-theory]].<ref name=\"indp quillen\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2011/jun/23/daniel-quillen-obituary |title=Daniel Quillen obituary |first=Graeme |last=Segal |date=23 June 2011 |work=The Independent |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref> It is currently held by [[Ben Green (mathematician)|Ben Green]].<ref name=\"bengreen\">{{cite web |url=https://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/member-of-staff/ben-green/ |title=Professor Ben Green |publisher=Magdalen College, Oxford |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery heights=\"200px\" widths=\"250px\">\nFile:Magdalen College - statues in the cloister.jpg|Two of the Cloister's hieroglyphics, the lion and the pelican, in front of the Senior Common Room.\nFile:Magdalen College cloister.jpg|Panorama across the Cloister. On the left is the Founder's Tower. \nFile:Magdalen College, view from the cloister.jpg|View of Founder's Tower from the Cloister.\nFile:Magdalen College, Oxford-15320233952.jpg|View of Founder's Tower from St. John's Quad. \nFile:Magdalen College, Oxford.jpg|The Cloister\nFile:Oxford - panoramio (38).jpg|View of the Great Tower from the Daubeny Laboratory, across [[High Street, Oxford|the High]]. \nFile:Magdalen Cloisters and New Buildings.jpg|Position of the New Building and lawns behind the Cloister\nFile:Oxford magdalen college lodgings.jpg|View of the Cloister and Great Tower from the New Building\nFile:Magdalen_College,_view_of_cloisters_from_Addison's_Walk,_Oct_2016.jpg|The Great Tower and cloister, viewed from Addison's Walk\nFile:Oxford magdalen college cour.jpg|St. John's Quad, showing (left to right) the gate to St. Swithun's quad, the Grammar Hall, and the President's Lodgings.\nFile:UK-2014-Oxford-Magdalen College 02.jpg|Gateway to St. Swithun's Quad (St. Swithun's Tower). \nFile:Magdalen College Oxford Old Grammar Hall.jpg|The old Grammar Hall\nFile:UK-2014-Oxford-Magdalen College 01.jpg|The President's Lodgings and Pride of India tree.\nFile:Magdalen College Muniment Tower.JPG|Muniment Tower.\nFile:Magdalen College - view on the tower and the chapel.jpg| St. John's Quad, showing (left to right) the President's Lodgings, Founder's Tower, Muniment Tower, the chapel, and the Great Tower behind.  \nFile:Ancient Door, Magdalen College, Oxford by Henry Fox Talbot.jpg|''Ancient Door, Magdalen College, Oxford'' by [[Henry Fox Talbot]], circa 1843, showing the western door to the chapel beneath the window depicting the Last Judgment.\nFile:Oxford magdalen college chapelle int.JPG|Interior of the chapel.\nFile:Arthur Foxton Ferguson - Academic Clerkship Magdalen College Oxford ca. 1898 (fourth from left in back row).jpg|The choir of Magdalen College ca. 1898\nFile:Oxford MagdalenCollege Gate&Ranges.jpg|Gate between the High and St. John's Quad. The Porter's Lodge is on the right.\nFile:Longwall Street, Oxford, looking south.jpg|Boundary wall along Longwall Street. \nFile:Magdalen college oxford waynflete building.jpg|The Waynflete Building, on the east side of Magdalen Bridge.\nFile:Y sculpture.jpg|''Y'' by Mark Wallinger in Bat Willow Meadow</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Magdalen College, Oxford}}\n* [http://www.magd.ox.ac.uk/ Official site]\n* [http://www.chem.ox.ac.uk/oxfordtour/magdalencollege/ Virtual Tour of Magdalen College]\n* [http://www.magdalencollegechoir.com Website of Magdalen College Choir]\n* [http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Gazetteer/Places/Europe/Great_Britain/England/Oxfordshire/Oxford/_Texts/FLEOXF/1*.html Fletcher's History of Oxford: Magdalen College]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060820005730/http://www.ofchoristers.net/Chapters/OxfordMagdelen.htm A history of the choristers of Magdalen Chapel, Oxford]\n* [http://magdmcr.co.uk/ Website of Magdalen Middle Common Room]\n\n{{University of Oxford}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1458 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in the 15th century]]\n[[Category:Colleges of the University of Oxford]]\n[[Category:Grade I listed buildings in Oxford]]\n[[Category:Grade I listed educational buildings]]\n[[Category:Magdalen College, Oxford|*]]\n[[Category:Organisations based in Oxford with royal patronage]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures of the University of Oxford]]\n[[Category:Mary Magdalene]]\n", "name_user": "Jamesmcmahon0", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's, womens \u2192 women's, 1470-1480 \u2192 1470\u20131480 (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magdalen_College,_Oxford"}
